{"title_page": "List of NCAA Division I men's soccer programs", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThis is a '''list of men's [[college soccer]] programs in the [[United States]]''', that play in [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[NCAA Division I|Division I]]. As of the most recent [[2019 NCAA Division I men's soccer season]], 206 schools in the United States sponsor Division I varsity men's soccer; 204 of these schools are full Division I members, and two (California Baptist and Merrimack) have begun a transition from [[NCAA Division II]] to Division I. This list reflects each team's conference affiliation as of the upcoming 2020 season.<ref name=\"Sponsorship\">{{cite web|title=NCAA Sports Sponsorship: Division I Men's Soccer|url=http://web1.ncaa.org/onlineDir/exec/sponsorship|work=NCAA.otg|publisher=National Collegiate Athletic Association|accessdate=June 30, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101230214415/http://web1.ncaa.org/onlineDir/exec/sponsorship|archive-date=December 30, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSeveral schools will change conferences during the 2019\u201320 offseason; all such changes officially take effect on July 1, 2020. Three schools will officially begin transitions from Division I on that date. One school, [[Valparaiso Crusaders men's soccer|Valparaiso]], dropped men's soccer after the 2019 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nwitimes.com/sports/college/valparaiso-university/valparaiso-to-drop-men-s-soccer-men-s-tennis/article_2d77497a-b5a2-500b-9b63-7d7a88d83039.html |title=Valparaiso to drop men's soccer, men's tennis |publisher=The Times/ Lee Enterprises, Inc. |date=November 20, 2019 |accessdate=2 December 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Current Division I schools==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"  style=\" width:100%; font:90%\"\n|-\n! Institution !! Location !! State !! Type !! Nickname !! Conference !! Primary conference\n|-\n|-\n| {{sort|Albany|[[University at Albany, SUNY]]}} <br>(Albany)\