]{{efn|group=c|California Baptist began a transition from Division II to Division I with the 2018\u201319 school year. CBU becomes a full D-I member with the 2022\u201323 school year.}}\n| [[Riverside, California|Riverside]]\n| [[California]]\n| Private/Baptist\n| [[California Baptist Lancers|Lancers]]\n| colspan=2| [[Western Athletic Conference]]\n|-\n| [[Dixie State University]]{{efn|group=c|Dixie State begins a transition from Division II to Division I with the 2020\u201321 school year, and is scheduled to become a full D-I member with the 2024\u201325 school year.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://dixiestateathletics.com/news/2019/1/11/general-blazing-a-new-trail-dixie-state-accepts-invitation-to-join-western-athletic-conference.aspx |title=Blazing a New Trail: Dixie State Accepts Invitation to Join Western Athletic Conference |publisher=Dixie State Trailblazers |date=January 11, 2019 |accessdate=January 25, 2019}}</ref>}}\n| {{sort|Saint George|[[St. George, Utah|St. George]]}}\n| [[Utah]]\n| State\n| [[Dixie State Trailblazers men's soccer|Trailblazers]]\n| colspan=2 | [[Western Athletic Conference]]\n|-\n| [[Grand Canyon University]]\n| [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]]\n| [[Arizona]]\n| Private/Christian\n| [[Grand Canyon Antelopes men's soccer|Antelopes]]\n| colspan=2| [[Western Athletic Conference]]\n|-\n| [[Houston Baptist University]]\n| [[Houston]]\n| [[Texas]]\n| Private/Baptist\n| [[Houston Baptist Huskies men's soccer|Huskies]]\n| [[Western Athletic Conference]]\n| [[Southland Conference]]\n|-\n| {{sort|Incarnate|[[University of the Incarnate Word]]}} \n| [[San Antonio]] & [[Alamo Heights, Texas|Alamo Heights]]\n| [[Texas]]\n| Private/Catholic\n| [[Incarnate Word Cardinals men's soccer|Cardinals]]\n| [[Western Athletic Conference]]\n| [[Southland Conference]]\n|-\n| [[San Jose State University]]\n| [[San Jose, California|San Jose]]\n| [[California]]\n| State\n| [[San Jose State Spartans men's soccer|Spartans]]\n| [[Western Athletic Conference]]\n| [[Mountain West Conference]]\n|-\n| [[Seattle University]]\n| [[Seattle]]\n| [[Washington (state)|Washington]]\n| Private/Catholic\n| [[Seattle Redhawks men's soccer|Redhawks]]\n| colspan=2| [[Western Athletic Conference]]\n|-\n| {{sort|UNLV|[[University of Nevada, Las Vegas]]}}<br>(UNLV)\n| [[Paradise, Nevada|Paradise]]\n| [[Nevada]]\n| State\n| [[UNLV Rebels men's soccer|Rebels]]\n| [[Western Athletic Conference]]\n| [[Mountain West Conference]]\n|-\n| [[Utah Valley University]]\n| [[Orem, Utah|Orem]]\n| [[Utah]]\n| State\n| [[Utah Valley Wolverines men's soccer|Wolverines]]\n| colspan=2| [[Western Athletic Conference]]\n|-\n| {{sort|UTRGV|[[University of Texas Rio Grande Valley]]}}<br>(UTRGV)\n| [[Edinburg, Texas|Edinburg]] & [[Rio Grande Valley]]\n| [[Texas]]\n| State\n| [[Texas\u2013Rio Grande Valley Vaqueros men's soccer|Vaqueros]]\n| colspan=2| [[Western Athletic Conference]]\n\n|}\n\n;Notes\n{{notelist|group=c}}\n\n==Scheduled additions==\nOne school is currently scheduled to add men's soccer to its athletic programs. In addition to the three men's soccer schools that will move their athletic programs from Division II to Division I in July 2020, one school that currently sponsors men's soccer in [[NCAA Division III|Division III]] has announced a transition to Division I in the near future.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"  style=\"width:90%; font:90%\"\n|-\n! Institution !! Location !! State !! Type !! Nickname !! Conference !! Primary Conference !! Starting\n|-\n| [[Chicago State University]] \n| [[Chicago]] \n| [[Illinois]] \n| Public  \n| [[Chicago State Cougars|Cougars]] \n| colspan=2| [[Western Athletic Conference]] \n| \u2013?\u2013 \u2021 <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.csu.edu/news/2012archive/westernathleticconference.htm | title=Chicago State University Joins Western Athletic Conference |publisher=Chicago State University |date=December 5, 2012 |accessdate=August 27, 2015 }}</ref>\n|}\n* \u2021 = Chicago State was expected to add men's soccer by 2014. The school eventually budgeted the sport for the 2016\u201317 school year. However, the State of Illinois' continuing budgetary problems and the school's own critical financial problems have repeatedly set this back. With the school's current financial situation and the needs of the athletic program, in April 2016, the University Budget Committee recommended that the Athletic Department \"... study the benefits of being Division 1 or another division.\"  <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.csu.edu/financialaffairs/ubc/documents/minutes_Apr26_2016.pdf |title=University Budget Committee minutes |publisher=Chicago State University |date=April 26, 2016 |accessdate=September 2, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180514144327/https://www.csu.edu/financialaffairs/ubc/documents/minutes_Apr26_2016.pdf |archive-date=May 14, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|+ List of NCAA Division II/III Institutions scheduled for Upward Transition\n!scope=\"col\"| School\n!scope=\"col\"| Location\n!scope=\"col\"| State\n!scope=\"col\"| Type\n!scope=\"col\"| Team \n!scope=\"col\"| Future Conference\n!scope=\"col\"| Making Transition\n!scope=\"col\"| Starting\n!scope=\"col\"| Full Membership\n|-\n|scope=row| [[University of St. Thomas (Minnesota)|University of St. Thomas]]\n| [[St. Thomas (Minnesota) Tommies|Tommies]] || [[Saint Paul, Minnesota|St. Paul]] || [[Minnesota]] || Private/Catholic || [[Summit League]] || From DIII to DI || 2021\u201322 || July 2025\u2013Pending approval of NCAA to move directly from [[NCAA Division III|Division III]] to Division I.  <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/university-of-st-thomas-wants-to-go-division-i-gets-invitation-to-summit-league/562174952/|title=St. Thomas announces intentions to go Division I after getting removed from MIAC|publisher=Star Tribune |date= October 4, 2019|access-date=24 October 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[College soccer]]\n* [[List of NCAA Division 