{"title_page": "Red Fields", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Red Field}}\n{{short description|2019 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Red Fields\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Keren Yedaya]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = \n| starring       = [[Neta Elkayam]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{film date|2019|7|31|[[Jerusalem Film Festival|Jerusalem FF]]|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 90 minutes\n| country        = Israel\n| language       = Hebrew\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Red Fields''''' is a 2019 Israeli [[drama film]] directed by [[Keren Yedaya]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://intl.filmfund.org.il/articles/?id=32 |title=Red Fields dir. by Keren Yedaya in post production |work= Israeli Film Council |accessdate=19 August 2019}}</ref> It was screened in the Contemporary World Cinema section at the [[2019 Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/toronto-film-festival-the-aeronauts-mosul-seberg-kristen-stewart-ore-to-festival-slate-1202667020/ |title=Toronto Adds ''The Aeronauts,'' ''Mosul,'' ''Seberg,'' & More To Festival Slate |work=Deadline |accessdate=16 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Neta Elkayam]] as Mamy\n* [[Ami Abu]] as Nissim\n* [[Riki Gal]] as Batia\n* [[Yuval Banai]] as Yaki \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|10679766|Red Fields}}\n\n{{Keren Yedaya}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Red Fields}}\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:2019 drama films]]\n[[Category:Israeli films]]\n[[Category:Israeli drama films]]\n[[Category:Hebrew-language films]]\n{{Israel-film-stub}}\n{{2010s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Red Field}}\n{{short description|2019 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Red Fields\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Keren Yedaya]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = \n| starring       = [[Neta Elkayam]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{film date|2019|7|31|[[Jerusalem Film Festival|Jerusalem FF]]|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 90 minutes\n| country        = Israel\n| language       = Hebrew\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Red Fields''''' is a 2019 Israeli [[drama film]] directed by [[Keren Yedaya]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://intl.filmfund.org.il/articles/?id=32 |title=Red Fields dir. by Keren Yedaya in post production |work= Israeli Film Council |accessdate=19 August 2019}}</ref> It was screened in the Contemporary World Cinema section at the [[2019 Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/toronto-film-festival-the-aeronauts-mosul-seberg-kristen-stewart-ore-to-festival-slate-1202667020/ |title=Toronto Adds ''The Aeronauts,'' ''Mosul,'' ''Seberg,'' & More To Festival Slate |work=Deadline |accessdate=16 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Neta Elkayam]] as Mamy\n* [[Ami Abu]] as Nissim\n* [[Riki Gal]] as Batia\n* [[Yuval Banai]] as Yaki \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|10679766|Red Fields}}\n\n{{Keren Yedaya}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Red Fields}}\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:2019 drama films]]\n[[Category:Israeli films]]\n[[Category:Israeli drama films]]\n[[Category:Hebrew-language films]]\n{{Israel-film-stub}}\n{{2010s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Fields"}
{"title_page": "Brine rejection", "text_new": "{{short description|Process by which salts are expelled from freezing water}}\n'''Brine rejection''' is a process that occurs when salty water freezes. The salts do not fit in the crystal structure of water [[ice]], so the salt is expelled.\n\nSince the oceans are salty, this process is important in nature. Salt rejected by the forming [[sea ice]] drains into the surrounding [[seawater]], creating saltier, denser [[brine]]. The denser brine sinks, influencing [[ocean circulation]].\n\n==Formation==\n[[File:Ice Thickness vs. Average Salinity.gif|thumb|Average salinity of sea ice as a function of ice thickness for cold sea ice sampled during the growth season. The standard error of the estimate is 1.5\u2030 for thin ice and 0.6\u2030 for thick ice.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal|last=Cox|first=G. F. N.|last2=Weeks|first2=W. F.|date=1974-01-01|title=Salinity Variations in Sea Ice|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/journal-of-glaciology/article/salinity-variations-in-sea-ice/0976B42E5B21CAE25BE26A0DD811513F/core-reader|journal=Journal of Glaciology|volume=13|issue=67|pages=109\u2013120|doi=10.1017/S0022143000023418|issn=0022-1430|bibcode=1974JGlac..13..109C}}</ref>]]\nAs water reaches the temperature where it begins to crystallize and form ice, salt ions are rejected from the lattices within the ice and either forced out into the surrounding water, or trapped among the ice crystals in pockets called brine cells. Generally, sea ice has a salinity ranging from 0 psu at the surface to 4 psu at the base.<ref name=\":1\"/> The faster that this [[freezing]] process occurs, the more brine cells are left in the ice. Once the ice reaches a critical thickness, roughly 15&nbsp;cm, the concentration of salt [[ions]] in the liquid around the ice begins to increase, as leftover brine is rejected from the cells.<ref name=\":1\"/> This increase is associated with the appearance of strong convective plumes, which flow from channels and within the ice and carry a significant salt flux. The brine that drains from the newly formed ice is replaced by a weak flow of relatively fresh water, from the liquid region below it. The new water partially freezes within the pores of the ice, increasing the solidity of the ice.\n\nAs sea ice ages and thickens, the initial salinity of the ice decreases due to the rejection of brine over time [Fig. 2].<ref name=\":1\"/> While the sea ice ages, [[desalinization]] occurs to such a degree that some multiyear ice has a [[salinity]] of less than 1 [[Practical salinity unit|PSU]].<ref name=\"descriptive_physical\">Talley L.D., Pickard G.L., Emery W.J., Swift J.H., 2011. Descriptive Physical Oceanography: An Introduction (Sixth Edition), Elsevier, Boston, 560 pp.</ref> This occurs in three different ways:\n*'''solute diffusion''' - this depends on the fact that brine inclusions trapped in ice will begin to migrate toward the warmer end of the ice block. The ice block is warmest at the water-ice interface, thus pushing the brine out into the water surrounding the ice.<ref name=salt_rejection>{{cite journal | last1 = Lake | first1 = R.A. | last2 = Lewis | first2 = E.L. | year = 1970 | title = Salt rejection by sea ice during growth | url = | journal = J. Geophys. Res. | volume = 75 | issue = | pages = 583\u2013597 }}</ref>\n*'''[[gravity]] drainage''' - Gravity drainage involves the movement of brine due to differences in density between brine in the interior of the ice and brine in the seawater outside of the ice, which occurs due to the development of a buoyancy driven convection system.<ref name=\"natural_convection\">Wettlaufer J.S., Worster M.G., Huppert H.E. (1997). Natural convection during solidification of an alloy from above with application to evolution of sea ice. J. Fluid. Mech. 344 291-316.</ref>\n*'''expulsion''' - the migration of brine due to cracking produced by thermal expansion of the ice, or pressure caused by the increased volume of the newly formed ice.<ref name=salt_rejection/>\n\n==Role in deep water formation and the thermohaline circulation==\n[[File:Climatology 81-10 min-max conc tmb.png|thumb|Arctic and Antarctic sea ice concentration climatology from 1981-2010, at the approximate seasonal maximum and minimum levels based on passive microwave satellite data.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nsidc.org/cryosphere/seaice/characteristics/difference.html|title=Arctic vs. Antarctic {{!}} National Snow and Ice Data Center|website=nsidc.org|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>]]\n\nBrine rejection occurs in the sea [[ice pack]]s around at the north and south poles of the earth [Fig. 3]{{clarify|date=October 2017}}. The [[Arctic Ocean]] has historically ranged from roughly 14-16 million square kilometers in late winter to roughly 7 million square kilometers each September.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nsidc.org/cryosphere/seaice/index.html|title=All About Sea Ice {{!}} National Snow and Ice Data Center|website=nsidc.org|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref> The annual increase of ice plays a major role in the movement of ocean circulation and deep water formation. The density of the water below the newly formed ice increases due to the brine rejection. Saltier water can also become colder without freezing.\n\nThe dense waters that form in the Arctic are called [[North Atlantic Deep Water]]s (NADW), while the [[Antarctic Bottom Water]] (AABW) forms in the southern hemisphere. These two areas of brine rejection play an important role in the [[thermohaline circulation]] of all of earth's oceans.\n\n==Brinicles==\nAs sea ice freezes, it rejects increasingly salty water, which drains through narrow brine channels that thread through the ice. The brine flowing through the brine channels and out of the bottom of the ice is very cold and salty, so it sinks in the warmer, fresher seawater under the ice, forming a [[plume (fluid dynamics)|plume]]. The plume is colder than the freezing point of sea water under the ice, so the seawater can freeze where it touches the plume. Ice freezing around the edges of the plume gradually builds a hollow icicle-like tube, called a [[brinicle]]. These frozen [[stalactite]]-like forms are fragile during early stages, but if brine drainage ceases, they may freeze solid. In calm waters, brinicles can reach the sea floor, freezing it fairly abruptly.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/nature/15835017|date=2011-11-23|title='Brinicle' ice finger of death filmed in Antarctic|first=Ella|last=Davies|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123182443/http://www.bbc.co.uk/nature/15835017|archive-date=2011-11-23}}</ref>\n\n==Climate change==\nThe deep ocean basins are [[stratified flows|stably stratified]], so mixing of surface waters with the deep ocean waters occurs only very slowly. The dissolved [[carbon dioxide|CO<sub>2</sub>]] of the surface waters of the ocean is roughly in equilibrium with the [[partial pressure]] of CO<sub>2</sub> in the atmosphere. As atmospheric CO<sub>2</sub> levels are rising, the [[ocean acidification|oceans are absorbing]] some CO<sub>2</sub> from the atmosphere. When surface waters sink, they carry considerable amounts of CO<sub>2</sub> into the deep oceans, away from the atmosphere. Because these waters are able to contain a large amount of CO<sub>2</sub>, they have helped slow the rise in [[Carbon dioxide in Earth's atmosphere|atmospheric CO<sub>2</sub> concentrations]], thus slowing some aspects of [[climate change]].\n\nClimate change could have different effects on ice melt and brine rejection. Previous studies have suggested that as [[ice cover]] thins, it will become a weaker insulator, resulting in larger ice production during the autumn and winter.<ref name=\":0\">Holland M.M., [[Cecilia Bitz|Bitz C.]], Tremblay B. (2006), Future abrupt reductions in the summer Arctic sea ice. Geophys. Res. Letters. 33, 1-5.</ref> The consequent increase in winter brine rejection will drive ocean ventilation, and strengthen the inflow of warm [[Atlantic]] waters. Studies of the last [[glacial maximum]] (LGM) have indicated that a drastic reduction in the production of sea ice and thus reduction of brine rejection, would result in the weakening of the stratification in the global deep oceans and in CO<sub>2</sub> release into the shallow oceans and the atmosphere, triggering global deglaciation.<ref name=\"life_hung\">{{cite journal | last1 = Thatje | first1 = S. | last2 = Hillenbrand | first2 = C.D. | last3 = Mackensen | first3 = A. | last4 = Larter | first4 = R. | year = 2008 | title = Life hung by a thread: endurance of Antarctic fauna in glacial periods | url = | journal = Ecology | volume = 89 | issue = 3| pages = 682\u2013692 | pmid = 18459332 }}</ref>\n\n==Life in channels and surrounding waters==\nLife in sea ice is energetically demanding, and sets limits at any hierarchical organizational, and organismic level, ranging from [[molecules]] to everything that an organism does.{{clarify|date=October 2017}}<ref name=\"life_hung\"/> Despite this fact, the brine-containing interstices and pockets found in sea ice host a variety of organisms, including [[bacteria]], [[autotrophic]] and heterotrophic [[protists]], [[microalgae]], and [[metazoa]].<ref>Giannelli V., Thomas D. N., Haas C., Kattner G., Kennedy H., Dieckmann G.S. (2001), Behaviour of dissolved organic matter and inorganic nutrients during experimental sea-ice formation, Ann. Glaciology. 33, 317-321.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n*http://www.bbc.com/earth/story/20161219-brinicle-finger-of-death Brinicle Video by BBC\n\n[[Category:Chemical oceanography]]\n[[Category:Earth phenomena]]\n[[Category:Sea ice]]\n[[Category:Water]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Process by which salts are expelled from freezing water}}\n'''Brine rejection''' is a process that occurs when salty water freezes. The salts do not fit in the crystal structure of water [[ice]], so the salt is expelled.\n\nSince the oceans are salty, this process is important in nature. Salt rejected by the forming [[sea ice]] drains into the surrounding [[seawater]], creating saltier, denser [[brine]]. The denser brine sinks, influencing [[ocean circulation]].\n\n==Formation==\n[[File:Ice Thickness vs. Average Salinity.gif|thumb|Average salinity of sea ice as a function of ice thickness for cold sea ice sampled during the growth season. The standard error of the estimate is 1.5\u2030 for thin ice and 0.6\u2030 for thick ice.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal|last=Cox|first=G. F. N.|last2=Weeks|first2=W. F.|date=1974-01-01|title=Salinity Variations in Sea Ice|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/journal-of-glaciology/article/salinity-variations-in-sea-ice/0976B42E5B21CAE25BE26A0DD811513F/core-reader|journal=Journal of Glaciology|volume=13|issue=67|pages=109\u2013120|doi=10.1017/S0022143000023418|issn=0022-1430|bibcode=1974JGlac..13..109C}}</ref>]]\nAs water reaches the temperature where it begins to crystallize and form ice, salt ions are rejected from the lattices within the ice and either forced out into the surrounding water, or trapped among the ice crystals in pockets called brine cells. Generally, sea ice has a salinity ranging from 0 psu at the surface to 4 psu at the base.<ref name=\":1\"/> The faster that this [[freezing]] process occurs, the more brine cells are left in the ice. Once the ice reaches a critical thickness, roughly 15&nbsp;cm, the concentration of salt [[ions]] in the liquid around the ice begins to increase, as leftover brine is rejected from the cells.<ref name=\":1\"/> This increase is associated with the appearance of strong convective plumes, which flow from channels and within the ice and carry a significant salt flux. The brine that drains from the newly formed ice is replaced by a weak flow of relatively fresh water, from the liquid region below it. The new water partially freezes within the pores of the ice, increasing the solidity of the ice.\n\nAs sea ice ages and thickens, the initial salinity of the ice decreases due to the rejection of brine over time [Fig. 2].<ref name=\":1\"/> While the sea ice ages, [[desalinization]] occurs to such a degree that some multiyear ice has a [[salinity]] of less than 1 [[Practical salinity unit|PSU]].<ref name=\"descriptive_physical\">Talley L.D., Pickard G.L., Emery W.J., Swift J.H., 2011. Descriptive Physical Oceanography: An Introduction (Sixth Edition), Elsevier, Boston, 560 pp.</ref> This occurs in three different ways:\n*'''solute diffusion''' - this depends on the fact that brine inclusions trapped in ice will begin to migrate toward the warmer end of the ice block. The ice block is warmest at the water-ice interface, thus pushing the brine out into the water surrounding the ice.<ref name=salt_rejection>Lake R.A., Lewis E.L. (1970), Salt rejection by sea ice during growth. J. Geophys. Res. 75, 583-597.</ref>\n*'''[[gravity]] drainage''' - Gravity drainage involves the movement of brine due to differences in density between brine in the interior of the ice and brine in the seawater outside of the ice, which occurs due to the development of a buoyancy driven convection system.<ref name=\"natural_convection\">Wettlaufer J.S., Worster M.G., Huppert H.E. (1997). Natural convection during solidification of an alloy from above with application to evolution of sea ice. J. Fluid. Mech. 344 291-316.</ref>\n*'''expulsion''' - the migration of brine due to cracking produced by thermal expansion of the ice, or pressure caused by the increased volume of the newly formed ice.<ref name=salt_rejection/>\n\n==Role in deep water formation and the thermohaline circulation==\n[[File:Climatology 81-10 min-max conc tmb.png|thumb|Arctic and Antarctic sea ice concentration climatology from 1981-2010, at the approximate seasonal maximum and minimum levels based on passive microwave satellite data.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nsidc.org/cryosphere/seaice/characteristics/difference.html|title=Arctic vs. Antarctic {{!}} National Snow and Ice Data Center|website=nsidc.org|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref>]]\n\nBrine rejection occurs in the sea [[ice pack]]s around at the north and south poles of the earth [Fig. 3]{{clarify|date=October 2017}}. The [[Arctic Ocean]] has historically ranged from roughly 14-16 million square kilometers in late winter to roughly 7 million square kilometers each September.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nsidc.org/cryosphere/seaice/index.html|title=All About Sea Ice {{!}} National Snow and Ice Data Center|website=nsidc.org|access-date=2017-04-20}}</ref> The annual increase of ice plays a major role in the movement of ocean circulation and deep water formation. The density of the water below the newly formed ice increases due to the brine rejection. Saltier water can also become colder without freezing.\n\nThe dense waters that form in the Arctic are called [[North Atlantic Deep Water]]s (NADW), while the [[Antarctic Bottom Water]] (AABW) forms in the southern hemisphere. These two areas of brine rejection play an important role in the [[thermohaline circulation]] of all of earth's oceans.\n\n==Brinicles==\nAs sea ice freezes, it rejects increasingly salty water, which drains through narrow brine channels that thread through the ice. The brine flowing through the brine channels and out of the bottom of the ice is very cold and salty, so it sinks in the warmer, fresher seawater under the ice, forming a [[plume (fluid dynamics)|plume]]. The plume is colder than the freezing point of sea water under the ice, so the seawater can freeze where it touches the plume. Ice freezing around the edges of the plume gradually builds a hollow icicle-like tube, called a [[brinicle]]. These frozen [[stalactite]]-like forms are fragile during early stages, but if brine drainage ceases, they may freeze solid. In calm waters, brinicles can reach the sea floor, freezing it fairly abruptly.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/nature/15835017|date=2011-11-23|title='Brinicle' ice finger of death filmed in Antarctic|first=Ella|last=Davies|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123182443/http://www.bbc.co.uk/nature/15835017|archive-date=2011-11-23}}</ref>\n\n==Climate change==\nThe deep ocean basins are [[stratified flows|stably stratified]], so mixing of surface waters with the deep ocean waters occurs only very slowly. The dissolved [[carbon dioxide|CO<sub>2</sub>]] of the surface waters of the ocean is roughly in equilibrium with the [[partial pressure]] of CO<sub>2</sub> in the atmosphere. As atmospheric CO<sub>2</sub> levels are rising, the [[ocean acidification|oceans are absorbing]] some CO<sub>2</sub> from the atmosphere. When surface waters sink, they carry considerable amounts of CO<sub>2</sub> into the deep oceans, away from the atmosphere. Because these waters are able to contain a large amount of CO<sub>2</sub>, they have helped slow the rise in [[Carbon dioxide in Earth's atmosphere|atmospheric CO<sub>2</sub> concentrations]], thus slowing some aspects of [[climate change]].\n\nClimate change could have different effects on ice melt and brine rejection. Previous studies have suggested that as [[ice cover]] thins, it will become a weaker insulator, resulting in larger ice production during the autumn and winter.<ref name=\":0\">Holland M.M., [[Cecilia Bitz|Bitz C.]], Tremblay B. (2006), Future abrupt reductions in the summer Arctic sea ice. Geophys. Res. Letters. 33, 1-5.</ref> The consequent increase in winter brine rejection will drive ocean ventilation, and strengthen the inflow of warm [[Atlantic]] waters. Studies of the last [[glacial maximum]] (LGM) have indicated that a drastic reduction in the production of sea ice and thus reduction of brine rejection, would result in the weakening of the stratification in the global deep oceans and in CO<sub>2</sub> release into the shallow oceans and the atmosphere, triggering global deglaciation.<ref name=\"life_hung\">Thatje S., Hillenbrand C.D., Mackensen A., Larter R. (2008) Life hung by a thread: endurance of Antarctic fauna in glacial periods. Ecology. Mar;89(3) 682-692. {{PMID|18459332}}</ref>\n\n==Life in channels and surrounding waters==\nLife in sea ice is energetically demanding, and sets limits at any hierarchical organizational, and organismic level, ranging from [[molecules]] to everything that an organism does.{{clarify|date=October 2017}}<ref name=\"life_hung\"/> Despite this fact, the brine-containing interstices and pockets found in sea ice host a variety of organisms, including [[bacteria]], [[autotrophic]] and heterotrophic [[protists]], [[microalgae]], and [[metazoa]].<ref>Giannelli V., Thomas D. N., Haas C., Kattner G., Kennedy H., Dieckmann G.S. (2001), Behaviour of dissolved organic matter and inorganic nutrients during experimental sea-ice formation, Ann. Glaciology. 33, 317-321.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n*http://www.bbc.com/earth/story/20161219-brinicle-finger-of-death Brinicle Video by BBC\n\n[[Category:Chemical oceanography]]\n[[Category:Earth phenomena]]\n[[Category:Sea ice]]\n[[Category:Water]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:, templated 1 journal cites", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brine_rejection"}
{"title_page": "Julio Iglesias", "text_new": "{{about|the singer Julio Iglesias|his father|Julio Iglesias Sr.|his son|Julio Iglesias Jr.|other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Spanish name|Iglesias|de la Cueva}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                = Julio Iglesias\n| image               = Julio Iglesias09.jpg\n| caption             =\n| image_size          =\n| birth_name          = Julio Jos\u00e9 Iglesias de la Cueva\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1943|9|23}}\n| birth_place         = [[Madrid]], Spain\n| years_active        = 1968\u2013present\n| website             = [http://www.julioiglesias.com/ www.julioiglesias.com]\n| spouse             = {{plainlist|\n* {{marriage|[[Isabel Preysler]]|1971|1979|end=divorced}}\n* {{marriage|Miranda Rijnsburger|2010}}\n}}\n| children           = 9, including [[Chabeli Iglesias]], [[Julio Iglesias Jr.]], [[Enrique Iglesias]], and Javier Iglesias Santos <ref>https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/10/europe/julio-iglesias-paternity-claim-intl/index.html</ref>\n| residence          = [[Marbella]] (M\u00e1laga), [[Andalusia]], [[Spain]]\n| module = {{Infobox musical artist | embed = yes\n| background          = solo_singer\n| genre               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Latin music|Latin]]\n* [[Latin pop]]\n* [[dance-pop]]\n* [[Adult contemporary music|adult contemporary]]\n}}\n| label               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n* [[Sony Music|Sony]]\n}}\n}}\n| module2 = {{Infobox football biography | embed = yes | header-color = #F0E68C\n| nocat_wdimage = yes\n| position = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| years1 = 1960\u20131964\n| clubs1 = [[Real Madrid Castilla]]\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Julio Jos\u00e9 Iglesias de la Cueva''' ({{IPA-es|\u02c8xuljo i\u02c8\u0263lesjas}}; born 23 September 1943) is a Spanish singer, songwriter and former professional footballer. Iglesias is recognized as the most commercially successful Continental European singer in the world and one of the top [[List of best-selling music artists|record sellers in music history]], having sold more than 100 million records worldwide in 14 languages<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/music/86012722/julio-iglesias-pulls-out-of-nz-tour|title=Julio Iglesias pulls out of NZ tour|work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]|date=November 2, 2016|accessdate=November 2, 2016}}</ref> It is estimated that during his career he has performed in more than 5000 concerts, for over 60 million people in five continents. In April 2013, Iglesias was inducted into the Hall of Fame of Latin Composers.\n\nIn 1983, he was celebrated as having recorded songs in the most languages in the world, and in 2013 for being the [[List of best-selling Latin music artists|artist in Latin music with the most records sold]] in history. In April 2013, he was awarded in Beijing as the most popular international artist in China. In Brazil, France, Romania, Italy, and others, Iglesias is the most successful foreign record seller, while in his home country, Spain, he has sold the most records in history, with 23 million records.\n\nDuring his career, Iglesias has won many awards in the music industry, including the [[Grammy]], [[Latin Grammy]], [[World Music Award]], [[Billboard Music Award]], [[American Music Award]] and [[Lo Nuestro Awards|Lo Nuestro Award]]. He has been awarded the Gold Medal for Merit in the Fine Arts of Spain and the [[Legion of Honour]] of France. [[UNICEF]] named him Special Ambassador for the Performing Arts in 1989. He has been a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] since 1985.\n\n==Early life==\nIglesias was born in [[Madrid]] to [[Julio Iglesias Sr.]], a [[medical doctor]] from [[Ourense]] who became one of the youngest [[gynecologist]]s in the country, and Mar\u00eda del Rosario de la Cueva y Perignat. Iglesias's paternal ancestry comes from [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Murashko|first=Alex|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/aug/09/local/me-1436|title=Hands Across the Water, to Spain's Galicia|date=9 August 2000|publisher=latimes.com|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> his paternal grandparents were named Manuela Puga Noguerol  and Ulpiano Iglesias Sarria. His maternal grandparents were Jos\u00e9 de la Cueva y Orejuela (1887\u20131955),<ref>{{cite book |last=Moral Roncal |first=Antonio M. |date=2003 |title=Cuba ante la Guerra Civil Espa\u00f1ola: la acci\u00f3n diplom\u00e1tica de Ram\u00f3n Estalella |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ze2gAAAAMAAJ&q=Julio+Iglesias+Jose+de+la+Cueva+y+Orejuela&dq=Julio+Iglesias+Jose+de+la+Cueva+y+Orejuela&hl=en&sa=X&ei=U3yZUrZ4kNegBI-hgbAP&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAA |publisher=Editorial Biblioteca Nueva, S.L. |isbn=8497421671 |accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref>  and Dolores de Perignat y Ruiz de Benavides,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elcorreogallego.es/tendencias/ecg/vips-julio-cumple-67-anos-plena-gira-mundial/idEdicion-2010-10-02/idNoticia-595712/|title=Julio cumple 67 a\u00f1os en plena gira mundial|date=10 February 2010|publisher=elcorreogallegos.es|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> who was a native of [[Guayama, Puerto Rico|Guayama]], [[Puerto Rico]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://peopleenespanol.com/article/julio-iglesias-tendra-una-estrella-en-el-paseo-de-la-fama-de-puerto-rico/|title=Julio Iglesias tendr\u00e1 una estrella en el Paseo de la Fama de Puerto Rico|accessdate=11 September 2016}}</ref> The name \"Iglesias\" translates as \"churches;\" likewise, Iglesias is of [[Jew]]ish ancestry from his maternal side, having mentioned that his mother's family name, \"de la Cueva y Perignat,\" meaning literally \"of the cave\" and referring to Jewish people in hiding, is a very common Jewish name.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MH&s_site=miami&p_multi=MH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB4D22FCBF3DE06&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=FRONT|date=12 July 1995|newspaper=[[The Miami Herald]]|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Brinn|first=David|url=http://www.jpost.com/Arts-and-Culture/Arts/Julio-Iglesias-still-speaks-the-language-of-love-331514|title=Julio Iglesias still speaks the language of love|date=12 November 2013|publisher=jpost.com|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> He alternated playing professional football with studying law at the [[CEU San Pablo University]] in Madrid. In the earliest years of his young adulthood, he was a goalkeeper for [[Real Madrid Castilla]] in the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]]. His professional football career was ruined when he was involved in a serious automobile accident, due to which he was unable to walk for two years.<ref name=\"ElSoldeCuervanaca\">{{cite news|url=http://www.oem.com.mx/elsoldecuernavaca/notas/n1335699.htm|title=El personaje de hoy|date=23 September 2009|publisher=oem.com.mx|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> Afterwards, he said of those years, \"I had more courage and attitude than talent.\" These were sorely tested when he was involved in that car crash\u2014it smashed his lower spine; his legs were permanently weakened as a direct result, and they still required therapy several years later. During his hospitalization after the accident, a nurse named Eladio Magdaleno gave him a guitar so that he could recover the dexterity of his hands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eltiempo.com/archivo/documento/MAM-4674151|title=Julio Iglesias no se olvida de vivir|first=Casa Editorial El|last=Tiempo|date=10 July 2011|website=El Tiempo}}</ref> In learning to play, he discovered his musical talent.<ref name=\"People-1988\">{{cite news|last1=Dougherty|first1=Steve|last2=Gold|first2=Todd|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20099784,00.html\n|title=Julio Iglesias' Good Life Demands Wine, Women, Song\u2014and More Women|date=29 August 1988|publisher=people.com|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Julio-Enrique\">{{cite book |last=Figueroa |first=Acton |date=2004 |title=Julio Iglesias and Enrique Iglesias |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0I0YfQauX0sC&pg=PA12&lpg=PA12&dq=Julio+Iglesias+legs+therapy+car+accident&source=bl&ots=KJLGFGPBRg&sig=_CE_rgotXD-MLoNBYo1880c1QLM&hl=en&sa=X&ei=2VaaUuChGcT6oASWwIC4Dg&ved=0CDgQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=Julio%20Iglesias%20legs%20therapy%20car%20accident&f=false |publisher=[[Rosen Publishing]] |isbn=1404202609 |accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> After his rehabilitation, Iglesias studied for three months at [[Bell Educational Trust|Bell Educational Trust's Language School]] in [[Cambridge, UK]]. After that, he went back to obtain his law degree at [[Complutense University of Madrid]].<ref>[http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20099784,00.html Julio Iglesias' Good Life Demands Wine, Women, Song\u2014and More Women] - website People.com</ref>\n\n==Entertainment career==\n[[File:Julio Iglesias (Spanje), Bestanddeelnr 923-3697.jpg|thumb|250px|Julio Iglesias at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1970]].]]\nIn 1968, he won the [[Benidorm International Song Festival]], a songwriter's event in Spain, with the song ''\"La vida sigue igual\"'' (meaning \"Life Goes On The Same\") which was used in the film ''La vida sigue igual,'' about his own life. After this event he signed a deal with Discos Columbia, the Spanish branch of the [[Columbia Records]] company, and released his first studio album, titled ''Yo Canto,'' or ''I Sing.'' The\nalbum spent 15 weeks in the Spanish charts,\nand peaked at #3.<ref name=\"Julio-Enrique\" /> He represented Spain in the 1970 [[Eurovision Song Contest 1970|Eurovision Song Contest]], finishing in fourth place<ref>{{cite web|last=Siim|first=Jarmo|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/news?id=1393&_t=iglesias_praises_eurovision_as_a_learning_moment|title=Iglesias praises Eurovision as a learning moment|date=11 October 2008|publisher=eurovision.tv|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> behind Ireland's winning entry, performed by [[Dana Rosemary Scallon|Dana]].<ref>{{cite news|agency=[[Associated Press]]|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=BgciAAAAIBAJ&sjid=GqYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7114,1414412&dq=julio+iglesias+dana+rosemary+scallon+1970+eurovision+song+contest&hl=en|title=Singer in Alabama eyes bid for the Irish presidency|date=8 August 1997|newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> His entry was the song \"[[Gwendolyne]].\" Shortly after, he had a number one hit in many European countries with \"Un Canto A Galicia,\" sung in [[Galician language|Galician]], in honour of his father, who hailed from [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]]. That single sold 1 million copies in Germany. In 1975, he found success in the Italian market by recording a song exclusively in Italian, called \"Se mi lasci non vale,\" or \"If You Leave Me, It Can't Be.\" Notable albums from this decade are ''[[A flor de piel (album)|A flor de piel]]'' (1974, with the European hit \"Manuela\"), ''[[El amor (Julio Iglesias album)|El amor]]'' (1975), and ''[[Soy (Julio Iglesias album)|Soy]]'' (1973). He also sang in French; one of his popular songs in this language became \"Je n'ai pas chang\u00e9.\"\n\nIn 1979, he moved to [[Miami, Florida]], in the United States, signed a deal with [[CBS Corporation|CBS International]], and started singing in different languages such as English, French, Portuguese, German and other languages to his music. Two years later, in 1981, he released the album ''[[De ni\u00f1a a mujer]],'' which he dedicated to his daughter. (She shared the cover photo with him.) From it came the first English-language hit of his career, a Spanish cover of \"[[Begin the Beguine]]\" which became number 1 in the United Kingdom; he also released a collection, ''[[Julio (album)|Julio]]'' (1983). In 1984, he released ''[[1100 Bel Air Place]]'', the hit album which established him as a star in the English-speaking entertainment industry. It sold over three million albums in the United States alone.<ref name=\"People-1988\" /> The first single, \"[[To All the Girls I've Loved Before]],\" a duet with [[Willie Nelson]], hit #1 on the Country charts and went Top Five in the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Trust|first=Gary|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/471241/ask-billboard-readers-favorite-charted-odd-couples|title=Ask Billboard: Readers' Favorite Charted Odd Couples|date=20 May 2011|publisher=billboard.com|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> It also featured \"[[All of You (Julio Iglesias and Diana Ross song)|All of You]],\" in vocal duet with [[Diana Ross]], a Top Twenty Pop hit, that climbed to #2 on the Adult Contemporary Chart with the help of a popular video.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.michiganrockandrolllegends.com/mrrl-hall-of-fame/190-diana-ross|title=DIANA ROSS|publisher=michiganrockandrolllegends.com|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> They also collaborate their friends The Beach Boys\n\nIn 1984, he had recorded and released the previously mentioned duets with [[Diana Ross]] and [[Willie Nelson]]. Iglesias won a [[Grammy Award for Best Latin Pop Album]] in the [[Grammy Awards of 1988|1988 Grammy Awards]] for the album ''[[Un hombre solo]]'' (\"A Man Alone\"). He recorded a duet with [[Stevie Wonder]], \"[[My Love (Julio Iglesias song)|My Love]]\", in his ''[[Non Stop (Julio Iglesias album)|Non Stop]]'' album, a crossover success in 1988. In the 1990s, Iglesias returned to his original Spanish melody in ''[[Tango (Julio Iglesias album)|Tango]]'' (1996), nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Latin Pop Album|Best Latin Pop Album]] at the 1998 Grammy Awards, losing to the ''[[Romances (Luis Miguel album)|Romances]]'' album by Mexican singer, [[Luis Miguel]].<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Latin Pop Performance\" on Rockonthenet.com|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/1998/grammys.htm|accessdate=17 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIglesias made a cameo appearance as himself on ''[[The Golden Girls]]'' as [[Sophia Petrillo]]'s date on St. Valentine's Day 1989. In 1993 he recorded Summer Wind with Frank Sinatra included in his successful album Duets. In 1994 publishes Crazy, including duets with Dolly Parton, Sting and Art Garfunkel. In 1995, Iglesias was the recipient of the [[Lo Nuestro Excellence Award|Excellence Award]] at the [[Premio Lo Nuestro 1995|1995 Lo Nuestro Awards]].<ref name=\"Winners-archive\">{{cite web |url=http://i.univision.com/contentuvn/rinconlatino/plnuestro/images/index_historia.swf|title=Lo Nuestro \u2013 Historia |language=Spanish |work=[[Univision]] |publisher=[[Univision Communications]]|accessdate=March 8, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626102925/http://i.univision.com/contentuvn/rinconlatino/plnuestro/images/index_historia.swf|archivedate=June 26, 2015}}</ref> In 2001, Iglesias was recognized as the [[Latin Recording Academy Person of the Year|Person of the Year]] by the [[Latin Recording Academy]].<ref name=\"Iglesias\">{{cite web|last=Susman|first=Gary|title=Model Patient|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,108354,00.html|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=November 8, 2010|date=May 7, 2001}}</ref> A year later, Iglesias was inducted into the [[International Latin Music Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite news|title=International Latin Music Hall of Fame Announces Inductees for 2002|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/international-latin-music-hall-of-fame-announces-inductees-for-2002-76803217.html|accessdate=31 October 2015|date=5 April 2002}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Julio released his album ''[[Divorcio]]'' (\"Divorce\"). In its first day of sales, ''Divorcio'' sold a record 350,000 albums in Spain, and reached the number 1 spot on the charts in Spain, Portugal, France, Italy, and Russia. In 2003 and 2004, aided by the success of his ''Divorcio'' album, Iglesias went on a ten-month world tour which took him from Europe to Asia and then on to North America, South America and Africa. More than half the shows on that tour sold out within days of going on sale. In December 2004, his Dutch girlfriend Miranda Rijnsburger and Iglesias himself recorded a duet of the Christmas song \"[[Silent Night (song)|Silent Night]]\". The song, which was not officially released, also included a voice message from Iglesias, Rijnsburger, and their 4 young children of that time. The song was released online through the singer's official website and a CD was included on their Christmas card as a holiday gift from the Iglesias family to their friends and fans around the world.\n\nIn 2008, Iglesias recorded another song as a gift to his fans. The family recorded \"The Little Drummer Boy\" in Spanish and English and included it in the family's Christmas card. Iglesias also made investments in the Dominican Republic's eastern town of [[Punta Cana]], a major tourist destination, where he took to spending most of the year. Indeed, Iglesias became a Dominican citizen in 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.diariolibre.com/noticias/2009/10/21/i220301_julio-iglesias-dice-estar-enamorado-repablica-dominicana.html|title=Julio Iglesias dice estar \"enamorado\" de Rep\u00fablica Dominicana|date=21 October 2009|publisher=diariolibre.com|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2006, Iglesias released a new English-language album, which he titled ''[[Romantic Classics]].'' \"I've chosen songs from the 1960s, 1970s and 1980s that I believe will come to be regarded as the new standards,\" Iglesias stated in the album's sleeve notes. The album featured his interpretations of [[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]]'s \"I Want to Know What Love Is,\" the [[Wham!]] selection \"Careless Whisper,\" and [[Richard Marx]]'s \"Right Here Waiting.\" ''Romantic Classics'' was Iglesias's highest debut on the Billboard charts, entering at number 31 in the United States, 21 in Canada, 10 in Australia, and top spots across Europe and Asia. He returned to the studio to record songs in [[Philippine languages|Filipino]] and [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]] for his Asian releases of ''Romantic Classics'' which helped propel record sales in the Asian entertainment industry. Iglesias promoted ''Romantic Classics'' in 2006; it was seen all over the world on television shows. In the United States, for example, he appeared on ''[[Dancing With The Stars]],'' where he sang his version of \"I Want To Know What Love Is,\" ''[[Good Morning America]]'', ''[[The View (U.S. TV series)|The View]],'' ''[[Fox and Friends]],'' and ''Martha Stewart.''\n\nIn 2008, Iglesias made a music video with [[Gulnara Karimova]], the daughter of Uzbek dictator [[Islam Karimov]].<ref name=\"Pizano\">{{cite web|last=Pizano|first=Pedro|title=Crooners and their Dictators|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/pedro-pizano/crooners-and-their-dictators_b_1982520.html|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=9 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2011, the artist launched a new studio album called ''[[1 (Julio Iglesias album)|1]]'' (or ''[[1 (Julio Iglesias album)|Numero 1]]'').\n\nIglesias's performance of the song \"[[La Mer (song)|La Mer]]\" (\"The Sea\") is featured in the soundtrack of the 2011 film ''[[Tinker Tailor Soldier Spy (film)|Tinker Tailor Soldier Spy]].'' The performance comes from a live album, which had gone out of print by the last days of December 2015, that he recorded live at the [[Paris Olympia|Olympia]] theater in Paris in 1976. At the beginning and the end of the recording, Iglesias introduces the song, and his backing musicians, in fluent French.\n\nIn October 2012, Iglesias performed a concert in [[Equatorial Guinea]], where tickets were reportedly $1,000 each.<ref name=\"Pizano\"/>\n\nOn 1 April 2013, in Beijing, he received two historic awards: '''First & Most Popular International Artist of All Time in [[China]],''' an award given by Sony Music China and which was presented to Julio by the world-renowned Chinese artist [[Lang Lang]], and the [[Guinness World Records]] for the Best-selling Male Latin Artist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2013/4/julio-iglesias-receives-world-record-certificate-in-beijing-47865/|title=Julio Iglesias receives world record certificat in Beijing|publisher=Guinness World Record|date=2 April 2013|accessdate=24 December 2013}}</ref> As Iglesias is a composer and lyricist, some of his songs{{Which|date=December 2015}} being of his own authorship and composition, on 23 April 2013, he was inducted into the [[Latin Songwriters Hall of Fame]], alongside [[Armando Manzanero]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Feliciano]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Gratereaux|first=Alexandra|url=http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/entertainment/2013/04/24/latin-songwriters-hall-fame-opens-honoring-julio-iglesias-jose-feliciano/|title=\nLatin Songwriters Hall of Fame Opens Honoring Julio Iglesias, Jose Feliciano|date=24 April 2013|publisher=foxnews.com|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Pajot|first=S.|url=http://blogs.miaminewtimes.com/crossfade/2012/12/latin_songwriters_hall_of_fame_2013_nominees.php|title=Latin Songwriters Hall of Fame Launches in Miami, Announces 2013 Nominees|date=12 December 2012|publisher=miaminewtimes.com|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, as was announced,{{When|date=December 2015}} Iglesias was slated to perform a concert (complete show) for the first time with his son [[Julio Iglesias Jr.]] in a tour in Romania, on 22 May at [[Polyvalent Hall (Cluj-Napoca)|Sala Polivalent\u0103]] in [[Cluj-Napoca]] and 2 July at [[Sala Palatului]] in the capital city, [[Bucharest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://observator.tv/eveniment/julio-iglesias-i-julio-iglesias-jr-primul-concert-impreuna-152154.html|title=Julio Iglesias \u0219i Julio Iglesias Jr., primul concert \u00eempreun\u0103|publisher=Observator|date=14 May 2015|language=Romanian}}</ref>\n\nBerklee College of Music, the most important private university of music in the world, named Julio Iglesias Honorary Doctor, in Boston, on May 9, 2015, in recognition of his achievements and influence in music, and for his enduring contribution to American and international culture.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6561138/julio-iglesias-receives-honorary-degree-from-berklee|title=Julio Iglesias Receives Honorary Degree from Berklee|magazine=Billboard|date=9 May 2015|language=English}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n{{More citations needed section |date=February 2020}}\nOn 29 January 1971, Iglesias married [[Isabel Preysler]], a [[Philippines|Filipina]] journalist and [[television host]]. Preysler, a [[Filipino people of Spanish ancestry|Filipina of Spanish ancestry]], was also a member of the wealthy and aristocratic P\u00e9rez de Tagle family. The couple had three children: [[Chabeli Iglesias|Ch\u00e1beli]] (born 3 September 1971), a socialite; [[Julio Iglesias Jr.|Julio Jr.]] (born 25 February 1973), a singer; and [[Enrique Iglesias|Enrique]] (born 8 May 1975), an internationally successful singer-songwriter, actor, and record producer. In the 1970s, Iglesias and his family were extensively depicted on the front pages of international newspapers and magazines. The marriage of Iglesias and Preysler ended in divorce in 1979.\n\nWhenever Iglesias was not on tour, he spent his time at his Miami residence, purchased in 1978 for $650,000. The mansion on the private [[Indian Creek, Florida|Indian Creek Island]], whose interior design was made by [[Virginia Sipl]],  was placed on the market in 2006 for a quoted $28 million, making it one of \"Ten Most Expensive Homes in the South\" in 2006 according to ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.forbes.com/realestate/2006/06/09/expensive-homes-south_cx_lr_0612home.html | title=Home Improvements - Most Expensive Home In The U.S. 2006: South | publisher=www.forbes.com | author=Lacey Rose | accessdate=12 June 2006 | date=12 June 2006}}</ref>\n\nAfter his divorce, Iglesias lived with Dutch model [[Miranda Rijnsburger]] (b. 1965), 22 years his junior, whom he married on 26 August 2010 in a small church in [[Marbella, Spain]]. They had five children: Miguel Alejandro Iglesias (born 7 September 1997), Rodrigo Iglesias (born 3 April 1999), twins Cristina and Victoria Iglesias (born 1 May 2001), and Guillermo Iglesias (born 5 May 2007). They took up residence in the Dominican Republic, where Iglesias had acquired several hotel complexes, as well as the [[Punta Cana International Airport]], which he acquired jointly with other investors, including fashion designer [[Oscar de la Renta]].<ref name=\"ElSoldeCuervanaca\" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Sanchez|first=Mamen|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20424857,00.html|title=Julio Iglesias & Miranda Rijnsburger: Married After 20 Years!|date=20 September 2010|publisher=people.com|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 December 2005, Iglesias's father, Julio Iglesias Sr., died of a heart attack at the age of 90. A week before his death, it became known that the 42-year-old wife of Julio Iglesias Sr., Ronna Keith, was pregnant with their second child. Their first child, Jaime, was born on 18 May 2004. The second child, Ruth, was born on 26 July 2006.\n\nIn 2008, after his house in Indian Creek did not sell at his asking price, he ordered it razed and said he planned to build another on the lot.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lewis|first=Christina S. N.|url=http://prev.dailyherald.com/story/?id=106350|title=Iglesias tears down and rebuilds rather than settling on low price|date=5 January 2008|publisher=dailyherald.com|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> In 2012, he purchased the property next door for $15 million and announced that he planned to build a new home on the combined properties.<ref>{{cite news|last=Owers|first=Paul|url=http://weblogs.sun-sentinel.com/business/realestate/housekeys/blog/2012/04/report_iglesias_spends_152m_fo_1.html|title=Report: Iglesias spends $15.2m for Miami-Dade home|date=4 April 2012|publisher=sun-sentinel.com|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Brennan|first=Morgan|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/morganbrennan/2012/08/23/inside-indian-creek-island-miamis-billionaire-bunker/2/|title=Inside Indian Creek Island, Miami's Billionaire Bunker|date=10 September 2012|work=forbes.com|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, he was declared as the biological father of a 43 year old Spaniard after having a short affair with the mother. The ruling in Spain is a victory for former ballerina Maria Edite Santos and her son Javier S\u00e1nchez, 43, who began the paternity claim three decades ago.\n\n== In popular culture ==\n\n* Punk band [[The Dead Milkmen|The Dead Milkmen's]] song \"Now Everybody's Me\" contains a reference to Julio, and the singer of the song claiming to have sung a duet with Julio entitled, \"Me and Julio Down By the Crackhouse\".\n* He appeared as the date of Sophia Petrillo ([[Estelle Getty]]) for the Valentine's Day episode of ''[[The Golden Girls]]''.\n* He is mentioned by [[Gary Busey|Gary Busey's]] character Eddie Lomax in the film ''[[The Firm (1993 film)|The Firm]]'', when questioned who supplied him with the information against the titular firm, he sarcastically replies, \"Julio Iglesias\" before being shot.\n*Raekwon the Chef name drops him in the song \u201cCriminology\u201d from his debut solo album Only Built 4 Cuban Linx.\n\n== Honours and Awards ==\n\n=== Honours ===\n\n==== Spanish National Honours ====\n\n* [[File:Medalla de Oro al m\u00e9rito en las Bellas Artes.png|60x60px]] [[Gold Medal of Merit in the Fine Arts (Spain)|Gold Medal of Merit in the Fine Arts]]\n* [[File:Orden_del_Dos_de_Mayo.gif|60x60px]] Gold Medal of the [[Community of Madrid]]\n\n==== Foreign Honours ====\n\n* {{flag|France}}\n** [[File:Legion Honneur Chevalier ribbon.svg|60x60px]]Knight of the [[Legion of Honour|Legion of Honor]]\n** [[Medal of the City of Paris]]\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Julio Iglesias discography}}\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n; Selected albums\n*1969: ''[[Yo canto (Julio Iglesias album)|Yo canto]]''\n*1970: ''Gwendolyne''\n*1972: ''[[Un canto a Galicia]]''\n*1973: ''[[Soy (Julio Iglesias album)|Soy]]''\n*1974: ''[[A flor de piel (album)|A flor de piel]]''\n*1974: ''Viens m'embrasser''{{Citation needed|date=February 2018|reason=This appears to be the name of a song only}}\n*1975: ''[[A M\u00e9xico]]''\n*1975: ''[[El amor (Julio Iglesias album)|El amor]]''\n*1976: ''[[America (Julio Iglesias album)|America]]''\n*1977: ''[[A mis 33 a\u00f1os]]''\n*1978: ''[[Aimer la vie]]''\n*1978: ''[[Emociones (Julio Iglesias album)|Emociones]]''\n*1978: ''[[Sono un pirata, sono un signore]]''\n*1979: ''[[\u00c0 vous les femmes]]''\n*1980: ''[[Hey! (Julio Iglesias album)|Hey!]]''\n*1981: ''[[De ni\u00f1a a mujer]]''\n*1982: ''[[Et l'amour crea la femme]]''\n*1982: ''[[Momentos (Julio Iglesias album)|Momentos]]''\n*1982: ''[[Momenti]]''\n{{col-2}}\n*1983: ''[[Julio (album)|Julio]]''\n*1984: ''[[1100 Bel Air Place]]'' \n*1985: ''[[Libra (Julio Iglesias album)|Libra]]''\n*1987: ''[[Un hombre solo]]''\n*1987: ''[[Tutto l'amore che ti manca]]''\n*1988: ''[[Non Stop (Julio Iglesias album)|Non Stop]]''\n*1989: ''[[Ra\u00edces (Julio Iglesias album)|Ra\u00edces]]''\n*1990: ''[[Starry Night (Julio Iglesias album)|Starry Night]]''\n*1992: ''[[Calor (album)|Calor]]''\n*1994: ''[[Crazy (Julio Iglesias album)|Crazy]]'' \n*1995: ''[[La Carretera|La carretera]]''\n*1996: ''[[Tango (Julio Iglesias album)|Tango]]''\n*2000: ''[[Noche de cuatro lunas]]''\n*2001: ''[[Ao Meu Brasil]]''\n*2003: ''[[Divorcio]]''\n*2006: ''[[Romantic Classics]]'' \n*2007: ''Quelque chose de France''\n*2011: ''[[1 (Julio Iglesias album)|1]]''\n*2015: ''[[M\u00e9xico (Julio Iglesias album)|M\u00e9xico]]''\n*2017: ''[[M\u00e9xico y Amigos]]'' \n*2017: ''[[Dois Cora\u00e7\u00f5es]]''  \n{{col-end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.julioiglesias.com/ Official website]\n* [http://www.musicadelrecuerdo.com/shopdisplayproducts.asp?search=Yes&amp;keyword=JULIO%20IGLESIAS Musicadelrecuerdo.com Musica de Julio Iglesias]\n* {{IMDb name|2960}}\n{{Commons category|Julio Iglesias}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box |\n  before=[[Salom\u00e9 (singer)|Salom\u00e9]]<br />with ''\"[[Vivo cantando]]\"'' |\n  title=[[Spain in the Eurovision Song Contest]] |\n  years=1970 |\n  after=[[Karina (Spain)|Karina]]<br />with ''\"[[En un mundo nuevo]]\"'' |\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Latin music|Spain}}\n{{Julio Iglesias}}\n{{Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award}}\n{{Latin Recording Academy Person of the Year}}\n{{Spain in the Eurovision Song Contest |state=autocollapse}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest 1970 |state=autocollapse}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iglesias, Julio}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:English-language singers from Spain]]\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:People from Madrid]]\n[[Category:Eurovision Song Contest entrants of 1970]]\n[[Category:French-language singers]]\n[[Category:Galician people (Spain)]]\n[[Category:German-language singers]]\n[[Category:Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award winners]]\n[[Category:Latin Recording Academy Person of the Year honorees]]\n[[Category:Italian-language singers]]\n[[Category:Russian-language singers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Singers from Madrid]]\n[[Category:Portuguese-language singers]]\n[[Category:Real Madrid Castilla footballers]]\n[[Category:Spanish Eurovision Song Contest entrants]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Spanish male singers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Miami]]\n[[Category:Spanish Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n[[Category:Spanish people of Galician descent]]\n[[Category:Spanish people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Spanish people of Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:Spanish pop singers]]\n[[Category:Latin pop singers]]\n[[Category:Sony Music Spain artists]]\n[[Category:Naturalized citizens of the Dominican Republic]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Florida]]\n[[Category:Latin music songwriters]]\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Spanish singers]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:Iglesias family|Julio]]\n[[Category:Country musicians from Florida]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n[[Category:Spanish emigrants to the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the singer Julio Iglesias|his father|Julio Iglesias Sr.|his son|Julio Iglesias Jr.|other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Spanish name|Iglesias|de la Cueva}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                = Julio Iglesias\n| image               = Julio Iglesias09.jpg\n| caption             =\n| image_size          =\n| birth_name          = Julio Jos\u00e9 Iglesias de la Cueva\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1943|9|23}}\n| birth_place         = [[Madrid]], Spain\n| years_active        = 1968\u2013present\n| website             = [http://www.julioiglesias.com/ www.julioiglesias.com]\n| spouse             = {{plainlist|\n* {{marriage|[[Isabel Preysler]]|1971|1979|end=divorced}}\n* {{marriage|Miranda Rijnsburger|2010}}\n}}\n| children           = 9, including [[Chabeli Iglesias]], [[Julio Iglesias Jr.]], [[Enrique Iglesias]], and Javier Iglesias Santos <ref>https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/10/europe/julio-iglesias-paternity-claim-intl/index.html</ref>\n| residence          = [[Marbella]] (M\u00e1laga), [[Andalusia]], [[Spain]]\n| module = {{Infobox musical artist | embed = yes\n| background          = solo_singer\n| genre               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Latin music|Latin]]\n* [[Latin pop]]\n* [[dance-pop]]\n* [[Adult contemporary music|adult contemporary]]\n}}\n| label               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n* [[Sony Music|Sony]]\n}}\n}}\n| module2 = {{Infobox football biography | embed = yes | header-color = #F0E68C\n| nocat_wdimage = yes\n| position = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| years1 = 1960\u20131964\n| clubs1 = [[Real Madrid Castilla]]\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Julio Jos\u00e9 Iglesias de la Cueva''' ({{IPA-es|\u02c8xuljo i\u02c8\u0263lesjas}}; born 23 September 1943) is a Spanish singer, songwriter and former professional footballer. Iglesias is recognized as the most commercially successful Continental European singer in the world and one of the top ten record sellers in music history, having sold more than 100 million records worldwide in 14 languages<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/music/86012722/julio-iglesias-pulls-out-of-nz-tour|title=Julio Iglesias pulls out of NZ tour|work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]|date=November 2, 2016|accessdate=November 2, 2016}}</ref> It is estimated that during his career he has performed in more than 5000 concerts, for over 60 million people in five continents. In April 2013, Iglesias was inducted into the Hall of Fame of Latin Composers.\n\nIn 1983, he was celebrated as having recorded songs in the most languages in the world, and in 2013 for being the [[List of best-selling Latin music artists|artist in Latin music with the most records sold]] in history. In April 2013, he was awarded in Beijing as the most popular international artist in China. In Brazil, France, Romania, Italy, and others, Iglesias is the most successful foreign record seller, while in his home country, Spain, he has sold the most records in history, with 23 million records.\n\nDuring his career, Iglesias has won many awards in the music industry, including the [[Grammy]], [[Latin Grammy]], [[World Music Award]], [[Billboard Music Award]], [[American Music Award]] and [[Lo Nuestro Awards|Lo Nuestro Award]]. He has been awarded the Gold Medal for Merit in the Fine Arts of Spain and the [[Legion of Honour]] of France. [[UNICEF]] named him Special Ambassador for the Performing Arts in 1989. He has been a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] since 1985.\n\n==Early life==\nIglesias was born in [[Madrid]] to [[Julio Iglesias Sr.]], a [[medical doctor]] from [[Ourense]] who became one of the youngest [[gynecologist]]s in the country, and Mar\u00eda del Rosario de la Cueva y Perignat. Iglesias's paternal ancestry comes from [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Murashko|first=Alex|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/aug/09/local/me-1436|title=Hands Across the Water, to Spain's Galicia|date=9 August 2000|publisher=latimes.com|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> his paternal grandparents were named Manuela Puga Noguerol  and Ulpiano Iglesias Sarria. His maternal grandparents were Jos\u00e9 de la Cueva y Orejuela (1887\u20131955),<ref>{{cite book |last=Moral Roncal |first=Antonio M. |date=2003 |title=Cuba ante la Guerra Civil Espa\u00f1ola: la acci\u00f3n diplom\u00e1tica de Ram\u00f3n Estalella |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ze2gAAAAMAAJ&q=Julio+Iglesias+Jose+de+la+Cueva+y+Orejuela&dq=Julio+Iglesias+Jose+de+la+Cueva+y+Orejuela&hl=en&sa=X&ei=U3yZUrZ4kNegBI-hgbAP&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAA |publisher=Editorial Biblioteca Nueva, S.L. |isbn=8497421671 |accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref>  and Dolores de Perignat y Ruiz de Benavides,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elcorreogallego.es/tendencias/ecg/vips-julio-cumple-67-anos-plena-gira-mundial/idEdicion-2010-10-02/idNoticia-595712/|title=Julio cumple 67 a\u00f1os en plena gira mundial|date=10 February 2010|publisher=elcorreogallegos.es|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> who was a native of [[Guayama, Puerto Rico|Guayama]], [[Puerto Rico]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://peopleenespanol.com/article/julio-iglesias-tendra-una-estrella-en-el-paseo-de-la-fama-de-puerto-rico/|title=Julio Iglesias tendr\u00e1 una estrella en el Paseo de la Fama de Puerto Rico|accessdate=11 September 2016}}</ref> The name \"Iglesias\" translates as \"churches;\" likewise, Iglesias is of [[Jew]]ish ancestry from his maternal side, having mentioned that his mother's family name, \"de la Cueva y Perignat,\" meaning literally \"of the cave\" and referring to Jewish people in hiding, is a very common Jewish name.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MH&s_site=miami&p_multi=MH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB4D22FCBF3DE06&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=FRONT|date=12 July 1995|newspaper=[[The Miami Herald]]|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Brinn|first=David|url=http://www.jpost.com/Arts-and-Culture/Arts/Julio-Iglesias-still-speaks-the-language-of-love-331514|title=Julio Iglesias still speaks the language of love|date=12 November 2013|publisher=jpost.com|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> He alternated playing professional football with studying law at the [[CEU San Pablo University]] in Madrid. In the earliest years of his young adulthood, he was a goalkeeper for [[Real Madrid Castilla]] in the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]]. His professional football career was ruined when he was involved in a serious automobile accident, due to which he was unable to walk for two years.<ref name=\"ElSoldeCuervanaca\">{{cite news|url=http://www.oem.com.mx/elsoldecuernavaca/notas/n1335699.htm|title=El personaje de hoy|date=23 September 2009|publisher=oem.com.mx|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> Afterwards, he said of those years, \"I had more courage and attitude than talent.\" These were sorely tested when he was involved in that car crash\u2014it smashed his lower spine; his legs were permanently weakened as a direct result, and they still required therapy several years later. During his hospitalization after the accident, a nurse named Eladio Magdaleno gave him a guitar so that he could recover the dexterity of his hands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eltiempo.com/archivo/documento/MAM-4674151|title=Julio Iglesias no se olvida de vivir|first=Casa Editorial El|last=Tiempo|date=10 July 2011|website=El Tiempo}}</ref> In learning to play, he discovered his musical talent.<ref name=\"People-1988\">{{cite news|last1=Dougherty|first1=Steve|last2=Gold|first2=Todd|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20099784,00.html\n|title=Julio Iglesias' Good Life Demands Wine, Women, Song\u2014and More Women|date=29 August 1988|publisher=people.com|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Julio-Enrique\">{{cite book |last=Figueroa |first=Acton |date=2004 |title=Julio Iglesias and Enrique Iglesias |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0I0YfQauX0sC&pg=PA12&lpg=PA12&dq=Julio+Iglesias+legs+therapy+car+accident&source=bl&ots=KJLGFGPBRg&sig=_CE_rgotXD-MLoNBYo1880c1QLM&hl=en&sa=X&ei=2VaaUuChGcT6oASWwIC4Dg&ved=0CDgQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=Julio%20Iglesias%20legs%20therapy%20car%20accident&f=false |publisher=[[Rosen Publishing]] |isbn=1404202609 |accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> After his rehabilitation, Iglesias studied for three months at [[Bell Educational Trust|Bell Educational Trust's Language School]] in [[Cambridge, UK]]. After that, he went back to obtain his law degree at [[Complutense University of Madrid]].<ref>[http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20099784,00.html Julio Iglesias' Good Life Demands Wine, Women, Song\u2014and More Women] - website People.com</ref>\n\n==Entertainment career==\n[[File:Julio Iglesias (Spanje), Bestanddeelnr 923-3697.jpg|thumb|250px|Julio Iglesias at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1970]].]]\nIn 1968, he won the [[Benidorm International Song Festival]], a songwriter's event in Spain, with the song ''\"La vida sigue igual\"'' (meaning \"Life Goes On The Same\") which was used in the film ''La vida sigue igual,'' about his own life. After this event he signed a deal with Discos Columbia, the Spanish branch of the [[Columbia Records]] company, and released his first studio album, titled ''Yo Canto,'' or ''I Sing.'' The\nalbum spent 15 weeks in the Spanish charts,\nand peaked at #3.<ref name=\"Julio-Enrique\" /> He represented Spain in the 1970 [[Eurovision Song Contest 1970|Eurovision Song Contest]], finishing in fourth place<ref>{{cite web|last=Siim|first=Jarmo|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/news?id=1393&_t=iglesias_praises_eurovision_as_a_learning_moment|title=Iglesias praises Eurovision as a learning moment|date=11 October 2008|publisher=eurovision.tv|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> behind Ireland's winning entry, performed by [[Dana Rosemary Scallon|Dana]].<ref>{{cite news|agency=[[Associated Press]]|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=BgciAAAAIBAJ&sjid=GqYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7114,1414412&dq=julio+iglesias+dana+rosemary+scallon+1970+eurovision+song+contest&hl=en|title=Singer in Alabama eyes bid for the Irish presidency|date=8 August 1997|newspaper=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> His entry was the song \"[[Gwendolyne]].\" Shortly after, he had a number one hit in many European countries with \"Un Canto A Galicia,\" sung in [[Galician language|Galician]], in honour of his father, who hailed from [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]]. That single sold 1 million copies in Germany. In 1975, he found success in the Italian market by recording a song exclusively in Italian, called \"Se mi lasci non vale,\" or \"If You Leave Me, It Can't Be.\" Notable albums from this decade are ''[[A flor de piel (album)|A flor de piel]]'' (1974, with the European hit \"Manuela\"), ''[[El amor (Julio Iglesias album)|El amor]]'' (1975), and ''[[Soy (Julio Iglesias album)|Soy]]'' (1973). He also sang in French; one of his popular songs in this language became \"Je n'ai pas chang\u00e9.\"\n\nIn 1979, he moved to [[Miami, Florida]], in the United States, signed a deal with [[CBS Corporation|CBS International]], and started singing in different languages such as English, French, Portuguese, German and other languages to his music. Two years later, in 1981, he released the album ''[[De ni\u00f1a a mujer]],'' which he dedicated to his daughter. (She shared the cover photo with him.) From it came the first English-language hit of his career, a Spanish cover of \"[[Begin the Beguine]]\" which became number 1 in the United Kingdom; he also released a collection, ''[[Julio (album)|Julio]]'' (1983). In 1984, he released ''[[1100 Bel Air Place]]'', the hit album which established him as a star in the English-speaking entertainment industry. It sold over three million albums in the United States alone.<ref name=\"People-1988\" /> The first single, \"[[To All the Girls I've Loved Before]],\" a duet with [[Willie Nelson]], hit #1 on the Country charts and went Top Five in the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Trust|first=Gary|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/471241/ask-billboard-readers-favorite-charted-odd-couples|title=Ask Billboard: Readers' Favorite Charted Odd Couples|date=20 May 2011|publisher=billboard.com|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> It also featured \"[[All of You (Julio Iglesias and Diana Ross song)|All of You]],\" in vocal duet with [[Diana Ross]], a Top Twenty Pop hit, that climbed to #2 on the Adult Contemporary Chart with the help of a popular video.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.michiganrockandrolllegends.com/mrrl-hall-of-fame/190-diana-ross|title=DIANA ROSS|publisher=michiganrockandrolllegends.com|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> They also collaborate their friends The Beach Boys\n\nIn 1984, he had recorded and released the previously mentioned duets with [[Diana Ross]] and [[Willie Nelson]]. Iglesias won a [[Grammy Award for Best Latin Pop Album]] in the [[Grammy Awards of 1988|1988 Grammy Awards]] for the album ''[[Un hombre solo]]'' (\"A Man Alone\"). He recorded a duet with [[Stevie Wonder]], \"[[My Love (Julio Iglesias song)|My Love]]\", in his ''[[Non Stop (Julio Iglesias album)|Non Stop]]'' album, a crossover success in 1988. In the 1990s, Iglesias returned to his original Spanish melody in ''[[Tango (Julio Iglesias album)|Tango]]'' (1996), nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Latin Pop Album|Best Latin Pop Album]] at the 1998 Grammy Awards, losing to the ''[[Romances (Luis Miguel album)|Romances]]'' album by Mexican singer, [[Luis Miguel]].<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Latin Pop Performance\" on Rockonthenet.com|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/1998/grammys.htm|accessdate=17 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIglesias made a cameo appearance as himself on ''[[The Golden Girls]]'' as [[Sophia Petrillo]]'s date on St. Valentine's Day 1989. In 1993 he recorded Summer Wind with Frank Sinatra included in his successful album Duets. In 1994 publishes Crazy, including duets with Dolly Parton, Sting and Art Garfunkel. In 1995, Iglesias was the recipient of the [[Lo Nuestro Excellence Award|Excellence Award]] at the [[Premio Lo Nuestro 1995|1995 Lo Nuestro Awards]].<ref name=\"Winners-archive\">{{cite web |url=http://i.univision.com/contentuvn/rinconlatino/plnuestro/images/index_historia.swf|title=Lo Nuestro \u2013 Historia |language=Spanish |work=[[Univision]] |publisher=[[Univision Communications]]|accessdate=March 8, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626102925/http://i.univision.com/contentuvn/rinconlatino/plnuestro/images/index_historia.swf|archivedate=June 26, 2015}}</ref> In 2001, Iglesias was recognized as the [[Latin Recording Academy Person of the Year|Person of the Year]] by the [[Latin Recording Academy]].<ref name=\"Iglesias\">{{cite web|last=Susman|first=Gary|title=Model Patient|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,108354,00.html|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=November 8, 2010|date=May 7, 2001}}</ref> A year later, Iglesias was inducted into the [[International Latin Music Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite news|title=International Latin Music Hall of Fame Announces Inductees for 2002|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/international-latin-music-hall-of-fame-announces-inductees-for-2002-76803217.html|accessdate=31 October 2015|date=5 April 2002}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Julio released his album ''[[Divorcio]]'' (\"Divorce\"). In its first day of sales, ''Divorcio'' sold a record 350,000 albums in Spain, and reached the number 1 spot on the charts in Spain, Portugal, France, Italy, and Russia. In 2003 and 2004, aided by the success of his ''Divorcio'' album, Iglesias went on a ten-month world tour which took him from Europe to Asia and then on to North America, South America and Africa. More than half the shows on that tour sold out within days of going on sale. In December 2004, his Dutch girlfriend Miranda Rijnsburger and Iglesias himself recorded a duet of the Christmas song \"[[Silent Night (song)|Silent Night]]\". The song, which was not officially released, also included a voice message from Iglesias, Rijnsburger, and their 4 young children of that time. The song was released online through the singer's official website and a CD was included on their Christmas card as a holiday gift from the Iglesias family to their friends and fans around the world.\n\nIn 2008, Iglesias recorded another song as a gift to his fans. The family recorded \"The Little Drummer Boy\" in Spanish and English and included it in the family's Christmas card. Iglesias also made investments in the Dominican Republic's eastern town of [[Punta Cana]], a major tourist destination, where he took to spending most of the year. Indeed, Iglesias became a Dominican citizen in 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.diariolibre.com/noticias/2009/10/21/i220301_julio-iglesias-dice-estar-enamorado-repablica-dominicana.html|title=Julio Iglesias dice estar \"enamorado\" de Rep\u00fablica Dominicana|date=21 October 2009|publisher=diariolibre.com|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2006, Iglesias released a new English-language album, which he titled ''[[Romantic Classics]].'' \"I've chosen songs from the 1960s, 1970s and 1980s that I believe will come to be regarded as the new standards,\" Iglesias stated in the album's sleeve notes. The album featured his interpretations of [[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]]'s \"I Want to Know What Love Is,\" the [[Wham!]] selection \"Careless Whisper,\" and [[Richard Marx]]'s \"Right Here Waiting.\" ''Romantic Classics'' was Iglesias's highest debut on the Billboard charts, entering at number 31 in the United States, 21 in Canada, 10 in Australia, and top spots across Europe and Asia. He returned to the studio to record songs in [[Philippine languages|Filipino]] and [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]] for his Asian releases of ''Romantic Classics'' which helped propel record sales in the Asian entertainment industry. Iglesias promoted ''Romantic Classics'' in 2006; it was seen all over the world on television shows. In the United States, for example, he appeared on ''[[Dancing With The Stars]],'' where he sang his version of \"I Want To Know What Love Is,\" ''[[Good Morning America]]'', ''[[The View (U.S. TV series)|The View]],'' ''[[Fox and Friends]],'' and ''Martha Stewart.''\n\nIn 2008, Iglesias made a music video with [[Gulnara Karimova]], the daughter of Uzbek dictator [[Islam Karimov]].<ref name=\"Pizano\">{{cite web|last=Pizano|first=Pedro|title=Crooners and their Dictators|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/pedro-pizano/crooners-and-their-dictators_b_1982520.html|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=9 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2011, the artist launched a new studio album called ''[[1 (Julio Iglesias album)|1]]'' (or ''[[1 (Julio Iglesias album)|Numero 1]]'').\n\nIglesias's performance of the song \"[[La Mer (song)|La Mer]]\" (\"The Sea\") is featured in the soundtrack of the 2011 film ''[[Tinker Tailor Soldier Spy (film)|Tinker Tailor Soldier Spy]].'' The performance comes from a live album, which had gone out of print by the last days of December 2015, that he recorded live at the [[Paris Olympia|Olympia]] theater in Paris in 1976. At the beginning and the end of the recording, Iglesias introduces the song, and his backing musicians, in fluent French.\n\nIn October 2012, Iglesias performed a concert in [[Equatorial Guinea]], where tickets were reportedly $1,000 each.<ref name=\"Pizano\"/>\n\nOn 1 April 2013, in Beijing, he received two historic awards: '''First & Most Popular International Artist of All Time in [[China]],''' an award given by Sony Music China and which was presented to Julio by the world-renowned Chinese artist [[Lang Lang]], and the [[Guinness World Records]] for the Best-selling Male Latin Artist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2013/4/julio-iglesias-receives-world-record-certificate-in-beijing-47865/|title=Julio Iglesias receives world record certificat in Beijing|publisher=Guinness World Record|date=2 April 2013|accessdate=24 December 2013}}</ref> As Iglesias is a composer and lyricist, some of his songs{{Which|date=December 2015}} being of his own authorship and composition, on 23 April 2013, he was inducted into the [[Latin Songwriters Hall of Fame]], alongside [[Armando Manzanero]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Feliciano]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Gratereaux|first=Alexandra|url=http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/entertainment/2013/04/24/latin-songwriters-hall-fame-opens-honoring-julio-iglesias-jose-feliciano/|title=\nLatin Songwriters Hall of Fame Opens Honoring Julio Iglesias, Jose Feliciano|date=24 April 2013|publisher=foxnews.com|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Pajot|first=S.|url=http://blogs.miaminewtimes.com/crossfade/2012/12/latin_songwriters_hall_of_fame_2013_nominees.php|title=Latin Songwriters Hall of Fame Launches in Miami, Announces 2013 Nominees|date=12 December 2012|publisher=miaminewtimes.com|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, as was announced,{{When|date=December 2015}} Iglesias was slated to perform a concert (complete show) for the first time with his son [[Julio Iglesias Jr.]] in a tour in Romania, on 22 May at [[Polyvalent Hall (Cluj-Napoca)|Sala Polivalent\u0103]] in [[Cluj-Napoca]] and 2 July at [[Sala Palatului]] in the capital city, [[Bucharest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://observator.tv/eveniment/julio-iglesias-i-julio-iglesias-jr-primul-concert-impreuna-152154.html|title=Julio Iglesias \u0219i Julio Iglesias Jr., primul concert \u00eempreun\u0103|publisher=Observator|date=14 May 2015|language=Romanian}}</ref>\n\nBerklee College of Music, the most important private university of music in the world, named Julio Iglesias Honorary Doctor, in Boston, on May 9, 2015, in recognition of his achievements and influence in music, and for his enduring contribution to American and international culture.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6561138/julio-iglesias-receives-honorary-degree-from-berklee|title=Julio Iglesias Receives Honorary Degree from Berklee|magazine=Billboard|date=9 May 2015|language=English}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n{{More citations needed section |date=February 2020}}\nOn 29 January 1971, Iglesias married [[Isabel Preysler]], a [[Philippines|Filipina]] journalist and [[television host]]. Preysler, a [[Filipino people of Spanish ancestry|Filipina of Spanish ancestry]], was also a member of the wealthy and aristocratic P\u00e9rez de Tagle family. The couple had three children: [[Chabeli Iglesias|Ch\u00e1beli]] (born 3 September 1971), a socialite; [[Julio Iglesias Jr.|Julio Jr.]] (born 25 February 1973), a singer; and [[Enrique Iglesias|Enrique]] (born 8 May 1975), an internationally successful singer-songwriter, actor, and record producer. In the 1970s, Iglesias and his family were extensively depicted on the front pages of international newspapers and magazines. The marriage of Iglesias and Preysler ended in divorce in 1979.\n\nWhenever Iglesias was not on tour, he spent his time at his Miami residence, purchased in 1978 for $650,000. The mansion on the private [[Indian Creek, Florida|Indian Creek Island]], whose interior design was made by [[Virginia Sipl]],  was placed on the market in 2006 for a quoted $28 million, making it one of \"Ten Most Expensive Homes in the South\" in 2006 according to ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.forbes.com/realestate/2006/06/09/expensive-homes-south_cx_lr_0612home.html | title=Home Improvements - Most Expensive Home In The U.S. 2006: South | publisher=www.forbes.com | author=Lacey Rose | accessdate=12 June 2006 | date=12 June 2006}}</ref>\n\nAfter his divorce, Iglesias lived with Dutch model [[Miranda Rijnsburger]] (b. 1965), 22 years his junior, whom he married on 26 August 2010 in a small church in [[Marbella, Spain]]. They had five children: Miguel Alejandro Iglesias (born 7 September 1997), Rodrigo Iglesias (born 3 April 1999), twins Cristina and Victoria Iglesias (born 1 May 2001), and Guillermo Iglesias (born 5 May 2007). They took up residence in the Dominican Republic, where Iglesias had acquired several hotel complexes, as well as the [[Punta Cana International Airport]], which he acquired jointly with other investors, including fashion designer [[Oscar de la Renta]].<ref name=\"ElSoldeCuervanaca\" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Sanchez|first=Mamen|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20424857,00.html|title=Julio Iglesias & Miranda Rijnsburger: Married After 20 Years!|date=20 September 2010|publisher=people.com|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 December 2005, Iglesias's father, Julio Iglesias Sr., died of a heart attack at the age of 90. A week before his death, it became known that the 42-year-old wife of Julio Iglesias Sr., Ronna Keith, was pregnant with their second child. Their first child, Jaime, was born on 18 May 2004. The second child, Ruth, was born on 26 July 2006.\n\nIn 2008, after his house in Indian Creek did not sell at his asking price, he ordered it razed and said he planned to build another on the lot.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lewis|first=Christina S. N.|url=http://prev.dailyherald.com/story/?id=106350|title=Iglesias tears down and rebuilds rather than settling on low price|date=5 January 2008|publisher=dailyherald.com|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> In 2012, he purchased the property next door for $15 million and announced that he planned to build a new home on the combined properties.<ref>{{cite news|last=Owers|first=Paul|url=http://weblogs.sun-sentinel.com/business/realestate/housekeys/blog/2012/04/report_iglesias_spends_152m_fo_1.html|title=Report: Iglesias spends $15.2m for Miami-Dade home|date=4 April 2012|publisher=sun-sentinel.com|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Brennan|first=Morgan|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/morganbrennan/2012/08/23/inside-indian-creek-island-miamis-billionaire-bunker/2/|title=Inside Indian Creek Island, Miami's Billionaire Bunker|date=10 September 2012|work=forbes.com|accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, he was declared as the biological father of a 43 year old Spaniard after having a short affair with the mother. The ruling in Spain is a victory for former ballerina Maria Edite Santos and her son Javier S\u00e1nchez, 43, who began the paternity claim three decades ago.\n\n== In popular culture ==\n\n* Punk band [[The Dead Milkmen|The Dead Milkmen's]] song \"Now Everybody's Me\" contains a reference to Julio, and the singer of the song claiming to have sung a duet with Julio entitled, \"Me and Julio Down By the Crackhouse\".\n* He appeared as the date of Sophia Petrillo ([[Estelle Getty]]) for the Valentine's Day episode of ''[[The Golden Girls]]''.\n* He is mentioned by [[Gary Busey|Gary Busey's]] character Eddie Lomax in the film ''[[The Firm (1993 film)|The Firm]]'', when questioned who supplied him with the information against the titular firm, he sarcastically replies, \"Julio Iglesias\" before being shot.\n*Raekwon the Chef name drops him in the song \u201cCriminology\u201d from his debut solo album Only Built 4 Cuban Linx.\n\n== Honours and Awards ==\n\n=== Honours ===\n\n==== Spanish National Honours ====\n\n* [[File:Medalla de Oro al m\u00e9rito en las Bellas Artes.png|60x60px]] [[Gold Medal of Merit in the Fine Arts (Spain)|Gold Medal of Merit in the Fine Arts]]\n* [[File:Orden_del_Dos_de_Mayo.gif|60x60px]] Gold Medal of the [[Community of Madrid]]\n\n==== Foreign Honours ====\n\n* {{flag|France}}\n** [[File:Legion Honneur Chevalier ribbon.svg|60x60px]]Knight of the [[Legion of Honour|Legion of Honor]]\n** [[Medal of the City of Paris]]\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Julio Iglesias discography}}\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n; Selected albums\n*1969: ''[[Yo canto (Julio Iglesias album)|Yo canto]]''\n*1970: ''Gwendolyne''\n*1972: ''[[Un canto a Galicia]]''\n*1973: ''[[Soy (Julio Iglesias album)|Soy]]''\n*1974: ''[[A flor de piel (album)|A flor de piel]]''\n*1974: ''Viens m'embrasser''{{Citation needed|date=February 2018|reason=This appears to be the name of a song only}}\n*1975: ''[[A M\u00e9xico]]''\n*1975: ''[[El amor (Julio Iglesias album)|El amor]]''\n*1976: ''[[America (Julio Iglesias album)|America]]''\n*1977: ''[[A mis 33 a\u00f1os]]''\n*1978: ''[[Aimer la vie]]''\n*1978: ''[[Emociones (Julio Iglesias album)|Emociones]]''\n*1978: ''[[Sono un pirata, sono un signore]]''\n*1979: ''[[\u00c0 vous les femmes]]''\n*1980: ''[[Hey! (Julio Iglesias album)|Hey!]]''\n*1981: ''[[De ni\u00f1a a mujer]]''\n*1982: ''[[Et l'amour crea la femme]]''\n*1982: ''[[Momentos (Julio Iglesias album)|Momentos]]''\n*1982: ''[[Momenti]]''\n{{col-2}}\n*1983: ''[[Julio (album)|Julio]]''\n*1984: ''[[1100 Bel Air Place]]'' \n*1985: ''[[Libra (Julio Iglesias album)|Libra]]''\n*1987: ''[[Un hombre solo]]''\n*1987: ''[[Tutto l'amore che ti manca]]''\n*1988: ''[[Non Stop (Julio Iglesias album)|Non Stop]]''\n*1989: ''[[Ra\u00edces (Julio Iglesias album)|Ra\u00edces]]''\n*1990: ''[[Starry Night (Julio Iglesias album)|Starry Night]]''\n*1992: ''[[Calor (album)|Calor]]''\n*1994: ''[[Crazy (Julio Iglesias album)|Crazy]]'' \n*1995: ''[[La Carretera|La carretera]]''\n*1996: ''[[Tango (Julio Iglesias album)|Tango]]''\n*2000: ''[[Noche de cuatro lunas]]''\n*2001: ''[[Ao Meu Brasil]]''\n*2003: ''[[Divorcio]]''\n*2006: ''[[Romantic Classics]]'' \n*2007: ''Quelque chose de France''\n*2011: ''[[1 (Julio Iglesias album)|1]]''\n*2015: ''[[M\u00e9xico (Julio Iglesias album)|M\u00e9xico]]''\n*2017: ''[[M\u00e9xico y Amigos]]'' \n*2017: ''[[Dois Cora\u00e7\u00f5es]]''  \n{{col-end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.julioiglesias.com/ Official website]\n* [http://www.musicadelrecuerdo.com/shopdisplayproducts.asp?search=Yes&amp;keyword=JULIO%20IGLESIAS Musicadelrecuerdo.com Musica de Julio Iglesias]\n* {{IMDb name|2960}}\n{{Commons category|Julio Iglesias}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box |\n  before=[[Salom\u00e9 (singer)|Salom\u00e9]]<br />with ''\"[[Vivo cantando]]\"'' |\n  title=[[Spain in the Eurovision Song Contest]] |\n  years=1970 |\n  after=[[Karina (Spain)|Karina]]<br />with ''\"[[En un mundo nuevo]]\"'' |\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Latin music|Spain}}\n{{Julio Iglesias}}\n{{Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award}}\n{{Latin Recording Academy Person of the Year}}\n{{Spain in the Eurovision Song Contest |state=autocollapse}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest 1970 |state=autocollapse}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iglesias, Julio}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:English-language singers from Spain]]\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:People from Madrid]]\n[[Category:Eurovision Song Contest entrants of 1970]]\n[[Category:French-language singers]]\n[[Category:Galician people (Spain)]]\n[[Category:German-language singers]]\n[[Category:Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award winners]]\n[[Category:Latin Recording Academy Person of the Year honorees]]\n[[Category:Italian-language singers]]\n[[Category:Russian-language singers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Singers from Madrid]]\n[[Category:Portuguese-language singers]]\n[[Category:Real Madrid Castilla footballers]]\n[[Category:Spanish Eurovision Song Contest entrants]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Spanish male singers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Miami]]\n[[Category:Spanish Roman Catholics]]\n[