{"title_page": "Alessio Bidoli", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|reason=Persistent [[WP:Disruptive editing|disruptive editing]]|small=yes}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{COI|date=April 2020}}\n{{Notability|Music|date=April 2020}}\n{{advert|date=October 2019}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name        = Alessio Bidoli\n| image = Alessio Bidoli e Bruno Canino (Ivrea SMC records studio).jpg\n| alt       = \n| caption      = \n| image_size     = \n| background     = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name     = \n| alias       = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1986|08|18}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|1986|08|18}} (death date then birth) -->\n| origin       = \n| instrument     = Violin\n| genre       = [[Classical music|Classical]]\n| occupation     = \n| years_active    = \n| label       = \n| associated_acts  = \n| website      = {{url|http://www.alessiobidoli.com}}\n}}\n'''Alessio Bidoli''' (born 1986) is an Italian violinist.  <ref>https://www.7giorni.info/cultura/peschiera-borromeo/il-talento-peschierese-alessio-bidoli-si-esibira-al-teatro-cinema-de-sica.html</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Musical education===\nShe was introduced to music with piano studies at age 6; in the following years, he began studying the violin. Even in the early years, he began to perform publicly as a soloist, participating in and winning numerous national competitions. <ref>https://www.universalmusic.it/musica-classica/artista/alessio-bidoli_33761664456/ </ref> At age 21, she was admitted at the Haute Ecole de Musique de Lausanne and Mozarteum (Salzburg) under Pierre Amoyal , and then the [[Accademia Musicale Chigiana]] in Siena, where she was trained by Master [[Salvatore Accardo]].<ref>http://www.mitosettembremusica.it/sites/default/files/2019-05/30_alessio_bidoli_san_fedele_scheda_web_print.pdf</ref>\nAt age 20, he graduated from the Verdi Conservatory in [[Milan]] with highest marks and honors. He then received a specialization diploma for violin from the International Piano Academy \"Incontri col Maestro\" in Imola.<ref>https://www.mywhere.it/70627/alessio-bidoli-chamber-works-nino-rota.html</ref>\n\n===Career===\n\n\nHe performed and collaborated with international musicians such as [[Bruno Canino]], [[Pierre Amoyal]], Irene Veneziano,Massimo Mercelli and many others. <ref>https://open.spotify.com/artist/1ojJIJOWiOBM7BS2gAc3Ld</ref>\nHe has featured with [[Vittorio Sgarbi]] in the theatre project Il Fin la Maraviglia, an account of the Baroque age via images and sounds, which was performed at the theatre in Chiasso (Switzerland) in 2015.<ref>https://luganoeventi.ch/it/eventi/25985/il-fin-la-maraviglia</ref>\nIn April 2009, he was struck down by a viral infection that led to his becoming tetraplegic, arising from Guillain-Barr\u00e9 Syndrome, but he succeeded in playing the violin again two years later, despite his medical prognosis<ref>https://www.corriere.it/buone-notizie/cards/natale-neurochirurgo-italiano-che-salva-bambini-kirgizi-5-storie-corriere/alessio-violino-nonno_principale.shtml</ref>\nBidoli has appeared as guest artist in radio broadcasts on Radio France, NDR Kultur, Radio Svizzera Italiana, RAI Radio 3<ref>https://www.raiplayradio.it/audio/2018/11/PRIMO--MOVIMENTO-5662aef6-580d-40dd-bdb0-010036a3d8b6.html</ref>\nRadio Vaticana, Radio Classica, and Radio Popolare.\n\n==Recordings==\n\n\u2022 2019 Alessio Bidoli (violin) and Bruno Canino (piano) - \"Verdi Fantasias\", Concerto Classics\n\n\u2022 2018 Alessio Bidoli (violin) and Bruno Canino (piano) - Saint Sa\u00ebns Violin Sonatas, Warner Classics\n\n\u2022 2017 Alessio Bidoli (violin) and Bruno Canino (piano) - Poulenc / Ravel / Stravinsky / Prokofiev, Warner Classics\n\n\u2022 2016 Alessio Bidoli (violin) and Bruno Canino (piano) - \"Italian Soul - Anima italiana\", Sony Classical\n\n\u2022 2013 Alessio Bidoli (violin) and Bruno Canino (piano) - \"Verdi Fantasias\", Sony Classical\n\n\u2022 2011 Alessio Bidoli (violin) and Stefania Mormone (piano) - Saint-Sa\u00ebns / Wieniawski / Grieg / Ponce / Elgar / Debussy, Amadeus\n\n==Instruments==\n\n\nAlessio Bidoli plays one of the violins made by his grandfather, Dante Regazzoni, a Lombard violin-maker whose workshop is now part of the Museo della Liuteria (MUSA) at the Accademia Nazionle di Santa Cecilia, Rome. <ref>https://amadeusmagazine.it/rubrica-news/in-un-cd-tutto-saint-saens-per-violino-e-pianoforte-con-il-duo-bidoli-canino/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.alessiobidoli.com Alessio Bidoli official website]\n\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bidoli, Alessio}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Milan]]\n[[Category:Italian classical violinists]]\n[[Category:Male violinists]]\n[[Category:21st-century classical violinists]]\n[[Category:21st-century male musicians]]\n\n\n{{violinist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|reason=Persistent [[WP:Disruptive editing|disruptive editing]]|small=yes}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{COI|date=April 2020}}\n{{Notability|Music|date=April 2020}}\n{{advert|date=October 2019}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name        = Alessio Bidoli\n| image = Alessio Bidoli e Bruno Canino (Ivrea SMC records studio).jpg\n| alt       = \n| caption      = \n| image_size     = \n| background     = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name     = \n| alias       = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1986|08|18}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|1986|08|18}} (death date then birth) -->\n| origin       = \n| instrument     = Violin\n| genre       = [[Classical music|Classical]]\n| occupation     = \n| years_active    = \n| label       = \n| associated_acts  = \n| website      = {{url|http://www.alessiobidoli.com}}\n}}\n'''Alessio Bidoli''' (born 1986) is a Italian violinist.  <ref>https://www.7giorni.info/cultura/peschiera-borromeo/il-talento-peschierese-alessio-bidoli-si-esibira-al-teatro-cinema-de-sica.html</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Musical education===\nShe was introduced to music with piano studies at age 6; in the following years, he began studying the violin. Even in the early years, he began to perform publicly as a soloist, participating in and winning numerous national competitions. <ref>https://www.universalmusic.it/musica-classica/artista/alessio-bidoli_33761664456/ </ref> At age 21, she was admitted at the Haute Ecole de Musique de Lausanne and Mozarteum (Salzburg) under Pierre Amoyal , and then the [[Accademia Musicale Chigiana]] in Siena, where she was trained by Master [[Salvatore Accardo]].<ref>http://www.mitosettembremusica.it/sites/default/files/2019-05/30_alessio_bidoli_san_fedele_scheda_web_print.pdf</ref>\nAt age 20, he graduated from the Verdi Conservatory in [[Milan]] with highest marks and honors. He then received a specialization diploma for violin from the International Piano Academy \"Incontri col Maestro\" in Imola.<ref>https://www.mywhere.it/70627/alessio-bidoli-chamber-works-nino-rota.html</ref>\n\n===Career===\n\n\nHe performed and collaborated with international musicians such as [[Bruno Canino]], [[Pierre Amoyal]], Irene Veneziano,Massimo Mercelli and many others. <ref>https://open.spotify.com/artist/1ojJIJOWiOBM7BS2gAc3Ld</ref>\nHe has featured with [[Vittorio Sgarbi]] in the theatre project Il Fin la Maraviglia, an account of the Baroque age via images and sounds, which was performed at the theatre in Chiasso (Switzerland) in 2015.<ref>https://luganoeventi.ch/it/eventi/25985/il-fin-la-maraviglia</ref>\nIn April 2009, he was struck down by a viral infection that led to his becoming tetraplegic, arising from Guillain-Barr\u00e9 Syndrome, but he succeeded in playing the violin again two years later, despite his medical prognosis<ref>https://www.corriere.it/buone-notizie/cards/natale-neurochirurgo-italiano-che-salva-bambini-kirgizi-5-storie-corriere/alessio-violino-nonno_principale.shtml</ref>\nBidoli has appeared as guest artist in radio broadcasts on Radio France, NDR Kultur, Radio Svizzera Italiana, RAI Radio 3<ref>https://www.raiplayradio.it/audio/2018/11/PRIMO--MOVIMENTO-5662aef6-580d-40dd-bdb0-010036a3d8b6.html</ref>\nRadio Vaticana, Radio Classica, and Radio Popolare.\n\n==Recordings==\n\n\u2022 2019 Alessio Bidoli (violin) and Bruno Canino (piano) - \"Verdi Fantasias\", Concerto Classics\n\n\u2022 2018 Alessio Bidoli (violin) and Bruno Canino (piano) - Saint Sa\u00ebns Violin Sonatas, Warner Classics\n\n\u2022 2017 Alessio Bidoli (violin) and Bruno Canino (piano) - Poulenc / Ravel / Stravinsky / Prokofiev, Warner Classics\n\n\u2022 2016 Alessio Bidoli (violin) and Bruno Canino (piano) - \"Italian Soul - Anima italiana\", Sony Classical\n\n\u2022 2013 Alessio Bidoli (violin) and Bruno Canino (piano) - \"Verdi Fantasias\", Sony Classical\n\n\u2022 2011 Alessio Bidoli (violin) and Stefania Mormone (piano) - Saint-Sa\u00ebns / Wieniawski / Grieg / Ponce / Elgar / Debussy, Amadeus\n\n==Instruments==\n\n\nAlessio Bidoli plays one of the violins made by his grandfather, Dante Regazzoni, a Lombard violin-maker whose workshop is now part of the Museo della Liuteria (MUSA) at the Accademia Nazionle di Santa Cecilia, Rome. <ref>https://amadeusmagazine.it/rubrica-news/in-un-cd-tutto-saint-saens-per-violino-e-pianoforte-con-il-duo-bidoli-canino/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.alessiobidoli.com Alessio Bidoli official website]\n\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bidoli, Alessio}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Milan]]\n[[Category:Italian classical violinists]]\n[[Category:Male violinists]]\n[[Category:21st-century classical violinists]]\n[[Category:21st-century male musicians]]\n\n\n{{violinist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Orenburg1", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alessio_Bidoli"}
{"title_page": "Mandolin playing traditions worldwide", "text_new": "{{short description|Global traditions of playing the mandolin}}\n[[File:Giuseppe Pettine in 1898.jpg|upright|right|thumb|Italian mandolin virtuoso and child prodigy [[Giuseppe Pettine]] (here pictured in 1898) brought the Italian playing style to America where he settled in Providence, Rhode Island, as a mandolin teacher and composer. Pettine is credited with promoting a style where \"one player plays both the rhythmic chords and the lyric melodic line at once, combining single strokes and tremolo.\"<ref name=academicpaper>{{cite journal\n |ref              = {{sfnref|Dickson}}\n |author           = Jean Dickson, University at Buffalo (SUNY)\n |title            = Mandolin Mania in Buffalo\u2019s Italian Community, 1895 to 1918\n |url              = http://wings.buffalo.edu/research/anthrogis/oldsite/JWA/V2N2/Dickson-art.pdf\n |journal          = Journal of World Anthropology: Occasional Papers<!-- : Volume II, Number 2 -->\n |volume           = II\n |issue            = 2\n |publication-date = 2006\n |pages            = 1\u201315\n |access-date      = 2015-03-30\n |archive-url      = https://web.archive.org/web/20150402143811/http://wings.buffalo.edu/research/anthrogis/oldsite/JWA/V2N2/Dickson-art.pdf\n |archive-date     = 2015-04-02\n |url-status         = dead\n}}</ref>]]\nFollowing its invention and development in Italy the [[mandolin]] spread throughout the European continent. The instrument was primarily used in a classical tradition with [[mandolin orchestra]]s, so called ''Estudiantinas'' or in Germany ''Zupforchestern'', appearing in many cities. Following this continental popularity of the mandolin family, local traditions appeared outside Europe in the Americas and in Japan. Travelling mandolin virtuosi like [[Giuseppe Pettine]], [[Raffaele Calace]] and [[Silvio Ranieri]] contributed to the mandolin becoming a \"fad\" instrument in the early 20th century.<ref name=academicpaper/> This \"mandolin craze\" was fading by the 1930s, but just as this practice was falling into disuse, the mandolin found a new niche in American [[country music|country]], [[old-time music]], [[Bluegrass music|bluegrass]] and [[folk music]]. More recently, the [[Baroque]] and [[Classical music|Classical]] mandolin repertory and styles have benefited from the raised awareness of and interest in [[Early music]], with media attention to classical players such as Israeli [[Avi Avital]], Italian [[Carlo Aonzo]] and American [[Joseph Brent]].\n\nSee also: [[History of the mandolin]]\n\n== Algeria ==\n\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n | align = right\n | image1 = Karim tizouiar.jpg\n | width1 = 176\n | alt1 = Karim Tizouiar with a mandole\n | caption1 = Karim Tizouiar with a mandole. His music helps to preserve and revive the [[Amazigh]] language and its heritage.\n\n | image2 =Abderrahmane Abdelli.jpg\n | width2 = 99\n | alt2 = Abderrahmane Abdelli with Algerian mandole\n | caption2  = [[Abderrahmane Abdelli]] with Algerian mandole\n}}\n\nAlgeria was colonized by the French in the 19th century and there were large numbers of Europeans living there during the mandolin's golden age. Mandolins and larger members of the mandolin family were used in orchestras, including orchestras playing native Algerian music. With the decline of the mandolin worldwide, the mandolin became less common until by the 21st century it was rare. However, mandolins and [[mandolas]] are still occasionally made by luthiers. The major mandolin-family instrument in use today is the mandocello-sized [[mondol]] or \"mandole\" (French word for mandola applied to the new instrument). The flatback instrument was the result of a corroboration between an Italian luthier and an Algerian musician and was used initially for [[Chaabi]]. It has since spread to other music forms. Prominent players today include [[Mohamed Rouane]], [[Takfarinas]], Mohamed Abdennour (P'tit Moh), [[Abderrahmane Abdelli]] and Kader Fahem. Past players include [[El Hadj M'Hamed El Anka]], [[Boudjemaa El Ankis]], [[El Hachemi Guerouabi]], [[Amar Ezzahi]], [[Cheikh El Hasnaoui]], and [[Loun\u00e8s Matoub]]. The mondol received some international attention on the movie ''El Gusto'' a featuring the reunion of some chaabi players (including a mondol player) years after the turmoil in Algeria came out in the 2010s.\n\n== Australia ==\n:[[:Category:Australian mandolinists|See Australian mandolinists]]\nThe earliest references to the mandolin in [[Australia]] come from [[Phil Skinner]] (1903\u20131991). In his article \"Recollections\"<ref name=\"Skinner\">Recollections - by Phil Skinner.  FIGA magazine January February 1981 (Fretted Instrument Guild of America)</ref> he mentions a [[Walter Stent]], who was \"active in the early part of the century and organised possibly the first Mandolin Orchestra in [[Sydney]].\"\n\nPhil Skinner played a key role in 20th century development of the mandolin movement in Australia, and was awarded an MBE in 1979 for services to music and the community. He was born Harry Skinner in Sydney in 1903 and started learning [[music]] at age 10 when his uncle tutored him on the [[banjo]]. Skinner began teaching part-time at age 18, until the [[Great Depression]] forced him to begin teaching full-time and learn a broader range of instruments. Skinner founded the Sydney Mandolin Orchestra, the oldest surviving mandolin orchestra in [[Australia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fame.asn.au/sydney/history.htm|title=The Sydney Mandolin Orchestra - history|website=Web.archive.org|accessdate=21 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227174540/http://www.fame.asn.au/sydney/history.htm|archivedate=27 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Sydney Mandolins (Artistic Director: Adrian Hooper) have contributed greatly to the repertoire through commissioning over 200 works by Australian and International composers. Most of these works have been released on Compact Disks and can regularly be heard on radio stations on the ABC and MBS networks. One of their members, mandolin virtuoso Paul Hooper, has had a number of Concertos written for him by composers such as Eric Gross. He has performed and recorded these works with the Sydney Symphony Orchestra and the Tasmanian Symphony Orchestra. As well, Paul Hooper has had many solo works dedicated to him by Australian composers e.g., Caroline Szeto, Larry Sitsky and Michael Smetanin, as well as other works by Robert Allworth and Betty Beath.<!--I trimmed some detail from this that was too off point for the article.-->\n\nIn January 1979, the [[Federation of Australian Mandolin Ensembles]] (FAME) Inc. formed. [[Bruce Morey]] from [[Melbourne]] is the first FAME President. An Australian Mandolin Orchestra toured [[Germany]] in May 1980.\n\nAustralian popular groups such as [[My Friend The Chocolate Cake]] use the mandolin extensively. [[The McClymonts]] also use the mandolin, as do [[Mic Conway|Mic Conway's National Junk Band]] and [[the Blue Tongue Lizards]]. Nevertheless, in folk and traditional styles, the mandolin remains more popular in [[Irish Music]] and other traditional repertoires.\n\n==Austria==\nAs the capital of an empire bordering Italy, musicians traveled to Vienna to work, compose and teach. Vienna was \"the centre for the cultivation of mandolin playing\" in the last part of the 18th century, and music written for mandolin has been preserved there.<ref name=WolkiHistory2>{{cite book |last= W\u00f6lki |first=Konrad |translator-last1= Harris|translator-first1= Keith |date=1984 |title=Geschichte der Mandoline |trans-title= History of the Mandolin |url= |language= English|location= Arlington, Virginia|publisher= Plucked String |page=10 |isbn= |author-link= }}</ref> Composers and players who worked there or whose works have been preserved include [[Leonhard von Call|Leonhard d'Call]], [[Georg Druschetzky]], [[Giovanni Giuliani]], [[Giovanni Hoffmann]], [[Leopold Kozeluch]], [[Karl Stefan Aichelburg|Aichelbourgh]], Giuseppe Blesber, Conrad Schlick (husband to [[Regina Strinasacchi]], [[Leopold Neuhauser]], Vincent Neuling.<ref name=WolkiHistory2/>\n\n== Belgium ==\nIn the early 20th century several mandolin orchestras (Estudiantinas) were active in Belgium. Today only a few groups remain: [http://mandolin.be/ Royal Estudiantina la Napolitaine] (founded in 1904) in [[Antwerp]], [http://brasschaatsmandolineorkest.be/ Brasschaats mandoline orkest] in [[Brasschaat]], the Brugs mandolinegezelschap, the Mandolineclub De Krikskes (Berchem), the Cercle royal des mandolinistes Estudiantina in [[Mons|Mons (Bergen)]], the K\u00f6niglichen Mandolinenorchester Eupen, [https://www.nassognemandoline.be/ the Ensemble de plectres de Nassogne] and the [http://www.mandoline.be/ Cercle royal des mandolinistes de Malmedy].\n\nGerda Abts is a well known mandolin virtuoso in Belgium. She is also mandolin teacher and gives lessons in the music academies of Lier, Wijnegem and Brasschaat. She is now also professor mandolin at the music high school \u201cKoninklijk Conservatorium Artesis Hogeschool Antwerpen\u201d. She also gives various concerts each year in different ensembles. She is in close contact to the Brasschaat mandolin Orchestra. Her site is www.gevoeligesnaar.be\n\n== Brazil ==\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n | align = right\n | image1 = Hamilton de Holanda 25\u00ba Premio da Musica Brasileira(0).jpg\n | width1 = 224\n | alt1 =  Brazilian Mandolin virtuoso Hamilton de Holanda playing a ten-string ''bandolim''\n | caption1 =  Brazilian Mandolin virtuoso Hamilton de Holanda playing a ten-string ''bandolim''.\n\n | image2 =Armandinho - MinC - Comit\u00ea do Patrim\u00f4nio Mundial (19).jpg\n | width2 = 126\n | alt2 = Armandinho (Brazilian guitarist) with bandolim or mandolin\n | caption2  =  Brazilian guitarist [[Armandinho (Brazilian guitarist)|Armandinho]] playing a bandolim.\n}}\n:[[:Category:Brazilian mandolinists|See Brazilian mandolinists]]\n:See also the [[Portuguese guitar]] and [[Portuguese music]].\n\nThe mandolin has a particular shape in [[Brazil]]ian music and is known as the ''bandolim'' in the [[Portuguese language]], which is spoken there. The Portuguese have a long tradition of mandolins and mandolin-like instruments and brought their music to their colonies.\n\nIn modern Brazilian music, the bandolim is almost exclusively a melody instrument, often accompanied by the chordal accompaniment of the [[cavaquinho]], a steel stringed instrument similar to a [[ukulele]]. The bandolim's popularity has risen and fallen with instrumental folk music styles, especially [[choro]]. The later part of the 20th century saw a renaissance of choro in Brazil, and with it, a revival of the country's mandolin tradition. Composer and mandolin virtuoso, [[Jacob do Bandolim]], did much to popularize the instrument through many recordings, and his influence continues to the present day. Some contemporary mandolin players in Brazil include Jacob's disciple [[D\u00e9o Rian]], and [[Hamilton de Holanda]] (the former, a traditional choro-style player, the latter an eclectic innovator.) Another is [[Joel Nascimento]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cliquemusic.uol.com.br/artistas/ver/joel-nascimento|title=Joel Nascimento|author=|date=|website=CliqueMusic.uol.com.br|accessdate=2014-05-30}}</ref>\n\n== China ==\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n | align = left\n | image1 = Liangyou 045 cover - Guan Zilan.jpg\n | width1 = 160\n | alt1 =  Guan Zilan on the cover of Liangyou magazine #45\n | caption1 = 1930 cover of the Chinese magazine ''Li\u00e1ngy\u01d2u'' (''[[The Young Companion]]'') with Chinese painter [[Guan Zilan]] playing a mandolin.\n | image2 =Shanghai-girls-chinese-posters.jpg\n | width2 = 130\n | alt2 = Chinese girl playing mandolin\n | caption2  = Advertising poster for the East Asian Cigarette Company c.&nbsp;1930s, with a girl playing a mandolin.\n}}\n\nWestern instruments such as the guitar, mandolin and ukulele were \"associated with youth and freedom\", \"sophistication and cosmopolitanism\" in Shanghai and Hong Kong in the 1920s and 1930s.<ref name=worldstring>{{cite web |url= http://worldonastringblog.blogspot.com/2012/12/guitars-come-to-china.html?m=1 |title=The First Comes to China |last=Millward |first= Jom|date=30 December 2012 |website= |publisher= |access-date= 26 June 2018|quote=}}</ref>  They appeared in the hands of movie stars and in magazines like [[Ling Long]] with \"fashionable young ladies,\" where they became part of the [[modern girl]] image.<ref name=worldstring/> Modern girls were  college-age women, perceived as active and modern.<ref name=socialmandolin>{{cite web |url= http://wemedia.ifeng.com/6088742/wemedia.shtml|title=\u522b\u627e\u4e86\uff0c\u7f8e\u5973\u90fd\u5728\u8fd9\u513f\u5462\uff0c\u6709\u989c\u6709\u8170\u8fd8\u6709\u817f [translation:  Don't look for it. Beautiful women are here.] |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= |publisher= |access-date=22 June 2018 |quote=[illustration with mandolin is 12th image down] ...characterized by the exquisite water-jet brushing of the Western style...content is mainly about women's social life, such as the campus activities of female college students, women driving motorcycles, swimming, horse riding, horse racing, rowing competitions, and participating in social assistance...no longer important to have advertisements in the 40s. What is important is the United States}}</ref>  Independent and westernized, they  engaged in western recreational activities such as \"driving motorcycles, swimming, horse riding, horse racing, rowing competitions,\" and playing musical instruments.<ref name=socialmandolin/>\n\nArtist Guan Zilan was one such modern girl, educated in Chinese and Japanese colleges.<ref name=moderngirljapan>{{cite book |last=Ikeda |first=Shinobu |chapter=The Allure of a 'Woman in Chinese Dress' |editor-last1=Croissant |editor-first1=Doris |editor-last2=Yeh |editor-first2=Catherine Vance |editor-last3=Mostow |editor-first3=Joshua Scott |title=Performing \"Nation\": Gender Politics in Literature, Theater, and the Visual Arts of China and Japan, 1880\u20131940 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9fNTyTgKRaMC&pg=PA367 |year=2008 |publisher=BRILL |isbn=90-04-17019-7 |page=367}}</ref> Her artwork was displayed in ''The Young Companion'' magazine, and she herself was on the cover with her mandolin.<ref>{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Art style \"Friends\" Illustrated |url= http://cnarts.net/cweb/Exhibition/show/xuanyan/wz-19.asp|magazine= The Young Companion (Li\u00e1ngy\u01d2u pictorial)|location= |publisher= |date= |access-date= 28 June 2018|quote=\"Best Friends\", Issue 57, 1930, \"Ms. Guan Zilan's Personal Exhibition\" Special Edition Liangyou Magazine Co., Ltd.}}</ref>\n\nMandolins were also seen in Shanghai in an advertisement poster of the East Asia Cigarette Company, which showed a woman, well-dressed, holding a mandolin.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.1930shanghai.com/items/90802/Lady-playing-Musical-Instrument-Poster|title=1930 Shanghai and more, Lady playing Musical Instrument Poster |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= 1930shanghai.com|publisher= |access-date= 22 June 2018|quote=advertisement poster from 1930 Shanghai era is a cigarette advertisement for \"East Asia Cigarette Company\".}}</ref> A variation of this image was used elsewhere as a calendar illustration.<ref>{{cite web |url=  http://www.sohu.com/a/191045047_781133|title=\u8001\u4e0a\u6d77\u753b\u7247\u91cc\u7684\u6c11\u56fd\u7f8e\u5973 [translation: The beauty of the Republic of China in old Shanghai paintings]|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= sohu.com|publisher= |access-date=22 June 2018 |quote=[illustration, 27th image down] Foreign capitalists quickly learned from the use of the \u201ccalendar painting\u201d style with calendar solar terms in Chinese traditional folk paintings and incorporated them into product advertisements...a record of the side of an era of the Republic of China (1912-1949)}}</ref>\n\nAlthough prominent in media in the hands of women, the instruments were not solely women's. Young men in western-run schools could choose them up as part of their education. Trying to be like his brother, [[Chou Wen-Chung]] was able to \"dabble in\" the mandolin at a school in [[Nanjing]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Chang |first= Peter M.|date= 2006 |title=Chou Wen-Chung: The Life and Work of a Contemporary Chinese-born American Composer |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=n2cazQcTvBsC&lpg=PA16&dq=shanghai%20mandolin&pg=PA16#v=onepage&q=shanghai%20mandolin&f=false |location= |publisher= Scarecrow Press |chapter=2 |page=16 |isbn= |author-link= }}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1920s and 30s when the mandolin came to China, its popularity had peaked worldwide. Although the imported western instruments never became common in China, they were advertised for sale in Shanghai in 1920, in English-language publications, such as  ''Our Navy, the Standard Publication of the U.S. Navy''.<ref name=navychina>{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Everything Musical, Go to Moutrie's|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=FIM9AQAAMAAJ&lpg=RA5-PA49&dq=shanghai%20mandolin&pg=RA5-PA50#v=onepage&q&f=false|magazine= Our Navy, the Standard Publication of the U.S. Navy|location= |publisher= |date= 1920 |access-date= 26 June 2018|quote=...For American Banjos,Mandolins, and Guitars...Honking, Shanghai, Tientsin}}</ref> When popularity for the fad began to fade after World War 1, China's neighbor Japan was an exception to that; mandolins were still popular and their use growing. Japan had commercial ties to coastal China, the very area from which the magazines and advertisements arose.\n\nDuring the Chinese Cultural Revolution (1966-1976) it became dangerous in China to stick out from other people. The establishment feared \"the taint of foreign ideas\" and tried to root out   the \u201crepresentatives of the bourgeoisie who have sneaked into ... various spheres of culture.\u201d<ref>{{cite magazine |last= Osnos|first= Evan |date= 6 May 2016|title= The Cost of the Cultural Revolution, Fifty Years Later |url= https://www.newyorker.com/news/daily-comment/the-cost-of-the-cultural-revolution-fifty-years-later/amp |magazine= New Yorker |location= |publisher= |access-date=26 June 2018 }}</ref> Western classical music largely came to an end in China during the Cultural Revolution, when \"listening to Beethoven became a political crime.\"<ref name=culturalrevchina>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/jul/08/after-the-cultural-revolution-what-western-classical-music-means-in-china |title=After the Cultural Revolution: what western classical music means in China |last= Thien|first= Madeleine |date=8 July 2016 |website= |publisher= The Guardian|access-date= 23 June 2018|quote=}}</ref> At the Shanghai Conservatory of Music, western musical instruments were destroyed.<ref name=culturalrevchina/>\n\n== Croatia ==\n[[File:Young-woman-with-a-mandolin-vekoslav-karas.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Painting by [[Croatia|Croation]] painter [[Vjekoslav Karas]], c.&nbsp;1845-1847. ''Rimljanka s lutnjom'' (''A romance with a lullabies'').]]\n\nThe mandolin is staple of folk and traditional music on the Croatian coast.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mandolincafe.com/forum/archive/index.php/t-102279.html |title=Croatian luthier introduction (forum discussion) |last1=Glas |first1=Kruno |last2= |first2= |date=13 January 2014 |website=mandolincafe.com |publisher=Mandolin Cafe |accessdate=2016-10-11 |quote=Mandolins are most popular in the coastal area of Croatia and not so much inland because in the 90s the focus was on tamburitza. So, mandolin was a bit neglected.}}</ref> Croatian painter [[Vjekoslav Karas]] (1821-1858) painted an image of a girl playing a mandolin in about 1845.\n\n== Czech and Slovak republics ==\n:[[:Category:Czech mandolinists|See Czech mandolinists]], [[Czech bluegrass]]\nFrom Italy mandolin music extended in popularity throughout Europe in the early 20th century, with mandolin orchestras appearing throughout the continent.\n\nIn the 21st century an increased interest in [[bluegrass music]], especially in Central European countries such as the [[Czech Republic]] and [[Slovakia|Slovak Republic]], has inspired many new mandolin players and builders. These players often mix traditional folk elements with bluegrass. Radim Zenkl came from this tradition, emigrating to the United States, where he has played with U.S. stars, including [[David Grisman]] and [[B\u00e9la Fleck]].\n\n== Finland ==\n[[File:Finnish mandolin makers.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Finnish soldiers from 1943 with 12-string mandolins. One of the soldiers, Private T\u00f6rr\u00f6nen was credited as the luthier.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mandolincafe.com/forum/threads/101928-Finnish-1943-mandolins-from-a-public-war-history-photo-collection |title=Finnish 1943 mandolins from a public war history photo collection |website=Mandolin Cafe Forum |accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> Mandolin in bottom left is strung.]]\n\nFinland has mandolin players rooted in the folk music scene. Prominent names include Petri Hakala, Seppo Sillanp\u00e4\u00e4 and Heikki Lahti, who have taught and recorded albums. Classical music is also represented with players such as Risto Aalto.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.mandolincafe.com/forum/showthread.php?92168-Finnish-mandolin-players-playing-Chris-Thile-s-music-Bach-etc |title= Finnish mandolin players playing Chris Thile's music, Bach etc.|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= January 2013 |website=mandolincafe.com |publisher= |access-date= 28 May 2018 |quote=}}</ref> A Finnish immigrant to the United States [[Arthur Kylander]] became a recording contract there in 1927, releasing 20 recordings with Victor Records, playing mandolin.\n\n== France ==\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n | align = right\n | image2 = Woman holding a mandolin by Kuroda Seiki (Kuroda Kinenkan).jpg\n | width2 = 141\n | alt2 = Woman holding a mandolin, by Kuroda Seiki\n | caption2 = Painting by [[Kuroda Seiki]], ''Woman holding a mandolin'', 1891. He was a Japanese painter living in France.\n\n| image3 =Scribner's magazine (1887) (14801544383).jpg\n | width3 = 170\n | alt3 = Charles Auguste \u00c9mile Durand, Poet with Mandolin\n | caption3  = Painting by [[Carolus-Duran|Charles Auguste \u00c9mile Durand]], ''The Poet with the Mandolin'', published in [[Scribner's Magazine]], 1887.\n}}\n\nIn the 21st century, some have perceived a \"rebirth\" of the mandolin in France.<ref name=castellar>{{cite web |url= https://www.festivalmandoline.fr/a-propos/la-mandoline/ |title= Festival International de Mandoline de Castellar Du 17 au 20 juillet 2019|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= festivalmandoline.fr|publisher= |access-date= 27 April 2019 |quote=}}</ref> Although an \"Italian\" instrument, France had a history with the mandolin family going back centuries, to the [[gittern]]s (12th-14th centuries), and the [[mandore (instrument)|mandore]] arrived from Spain about 1570.<ref name=castellar/> One of the earliest surviving books of mandore music, the ''Music Tablature of Fran\u00e7ois de Chancey'' was published in 1629 and featured music for the French court.<ref name=castellar/> It was dedicated to the [[Cardinal Richelieu|Duke of Richelieu]], Prime Minister of [[Louis XIII]].<ref name=castellar/>\n\nPrior to the ''Golden Age of Mandolins'', France had a history with the mandolin, with mandolinists playing in Paris until the Napoleonic Wars.<ref name=\"Sparks1\">{{harvnb|Sparks|2003|page=1}}</ref>  The players, teachers and composers included [[Giovanni Fouchetti]], [[Eduardo Mezzacapo]], [[Gabriele Leone]], and [[Giovanni Battista Gervasio]].<ref name=\"Sparks98-109\">{{harvnb|Sparks|2003|page=98\u2013109}}</ref> From the mid 1750s until the Napoleanic War, virtuosos traveled Europe, performing, teaching and composing, many settling in France. Leone settled in Paris, Gervasio in [[Grenoble]]. Beginning with the French Revolution, the instrument declined from formal performance and \"eclypsed\" by 1820.<ref name=castellar/> It was rediscovered when the Spanish Students came to Paris for the Carnival of 1878. This was the beginning of the \"Golden Age\" of mandolins. During the Golden age itself (1880s-1920s), the mandolin had a strong presence in France. By the beginning of the 20th century, Paris had at least 30 mandolin orchestras.<ref name=castellar/> Prominent mandolin players or composers included [[Jules Cottin]] and his sister Madeleine Cottin, Jean Pietrapertosa, and [[Edgar Bara]].<ref name=\"Sparks98-109\"/> Paris had dozens of \"estudiantina\" mandolin orchestras in the early 1900s.<ref name=\"Sparks98-109\"/> Mandolin magazines included ''L'Estudiantina'', ''Le Plectre'', ''\u00c9cole de la mandolie''.<ref name=\"Sparks98-109\"/>\n\nWorld War I marks the end of the golden age, as a \"wave of American music at the Liberation buried the mandolin orchestras.\"<ref name=castellar/>\n\nIn the 21st century, interest in Baroque music has inspired a revival of concert mandolins for classical music, as musicians have begun rediscovering the \"great reperatoire.\"<ref name=castellar/> Partly this has been fed by the classical mandolin music tradition, preserved in Japan and Korea.<ref name=castellar/> French culture accepts music from around the globe, including former colonies \u2014 the [[Maghreb]].<ref name=castellar/> Algeria in particular had a mandolin culture and created its own mandolin family instrument, [[Algerian mandole|the mandole]]. Other mandolin imports to France include Latin music from South America, American bluegrass mandolin, and the \"plectrum instruments\" of Slavic culture.<ref name=castellar/>\n\nToday, French mandolinists include Patrick Vaillant, a prominent modern player, composer and recording artist for the mandolin, who also organizes courses for aspiring players.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mandopolis.org/?p=1419#comments |title=Stage de Mandoline avec Patrick Vaillant, \u00e0 Pigna ! |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= November 26, 2012|website= |publisher= |access-date= September 22, 2015|quote=Partant, am\u00e9liorer ses performances mandolinistiques et \u00e9tendre son domaine musical, acc\u00e9der mieux arm\u00e9 \u00e0 l'improvisation.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.livioufestival.com/patrick-vaillant-daniel-malavergne-2/ |title=Patrick VVaillant and Daniel Malevergna |website= livioufestival.com|publisher= |access-date= September 22, 2015|quote=Son bagage traditionnel, son go\u00fbt de l'improvisation, une inspiration travers\u00e9e de M\u00e9diterran\u00e9e et de jazz, l'originalit\u00e9 de son jeu comme de ses compositions, ont fait de lui un mandoliniste internationalement reconnu}}</ref>\n\n== Germany ==\n[[File:Fotothek df roe-neg 0006329 013 Mandolinenspielerin.jpg|thumb|right|upright|A woman playing a bowlback mandolin in Germany in 1952.]]\n\nThe [[Mandore (instrument)|mandore]] was known in Germany, prior to the invention of the Neapolitan mandolin.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Tyler |first=James |last2= |first2= |date=January 1981 |title=The Mandore in the 16th and 17th Centuries |url=http://le.luth.free.fr/mandore/articles/01-Tyler_mandore.pdf |journal=Early Music |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=2, 3 |doi= 10.1093/earlyj/9.1.22|access-date=21 October 2016|quote=...Under the name quintern the mandore is familiar to us from the illustrations found in Sebastian Virdung's Musica getutscht (1511) and Martin Agricola's Musica Instrumentalis Duedsch (1528)...Praetorius....gives an illustration of a Mandoraen... }}</ref> The mandolin spread to Germany with the visits of Italian mandolin virtuosi, including Achille Coronati.<ref name=germansparks>{{cite book |last=Sparks |first=Paul |date=1995 |title=The Classical Mandolin |url= |location=Oxford |publisher=Clarendon Press |pages=115\u2013117 |isbn=978-0-19-517337-6}}</ref> [[George Frideric Handel]] composed ''[[Alexander Balus]]'' in 1748. When the mandolin declined in much of Europe after the French Revolution, it found some energy in Bohemia, Germany and Vienna.<ref name=castellar/> [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart]] placed it in his 1787 work ''[[Don Giovanni]]'', and Beethoven  [[Beethoven's mandolin|experimented with four compositions]] in 1795 and 1796. [[Johann Nepomuk Hummel]] created a mandolin concerto in 1799 and a mandolin and piano sonata.<ref name=castellar/>\n\nThe mandolin gained popularity as a folk instrument, especially with the groups of youth participating in the [[German youth movement]], which began in 1897.<ref name=germansparks/> In the early 20th century the mandolin was popular in the [[Wandervogel]] movement (groups of young men and women, hiking and camping, singing and playing instruments), due to the instrument's small size.<ref name=germansparks/>\n\nThe mandolin became increasingly popular in contemporary music during the 20th century. An important German composer for mandolin and mandolin orchestra of the 20th century was [[Konrad W\u00f6lki]]; he was instrumental in bringing musicological recognition of the mandolin and the orchestra. Mandolin orchestras are still playing in Germany, in various chamber music ensembles and as a solo instrument. The instrument is popular enough today that there is an increasing number of professional mandolin players and composers writing new works for the mandolin.\n\nAt the college level the mandolin has a presence, in the professorial chair for mandolins, chaired by Caterina Lichtenberg. She succeeded Marga Wilden-H\u00fcsgen at the Hochschule f\u00fcr Musik und Tanz K\u00f6ln, in Wuppertal. Another program with specialized training for students offering a diploma in this instrument takes place by Gertrud Weyhofen at the Music Academy Kassel and more recently at the University of Music Saar and by Steffen Trekel at Hamburg Conservatory.\n\nThe instrument was present in the folk revival of the 1970s. One mandolin player was Erich Schmeckenbecher in the duo ''[[Zupfgeigenhansel]]''. Comedian Hans S\u00fcper played a modified mandolin, which he called his \"Bovec,\" in the duo ''Colonia''.\n\n== Greece ==\nThe mandolin has a long tradition in the [[Ionian Sea|Ionian]] islands (the ''[[Heptanese]]'') and [[Crete]], and later in the Urban centers of Southern Mainland Greece. It has long been played in the [[Aegean Sea|Aegean]] islands outside the control of the [[Ottoman Empire]]. It is common to see [[Cantata#The kantades of the Ionian Islands|choirs accompanied by mandolin players]] (the ''mandolin\u00e1tes'') in the [[Ionian islands]] and especially in the cities of [[Corfu]], [[Zakynthos]], [[Lefkada]] and [[Kefalonia]]. The evolution of the repertoire for choir and mandolins (''kant\u00e1des'') occurred during [[Venice|Venetian]] rule over the islands.\n\nOn the island of [[Crete]], along with the [[Lyra (Cretan)|lyra]] and the laouto ([[lute]]), the mandolin is one of the main instruments used in [[Music of Crete|Cretan Music]]. It appeared on Crete around the time of the Venetian rule of the island. Different variants of the mandolin, such as the \"mantola,\" were used to accompany the lyra, the [[violin]], and the laouto. Stelios Foustalierakis reported that the mandolin and the ''mpoulgari'' were used to accompany the lyra in the beginning of the 20th century in the city of Rethimno. There are also reports that the mandolin was mostly a woman's musical instrument. Nowadays it is played mainly as a solo instrument in personal and family events on the [[Ionian Sea|Ionian]] islands and Crete.\n\n[[Nikolaos Lavdas]] was a significant composer and mandolinists for Greece, who was the founder and director of the \"[https://athenianmandolinata.com/about/ Athenian Mandolinata]\", one of the oldest music associations and music schools in Greece.<ref>{{cite book |title=Art music in the Balkans |last=Shupo |first=Sokol |page=63 |year=2004 |publisher=ASMUS |oclc=443331457 }}</ref>\n\n== India ==\n:[[:Category:Indian mandolinists|See Indian mandolinists]]\n[[File:U. Srinivas.jpg|thumb|right|U. Srinivas]]\nMandolin music was used in Indian movies as far back as the 1940s by the [[Raj Kapoor]] Studios in movies such as [[Barsaat (1949 film)|Barsaat]]. The movie [[Dilwale Dulhania Le Jayenge]] (1995) used mandolin in several places. Bollywood music composer [[Sajjad Hussain (composer)|Ustad Sajjad Hussain]] (1917 \u2013 1995) played the mandolin as a \"Top Grade\" player for the Indian film industry in Mumbai for more than five decades and was reputed to have played more than 22,000 songs, including title-songs and background music.<ref name=Hussain>{{cite web |url= http://meetkalakar.com/Artist/1509-Mustafa-Sajjad-Hussain |title= Mustafa Sajjad Hussain, Mandolin artist|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=Meetkalakar.com |publisher= |access-date= 30 August 2018|quote=}}</ref> Besides the music for movies, he was known to play Indian classical music (Hindustani), as well as Arab and Sufi music.<ref name=Hussain/>\n\nAdoption of the mandolin in [[Carnatic music]] is recent and involves an electric instrument. [[U. Srinivas]] (1969-2014) has, over the last couple of decades, made his version of the mandolin very popular in India and abroad.\n\nMany adaptations of the instrument have been done to cater to the special needs of Indian Carnatic music.\nIn [[Indian classical music]] and Indian light music, the mandolin, which bears little resemblance to the European mandolin, is usually tuned E\u2013B\u2013E\u2013B. As there is no concept of absolute pitch in Indian classical music, any convenient tuning maintaining these relative pitch intervals between the strings can be used. Another prevalent tuning with these intervals is C\u2013G\u2013C\u2013G, which corresponds to ''sa\u2013pa\u2013sa\u2013pa'' in the Indian carnatic classical music style. This tuning corresponds to the way violins are tuned for carnatic classical music. This type of mandolin is also used in [[Bhangra (music)|Bhangra]], dance music popular in Punjabi culture.\n\n[[Uppalapu Rajesh]] is another performer using the mandolin in Indian music, playing Indian classical music, jazz-fusion, and world music. He was nominated for a Grammy in 2009.<ref name=\"CR2\">{{cite news|title= Soul Strings: U Rajesh on the legacy of playing an Italian lute in the Carnatic classical system |url= http://indianexpress.com/article/lifestyle/art-and-culture/u-rajesh-soul-strings-4803160/ |newspaper=[[The Indian Express]] |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180322204500/http://indianexpress.com/article/lifestyle/art-and-culture/u-rajesh-soul-strings-4803160/ |archivedate= 22 March 2018 }}</ref> He is brother to U. Srinivas.\n\n== Ireland ==\n:[[:Category:Irish mandolinists|See Irish mandolinists]]\nThe mandolin has become a more common instrument amongst Irish traditional musicians. Fiddle tunes are readily accessible to the mandolin player because of the equivalent tuning and range of the two instruments, and the practically identical (allowing for the lack of frets on the fiddle) left hand fingerings.\n\nThough almost any variety of acoustic mandolin might be adequate for Irish traditional music, virtually all Irish players prefer flat-backed instruments with oval sound holes to the Italian-style bowl-back mandolins or the carved-top mandolins with f-holes favoured by [[Bluegrass music|bluegrass]] mandolinists. The former are often too soft-toned to hold their own in a session (as well as having a tendency to not stay in place on the player's lap), whilst the latter tend to sound harsh and overbearing to the traditional ear. The f-hole mandolin, however, does come into its own in a traditional session, where its brighter tone cuts through the sonic clutter of a pub. Greatly preferred for formal performance and recording are flat-topped \"Irish-style\" mandolins (reminiscent of the WWI-era Martin Army-Navy mandolin) and carved (arch) top mandolins with oval soundholes, such as the Gibson A-style of the 1920s.\n\nNoteworthy Irish mandolinists include [[Andy Irvine (musician)|Andy Irvine]] (who, like [[Johnny Moynihan]], almost always tunes the top E down to D, to achieve an open tuning of G\u2013D\u2013A\u2013D),<ref name=\"Walsh\">{{cite book|last1=\u00d3 Callanain|first1= Niall|last2=Walsh|first2= Tommy|year=1989|title= The Irish Bouzouki|location=Ireland|publisher= Waltons|isbn= 0-7866-1595-8}}</ref>{{rp|38}} [[Paul Brady]], [[Mick Moloney]], [[Paul Kelly (Irish musician)|Paul Kelly]] and Claudine Langille. [[John Sheahan]] and the late [[Barney McKenna]], respectively fiddle player and tenor banjo player with [[the Dubliners]], are also accomplished Irish mandolin players. The instruments used are either flat-backed, oval hole examples as described above (made by UK luthier Roger Bucknall of Fylde Guitars), or carved-top, oval hole instruments with arched back (made by Stefan Sobell in Northumberland). The Irish guitarist [[Rory Gallagher]] often played the mandolin on stage, and he most famously used it in the song \"Going To My Hometown.\"\n\n== Israel ==\n:[[:Category:Israeli mandolinists|See Israeli mandolinists]]\n\nThe re-founding of Israel after World War II drew people from all across the world. Among them were people from Eastern European countries, where mandolin orchestras had been in use before the war. Researchers, such as Jeff Warschauer have gone to Israel, seeking to preserve klesmer music and Yiddish songs.<ref name=cantor/>\n\nMandolin orchestras were founded in the 1920s in the pioneering settlement in the Jezreel Valley and in the Jordan Valley by a teacher named Goldman. The orchestra in the Jordan Valley continues to operate today.\n\nThe oldest of the mandolin orchestras, which has been continuously active since the 1940s, is the Shfeya Orchestra, founded by Moshe Medalia, and today made up of graduates from the Shfeya Youth Village.<ref name=moshe>{{cite web |url= http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3690289,00.html|title=The student who became a music teacher  |last=Man |first=Nadav |date=23 March 2009 |website=ynetnews.com |publisher= |access-date=29 May 2017 |quote=}}</ref> The village is a boarding school for at-risk junior and senior high-school students.<ref name=school>{{cite web |url=http://www.hadassah.org/connecting-to-israel/youth-aliyah.html |title=Our Villages, Meir Shfeyah |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= hadassah.org|publisher= |access-date= 29 May 2017|quote=}}</ref> Part of the education includes students working together in small groups, teaching music to one another.<ref name=moshe/> There wasn't much in the way of learning materials when Moshe Jacobson, founder of the music program arrived in 1942. So he wrote text books for the instruments and composed music and songs.<ref name=moshe/>\n\n[[Shimon Peres]] was an example of someone who brought his musical background. Peres, (born Szymon Perski), grew up in the then Polish town of [[Vishnyeva]], was part of a mandolin orchestra when he was a child.<ref name=speres>{{cite news | url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/larger-than-life-shimon-peres-a-legacy-in-pictures/ | title=Larger than life: Shimon Peres, a legacy in pictures | newspaper=[[The Times of Israel]] | author=Raphael Ahren | date=2016-09-28 | accessdate=2017-05-29}}</ref>  The Vishnyeva orchestra of which he was part of was immortalized in a black-and-white photography, a group of young people dressed up holding their mandolins.<ref name=speres/> Although busy with his political career, Peres remained musical for the rest of his life, composing songs in his home in Israel.<ref name=\"auto4\">[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/32453580/ns/world_news-wonderful_world/t/poems-turn-song-israeli-ex-leader-turns/#.V-ta_fl97IU Poems turn to song as ex-leader turns 86] AP, updated August 17, 2009 7:55:07 PM ET</ref>\n\nIsrael today has four especially prominent mandolinists: [[Avi Avital]],<ref name=israel1>[http://www.thebluegrassspecial.com/archive/2011/jan2011/bordercrossingjan2011.php Artist To Artist: 10 Minutes With Avi Avital.] ''The Bluegrass Special'', January 2011 by Joe Brent.</ref> Alon Sariel,<ref name=israel2>{{cite web| url=http://www.mandolin.org.uk/interviews/sariel.php| title=Alon Sariel interview| last=| first=| date=| website=Mandolin.org.uk| publisher=| access-date=September 3, 2015| quote=What mandolins do you own? Which one(s) is(are) your favourite(s)? Whoever knows the Beer-Sheva school of mandolin must have heard of the Israeli type of modern mandolins. A mandolin maker called Arik Kerman who lives in Tel-Aviv, invented a formula to make the mandolin in a way for which it has a much of a round and sweet sound, and can easily produce a very soft sound other than the metallic Neapolitan one...}}</ref><ref name=israel3>{{cite web|url=http://www.alon-sariel.com/repertoire/instrumentarium/|title=Instrumentarium|author=|date=|website=Alon Sariel \u2013 mandolinist, conductor, lutenist|accessdate=16 March 2018}}</ref> [[Jacob Reuven]],<ref name=mandoKerman>{{cite web| url=http://www.mandolincafe.com/forum/showthread.php?102738-Avi-Avital-and-the-Arik-Kerman-mandolin| title=Thread: Avi Avital and the Arik Kerman mandolin| last=| first=| date=| website=mandolincafe.com| publisher=| access-date=September 3, 2015| quote=This thread digressed into the topic of Avi's Kerman, where it was established that it has a double top and a convex back. \u2026 it looks like it is based on the modern German flatback as made by makers such as Seifert, a little deep-bodied. The difference from the German models is that it has the sound holes on the edges and, even more important(?) has a double top.}}</ref> and Tom Cohen.<ref name=israel4>{{cite web| url=http://frusion.co.uk/artists/concert/global/Tom_Cohen.html| title=Concert artists: Tom Cohen| last=| first=| date=| website=frusion.co.uk| publisher=| access-date=September 3, 2015| quote=The mandolin that Tom plays was built especially for him by Israeli artist Arik Kerman and new instrument is currently being built for, and inspired by him, by internationally-known luthier Boaz Elkayam.}}</ref> Another is composer [[Shaul Bustan]], whose works include a ''Concerto for Mandolin and Accordion'' (2010) and an arrangement of Mozart's ''Symphony No 40 in G minor'' for mandolin, mandola, guitar and double bass (2014).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shaulbustan.com |title= Shaul Bustan, composer, conductor and multi-instrumentalist |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=Shaulbustan.com |publisher= |access-date=1 July 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n== Italy ==\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n | align = right\n|header=19th-century visitors to Italy capture mandolin in art\n| \n| image3 = Chase William Merritt The Mandolin Player 1878.jpg\n | width3 = 149\n | alt3 = 1924 Gibson F-5 mandolin\n | caption3  = ''The Mandolin Player'' by [[William Merritt Chase]] (1879). He visited Italy 1877-1878. The mandolin in the painting was among his props in the USA.<ref name=globe>{{cite news |last= Guerrieri |first= Matthew|date=20 October 2016 |title= Exotic collection was instrumental for painter William Merritt Chase|url= https://www2.bostonglobe.com/arts/music/2016/10/20/exotic-collection-was-instrumental-for-painter-william-merritt-chase/CxdPlbK0ISoU8doT4AxLfN/story.html|work= Boston Globe|location= Boston, Massachusetts|access-date= 28 April 2019|quote=A few made their way into Chase\u2019s art: \u201cThe Mandolin Player\u201d (1879) plucks Chase\u2019s fanciest specimen, a Spanish instrument with inlaid mother-of-pearl }}</ref>\n\n|image2= Schwarz 1851.jpg\n | width2 = 150\n | alt2 = Gibson A4 mandolin\n | caption2  =Estonia/Russia, ''The Mandolin Player'' by [[Julie Wilhelmine Hagen-Schwarz]], 1851.<ref name=kusnt>{{cite web |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080309083045/http://www.tartmus.ee/et/kogud/schwarz.html |title= Julie Hagen-Schwarz Mandoliinim\u00e4ngija. 1851 \u00d5li, l\u00f5uend. 157 x 106,5|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= liveestonia.com|publisher= |access-date=28 April 2019 |quote=}}</ref> She visited Italy for several years, when this was painted.\n\n | image1 = Duret Vendangeur.jpg\n | width1 = 166\n | alt1 = Painting, Grape-picker Extemporing, by Francisque Joseph Duret, 1839\n | caption1 = French sculptor [[Francisque Joseph Duret]] visited Naples and made ''Grape-picker Extemporizing'' by 1839. The mandolin was a folk instrument for most of the 19th century.\n\n}}\n:[[:Category:Italian mandolinists|See Italian mandolinists]]\nImportant performers in the Italian tradition include [[Raffaele Calace]] (luthier, virtuoso and composer of 180 works for many instruments including mandolin), [[Pietro Denis]] (who also composed ''Sonata for mandolin & continuo No. 1 in D major'' and ''Sonata No. 3''), [[Giovanni Fouchetti]], [[Gabriele Leone]], [[Carlo Munier]] (1859\u20131911), [[Giuseppe Branzoli]] (1835\u20131909), [[Giovanni Gioviale]] (1885\u20131949) and [[Silvio Ranieri]] (1882\u20131956).<ref name=lgma>[http://www.mandolinscotland.org/home/Newsletters/LGMA_SPRING_2007_NEWSLETTER3.pdf Ian Pommerenke, ''The Mandolin in the early to mid 19th Century'', Lanarkshire Guitar and Mandolin Association Newsletter, Spring 2007.]</ref><ref name=lgma2>[http://www.mandolinscotland.org/home/Newsletters/LGMA_November_2006_Newsletter.pdf Ian Pommerenke, ''The Mandolin the early 18th Century'', Lanarkshire Guitar and Mandolin Association Newsletter, November 2006.]</ref>\n\n[[Antonio Vivaldi]] composed a mandolin concerto (''Concerto in C major op.3 no.6'') and two concertos for two mandolins and orchestra.\n\n[[Antonio Maria Bononcini]] composed ''La conquista delle Spagne di Scipione Africano il giovane'' in 1707. Others include [[Giovanni Battista Gervasio]] (''Sonata in D major for Mandolin and Basso Continuo''), [[Giuseppe Giuliano]] (''Sonata in D major for Mandolin and Basso Continuo''), [[Emanuele Barbella]] (''Sonata in D major for Mandolin and Basso Continuo''), [[Domenico Scarlatti]] (''Sonata no.54 (K.89) in D minor for Mandolin and Basso Continuo''), and [[Addiego Guerra]] (''Sonata in G major for Mandolin and Basso Continuo'').<ref name=lgma/><ref name=recording>{{cite AV media |url=http://www.claudiorecords.com/detail/taylor.html |people=Frances Taylor, mandolinist |title=Italian Mandolin Sonatas |via=Claudio Records |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304002201/http://www.claudiorecords.com/detail/taylor.html |archive-date=2016-03-04}}</ref>\n\nMore contemporary composers for the mandolin include [[Giuseppe Anedda]] (a virtuoso performer and teacher of the first chair of the Conservatory of Italian mandolin), [[Carlo Aonzo]] and [[Dorina Frati]].\n\n=== Cultural ghettoization and revival in Naples ===\n\nIn the late 20th century, information on the instrument, especially its history became hard to find in Naples, where there instrument was born.<ref name=foolk>{{cite web |url= http://www.blogfoolk.com/2017/01/splendori-musicali-settecenteschi.html?m=1|title=Splendori musicali settecenteschi, \"Mandolini al Cinema\" e Pink Floyd a pizzico: intervista al maestro e outsider del mandolino Mauro Squillante (translation: Splendors eighteenth-century music, \"Mandolins at the Cinema\" and Pink Floyd to pinch: interview with the teacher and outsiders mandolin Mauro Squillante) |last= De Rosa|first= Ciro|date= 17 January 2017|website= blogfoolk.com|publisher= |access-date=8 July 2017i |quote=}}</ref>\n\nHistorian Konrad W\u00f6lki commented on this in 1939, suggesting that after only 100 years, there was a disturbing ignorance of the mandolin's history among Italian specialists.<ref name=WolkiHistory1>{{cite book |last= W\u00f6lki |first=Konrad |translator-last1= Harris|translator-first1= Keith |date=1984 |title=Geschichte der Mandoline |trans-title= History of the Mandolin |url= |language= English|location= Arlington, Virginia|publisher= Plucked String |page=12 |isbn= |author-link= }}</ref> He felt that mandolinists must have fared better away from home and left \"hardly any evidence of classical Italian mandolin music in Italy itself.\"<ref name=WolkiHistory1/> His lists of places where the mandolin did better include Vienna, France and Germany.<ref name=WolkiHistory1/>\n\nThe term ''cultural ghettoization'' has been used to describe the situation where no information is readily available about the mandolin's history, its luthiers, composers, musicians, and the relationship of the instrument to folk music and the \"classic Neapolitan song\".<ref name=foolk/> Tourists arriving in the city were more likely to find such information elsewhere.<ref name=foolk/> The city had moved on from mandolins and didn't place particular emphasis on remembering their history or place in Neapolitan culture.<ref name=foolk/>\n\nFurthermore, throughout Italy there was a similar slide. By 1992 there was only one active chair remaining for mandolins at the country's conservatories, the Pollini Conservatory of Padua.<ref name=esspr>{{cite web |url=http://www.espressonapoletano.it/il-mandolino-trova-casa/#.WWI0gZ9MEwj |title= \n(Translation: The mandolin is home) |last=Esposito |first=Ornella |date= 8 February 2017|website= Espressonapoletano.it|access-date= 9 July 2017|quote=}}</ref>\n\nSince then there has been some progress made to revive the mandolin and knowledge of it.\n\nProjects to address the lack of visibility of the mandolin and its history include the formation of a Neapolitan Mandolin Association in 1988,  the restarting of the Neapolitan Mandolin Academy in 1992, and the creation of the Mandolin House.<ref name=foolk/>\n\nThe Neapolitan Mandolin Academy is a school in Naples offering a specialized course of study in the mandolin.\n\nThe Mandolin House is a restored house in via Duomo that has room for concerts, and which offers classes to international visitors, as well as serving as an information point for tourists.<ref name=esspr/> The crowdfunded project was in part begun by the efforts of [[Mauro Squillante]] as he tried to revive the mandolin tradition.<ref name=esspr/> He wanted a place in which to give concerts, do training and give exhibitions.<ref name=esspr/>\n\nAnother sign of progress is the growth of the mandolin within the college education system. While in 1992 there was only one active conservatory chair for mandolins, at Padua (instructor [[Dorina Frati]]), today there are also the [[Music conservatories of Naples]], the Conservatorio di Milan (mandolin professor [[Ugo Orlandi]]), the Conservatorio di Musica \"Niccol\u00f2 Piccinni\" in Bari (instructor [[Mauro Squillante]]), the Conservatorio di Musica \"Nicola Sala\" in Benevento (instructor [[Nunzio Reina]]), and conservatories in Palermo, and Salerno as well.<ref name=esspr/><ref name=foolk/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.conservatorio.bn.it/index.php?p=274 |title= MANDOLINO, REINA NUNZIO|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= conservatorio.bn.it|publisher= Conservatorio Statale di Musica Nicola Sala |access-date=10 July 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n== Japan ==\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n | align = right\n | image1 = Poster of Sakura Beer 2 by Kitano Tsunetomi.jpg\n | width1 = 132\n | alt1 = Kitano Tsunetomi artwork on Sakura beer poster\n | caption1 = Japan, 1916, Sakura beer poster with girl playing mandolin. Art by [[Kitano Tsunetomi]].\n\n| image2= Morishige Takei 01.jpg\n | width2 = 150\n | alt2 = Morishige Takei in 1913\n | caption2  =Morishige Takei in 1913. \n}}\n\nInstruments of the mandolin family are popular in Japan, particularly Neapolitan (round-back) style instruments, and Roman-Embergher style mandolins are still being made there.<ref name=Sparks174-177>{{harvnb|Sparks|2003|page=174\u2013177}}</ref> Japan became seriously interested in mandolins at the beginning of the 20th century during a process of becoming westernized.<ref name=Sparks133-134>{{harvnb|Sparks|2003|page=133\u2013134}}</ref> In 1901, musical educator Kimihachi Hiruma (1867-1936) returned home to Japan after studying the mandolin.<ref name=Hiruma>{{cite web |url=https://www.ikegaku.co.jp/freshmandolin_his.htm |title=\u30de\u30f3\u30c9\u30ea\u30f3\u306e\u751f\u307e\u308c\u3068\u4f1d\u6765 (Birth and Inheritance of the Mandolin) |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=ikegaku.co.jp |publisher=ikegaku I Mandolini a congresso |access-date=22 May 2016 |quote=\u672c\u683c\u7684\u306a\u666e\u53ca\u306f\u3001\u6771\u4eac\u97f3\u697d\u5b66\u6821\u306e\u8b1b\u5e2b\u3067\u3042\u3063\u305f\u6bd4\u7559\u9593\u8ce2\u516b(1867-1936)\u304c\u30a4\u30bf\u30ea\u30a2\u4eba\u306e\u30a2\u30c3\u30c6\u30a3\u30ec\u30fb\u30b3\u30eb\u30ca\u30c6\u30a3\u306b\u30de\u30f3\u30c9\u30ea\u30f3\u3092\u5b66\u3093\u30671901\u5e74\u306b\u5e30\u56fd\u3001\u30de\u30f3\u30c9\u30ea\u30f3\u30fb\u30ae\u30bf\u30fc\u587e\u3092\u958b\u3044\u305f\u3053\u3068\u304c\u5951\u6a5f\u3068\u306a\u308a\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002[translation:...Kimihachi Hiruma (1867-1936) who was a lecturer at the Tokyo Music School learned mandolin at Italy's Attila Kornati, returned home in 1901, opened a mandolin / guitar cram school...]  }}</ref> He opened a school and founded a mandolin ensemble in 1905.<ref name=Hiruma/>\n\nWhere interest in the mandolin declined in the United States and parts of Europe after World War I, in Japan there was a boom, with orchestras being formed all over the country.<ref name=\"Sparks133-134\"/>\n\nConnections to the West, including cultural connections with World War II ally Italy, were forming. One musical connection that encouraged mandolin music growth was a visit by mandolin virtuoso [[Raffaele Calace]], who toured extensively at the end of 1924, into 1925, and who gave a performance for the Japanese emperor. Another visiting mandolin virtuoso, Samuel Adelstein, toured from his home in the United States.\n\nThe expansion of mandolin use continued after World War II through the late 1960s, and Japan still maintains a strong classical music tradition using mandolins, with active orchestras and university music programs. New orchestras were founded and new orchestral compositions composed. Japanese mandolin orchestras today may consist of up to 40 or 50 members, and can include woodwind, percussion, and brass sections. Japan also maintains an extensive collection of 20th-century mandolin music from Europe and one of the most complete collections of mandolin magazines from mandolin's golden age, purchased by Morishige Takei.\n\nIn [[Nagoya]] the [[Mandolin Melodies Museum]], founded by mandolin player Hirokazu Nanya, is dedicated to mandolins.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.t-museum.jp/|title=MATSUSHIMA\uff5cThe Museum Matsushima|website=T-museum.jp|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Influential people ====\n[[Morishige Takei]] (1890\u20131949), a member of the court of Emperor [[Hirohito]], established a mandolin orchestra in the Italian style before [[World War II]].<ref name=coldwell>{{cite web |url= http://www.digitalguitararchive.com/2012/02/morishige-takei/|title= Morishige Takei|last= Coldwell|first= Robert|date= 4 February 2012|website= digitalguitararchive.com |publisher= |access-date= 16 April 2018|quote=}}</ref> He was able to maintain his mandolin-guitar orchestra until 1943, in spite of the [[National Mobilization Law]] of 1938 that allowed the government to assert control of music, and ban western music and instruments, including the electric guitar, banjo and ukulele.<ref name=Japan1938>{{cite book |last= Yano|first= Christine Reiko |date= 2003|title= Tears of Longing: Nostalgia and the Nation in Japanese Popular Song|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=SnGY9XQj0ocC&lpg=PA37&dq=National%20%20Mobilization%20Law%20of%201938%2C%20mandolin&pg=PA38#v=onepage&q=National%20%20Mobilization%20Law%20of%201938,%20mandolin&f=false|location= |publisher= Harvard Univ Asia Center|pages= 37\u201338|isbn= 9780674012769|author-link= }}</ref><ref name=coldwell/> He was also a major composer, with 114 compositions for mandolin.\n\nAnother composer, [[Jiro Nakano]] (1902\u20132000), arranged many of the Italian works for regular orchestras or winds composed before World War II as new repertoires for Japanese mandolin orchestras.\n\nOriginal compositions for mandolin orchestras were composed increasingly after World War II. [[Seiichi Suzuki (composer)|Seiichi Suzuki]] (1901\u20131980) composed music for early [[Akira Kurosawa|Kurosawa]] films. Others include Tadashi Hattori (1908\u20132008), and [[Hiroshi Ohguri]] (1918\u20131982). Ohguri was influenced by [[B\u00e9la Bart\u00f3k]] and composed many symphonic works for Japanese mandolin orchestras. [[Yasuo Kuwahara]] (1946\u20132003) used German techniques. Many of his works were published in Germany.\n\n== Jewish Eastern Europe and diaspora ==\nIn Jewish communities in Eastern Europe and North America the mandolin was important in the years before World War II. The modern Ger Mandolin Orchestra website explained the importance, calling mandolins a \"quintessential Jewish musical form... Mandolin clubs and orchestras were at one time ubiquitous in Jewish Eastern Europe and in North American immigrant communities.\"<ref name=Ger>{{cite web |url=https://germandolin.com/about |title=The Ger Mandolin Orchestra Story |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=germandolin.com |publisher= |access-date= 22 May 2017|quote=}}</ref>  In the Holocaust Museum in Washington D.C, recorded memories recall the mandolin's place in Eastern Europe, in Poland, Latvia, Lithuania, Croatia and Macedonia. For some, the mandolin was progressive.<ref>{{cite interview |last=Salsitz |first= Norman|subject-link= |interviewer=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum ID Card Project |title=Oral history interview with Norman Salsitz |url=https://collections.ushmm.org/search/catalog/irn509201 |publisher=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |location= |date= 5 November 1992|access-date=28 May 2017|quote=From interview about life in [[Kolbuszowa]] in the 1930s to 1945: But the sisters went to school, the sisters used to all play mandolin, progressive. So the brothers nod their heads, progressive. They were progressive, Jewish, traditional. }}</ref> Individuals, once from Eastern Europe, speak of playing music in different languages, of family members who were able to make the instruments needed for an entire orchestra, of playing or having family members play in mandolin orchestras, of parents who used to teach music.\n\nThe instrument was inexpensive and fairly easy for beginners to learn and became a first instrument for children.<ref name=Warschauer>{{Cite AV media notes |title=Jeff Warschauer The Singing Waltz Klezmer Guitar and Mandolin |title-link= |others= |year=1997 |chapter= |url= |access-date= |first= |last= |author-link= |first2= |last2= |author-link2= |page=1 |pages= |type= |publisher=Omega |id= |location= |ref=}}</ref> In the United States, it was embraced by left-wing \"Socialists and Unionists\" as the \"Instrument of the people\" and was part of the curriculum in Yiddish schools.<ref name=Ger/><ref name=Dumneazu>{{cite web |url=http://horinca.blogspot.com/2010/12/chanukah-why-no-jewish-mandolin.html |title=Chanukah: Why no Jewish Mandolin Orchestras?  |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=horinca.blogspot.com |publisher= |access-date=22 May 2017 |quote=}}</ref> There were Jewish mandolin orchestras and the instrument was popular with apartment dwellers as a quiet instrument that wouldn't disturb the neighbors.<ref name=Dumneazu/> When Avner Yonai started researching the likely pieces that an Eastern European mandolin orchestra would have played, he found that little could be found about the repertoire his ancestor had played Poland; it was likely to have been light classical pieces, tango, and folk songs, possibly ethnic music from Jewish theater, Yiddish songs, [[Hasidic]] music and Klezmer.<ref name=Dumneazu/><ref name=GerTablet>{{cite web |url=http://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-arts-and-culture/music/48739/plucky-move |title=Plucky Move |last= Gelfrand|first=Alexander |date= |website=tabletmag.com |publisher= |access-date= 22 May 2017|quote=}}</ref>\n\nJewish mandolinists were prominent on the American mandolin. The earliest were performing during the Golden Era of the Mandolin, from the 1880s through the 1920s. They include [[Vaudeville]] musician [[Samuel Siegel]] of Des Moines (parents from Baden, Germany), Charles J. Levin of Baltimore, Samuel Adelstein of San Francisco, C.H. Pomeroy of Salt Lake City, and [[Valentine Abt]] of Pittsburgh.<ref name=Naxos>{{Cite AV media notes |title=Spaghetti Rag, Rag Music for Mandolins |title-link= |others= |year= |chapter= |url=https://www.naxos.com/mainsite/blurbs_reviews.asp?item_code=8.557999&catNum=557999&filetype=About%20this%20Recording&language=English |access-date=22 May 2017 |first= Ugo|last=Orlandi |author-link= |first2= Fiorenzo|last2= Gitti|author-link2= |page= |pages= |type= |publisher=Naxos |id= |location= |ref=}}</ref> \nAnother player who helped to keep the mandolin in the public eye after the Golden Era passed was [[Dave Apollon]] (1897-1972). Apollon grew up in [[Kiev]] and performed in [[Vaudeville]] for 20 years, played with Russian, Latin, Gypsy and Ragtime material.<ref name=ApollonCAfe>{{cite web |url= https://www.mandolincafe.com/archives/article.html|title=History of the Mandolin in America |last=Coolik |first=Daniel |date=18 November 1998 |website= mandolincafe.org|publisher= |access-date=22 May 2017 |quote=}}</ref> His long lifetime playing let people hear virtuoso performances of the mandolin, and he contributed to the instrument's revival.<ref name=ApollonCAfe/>\n\nModern players play a variety of music, as they explore their roots. Avner Yonai, descendant of people from Gora Kalwaria, Poland, put together an orchestra in Berkeley, California in honor of the original Ger Mandolin Orchestra.<ref name=Ger/><ref name=GerTablet/> Examples of the New Ger Mandolin Orchestra's reperatoire include ''Russian Rag'' (a mandolin orchestra piece) and the \n''Abe Schwartz Freylekh'' (Klezmer adapted for mandolins).<ref name=Dumneazu/> Klezmer and mandolins came together in the 1970s in a \"revival\" in New York City, where \"the overwhelmingly Jewish folk music scene would gather for Jam sessions \u2013 fiddles, banjos, and mandolins\", with Klezmer and Bluegrass musician [[Andy Statman]] being credited for the success of the revival. Statman mixed jazz with klezmer.<ref name=Dumneazu/>\n\nJeff Warschauer (a [[cantor]] since 2015) started the Klezmer Conservatory Band (1990-2003) and is part of The Strauss/Warschauer Duo (1995 to present) and has led Jewish mandolin orchestras ''Klez Camp'' and ''New York Arbeiter Ring''.<ref name=Dumneazu/><ref name=cantor>{{cite web |url=http://www.cantorjeff.com/ |title=Jeff Warschauer Cantor, Musician, and Educator |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=cantorjeff.com |publisher= |access-date=28 May 2017 |quote=}}</ref> He has become a modern link to the older Jewish tradition, interviewing older Jewish musicians to collect songs in Yiddish and klesmer music.<ref name=cantor/> Coming from a background in [[Bluegrass music|Bluegrass]], [[Swing music|Swing]], [[R&B]] and [[Folk music]], he adapted his skills to use the mandolin in Klezmer, which doesn't use mandolin as a traditional instrument<ref name=Warschauer/> In one example on his album ''The Singing Waltz'', Warschauer mixed mandolin with trombones for the song ''Dem Helfand's Tants'' (''The Elephant's Dance''), a combination that was also used for the ''Odessa Swing'' (composed by Steve Netsky).<ref name=Warschauer/> He mixed accordion, drums and piano with mandolin on the song ''Ot Azoy'' (''That's the Way!'').<ref name=Warschauer/>\n\nAnother bandleader is Eric Stein of Canada; his ''Beyond the Pale'' band plays Klezmer and Eastern European music.<ref name=Dumneazu/>\n\nAlthough information today is sparse, evidence of the musical culture remains, collected at The United States Holocaust Memorial Museum in Washington D.C., where there are pictures and recorded memories of Eastern European Jewish people, which recall the culture that existed in the first decades of the 20th century. Those that remained, emigrants to other countries took their music and memories with them, and gradually assimilated. Drawing on them for their memories has been part of the revival of the cultures that passed.\n\n== Latvia ==\nThe Holocaust Museum has online artifacts dealing with musician Elfa Heifecs, a Jewish musician from Riga, Latvia, who organized mandolin orchestra there, about 1930.<ref name=Elfa>{{cite web |url=http://collections.ushmm.org/search/catalog/pa1166407 |title=Elja Heifecs conducts a Jewish mandolin orchestra in Riga, Latvia.|last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website=ushmm.org |publisher=United States Holocaust Museum |access-date=25 October 2016 |quote=}}</ref><ref name=Elfa2>{{cite web |url= https://collections.ushmm.org/search/catalog/irn523433 |title= Text only poster for a musical performance in prewar Riga|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= |publisher= United States Holocaust Memorial Museum|access-date= 7 February 2018 |quote=Announcement for a concert featuring 25 year old Elja Heifecs and his Mandolin Orchestra in Riga, Latvia, on January 10, 1937.}}</ref><ref name=Elfa3>{{cite web |url= https://collections.ushmm.org/search/catalog/pa1166409 |title= Elja Heifecs gives mandolin lessons to two students.|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= |publisher= United States Holocaust Memorial Museum|access-date= 7 February 2018 |quote=[caption]: Elja Heifecs gives mandolin lessons to two students.}}</ref>\n\n== Macedonia ==\nMacedonia has a mandolin tradition that dates back before World War II; The [[United States Holocaust Museum]] has a 1929 photo of a Jewish mandolin orchestra on display online.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://collections.ushmm.org/search/catalog/pa1119054 |title=A group of Macedonian Jewish youth who are members of a mandolin band, pose outside a building in Bitola, Macedonia |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website=ushmm.org |publisher=United States Holocaust Museum |access-date=11 October 2016 |quote=Caption: A group of Macedonian Jewish youth who are members of a mandolin band, pose outside a building in Bitola, Macedonia. Date: 1930 March 02 Locale: Bitola, [Macedonia; Bitolj] Yugoslavia }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/culturalinstitute/beta/asset/dihovo-macedonia-yugoslavia-a-group-of-mandolin-players-on-a-hike-22-12-1929/TAE0bZjY_znP6g?hl=en |title=Dihovo, Macedonia, Yugoslavia, A group of mandolin players on a hike, 22/12/1929 |last1=Vashem |first1=Yad |last2= |first2= |date= |website=google.com |publisher=Google Arts and Culture |access-date=11 October 2016 |quote= Title: Dihovo, Macedonia, Yugoslavia, A group of mandolin players on a hike, 22/12/1929. Location: Bitola, Yugoslavia Subject Keywords: Music, Prewar period, Orchestras Origin: Gabriel Albocher Name of submitter: Nina Shpringer Aharoni Credit: Yad Vashem Collection: Yad Vashem Photo Archive Archival signature: 6214/38  }}</ref> In modern times, the Skopje Mandolin orchestra was formed in 2001 and has performed in international competitions.<ref name=skopje>{{cite web|url=http://visitskopje.mk/index.php/concerts/179-concert-of-the-mandolin-orchestra |title=Concert of the Mandolin Orchestra |website=visitskopje.mk |access-date=11 October 2016 |quote=Formed in 2001, the Mandolin Orchestra \"Skopje\" has won multiple...  Under Ramadan Shukri's conducting, the orchestra will performs its traditional annual pre- new year's concert... Soloists as Suzana Turundzieva, Mustafa Imeri, Serafina Fantauzo, Gligor Popovski and Lazar Sandev... |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416051026/http://visitskopje.mk/index.php/concerts/179-concert-of-the-mandolin-orchestra |archivedate=16 April 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ladna.com.mk/en/news/mandolin-orchestra |title=News, Mandolin Orchestra from Skopje |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website=ladna.com |publisher= |access-date=11 October 2016 |quote=Ladna sponsored the Mandolin Orchestra in Skopje, supporting its members on the 10-th International Festival in Vienne France, where the orchestra had won two gold medals...}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mandolin-orchestra.org/orchestra.htm |title=Skopje Mandolin Orchestra of the Youth Cultural Center (Macedonia)  |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website=mandolin-orchestra.org/orchestra.htm |publisher= |access-date=11 October 2016 |quote=The Mandolin Orchestra in Skopje, Macedonia, is one of the top touring mandolin orchestras in Europe....young musicians, aged 14 to 22}}</ref> Mandolinists associated with the Skopje Mandolin Orchestra include Ramadan Shukri, Suzana Turundzieva, Mustafa Imeri, Serafina Fantauzo, Gligor Popovski and Lazar Sandev.<ref name=skopje/>\n\n==Mexico==\nColonized by Spain, Mexico had both Spanish instruments as well as instruments created locally. These include the [[bandurria]] and the [[bandol\u00f3n]].\n\nWhen [[Carlo Curti]] finished with playing mandolin with his \"Spanish Students\" in the United States, he organized a new act in Mexico in 1883-1884, the Mexican Typical Orchestra, which performed at the World's Industrial and\nCotton Exposition (1885) in New Orleans and then toured the United States.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Castillo |first=Manuel M.  |last2= |first2= |date=2014 |title=Italian and Spanish Influence on Selected Works of Mexican Composers: Mar\u00eda Grever, Ignacio Fern\u00e1ndez Esper\u00f3n \"Tata Nacho,\" and August\u00edn Lara |url=http://uknowledge.uky.edu/music_etds/32/ |journal=The UNiversity of Kentucky UKnowledge, Thesis and Dissertations, Music |publisher=The University of Kentucky |volume= |issue= |pages= 20|doi= |access-date=September 8, 2015|quote=[Full article: https://uknowledge.uky.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1034&context=music_etds]}}</ref> The band included as many as seven [[bandol\u00f3n]]s. Bandol\u00f3ns were developed in Mexico, guitar sized instruments with 18 strings (in 6 courses of 3) related to the [[bandurria]].<ref>\n{{cite web |url=http://lexicoon.org/es/bandolon |title= DEFINICI\u00d3N DE BANDOL\u00d3N, qu\u00e9 significa bandol\u00f3n |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=lexicoon.org |publisher= |access-date=September 16, 2015 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Alfab\u00e9tico tem\u00e1tica Invicta |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=01uOcTvyNuIC&lpg=PA863&ots=Ca6mDUyFA3&dq=El%20bandol%C3%B3n&pg=PA863#v=onepage&q&f=false |location= |publisher= |page=863 |date= |isbn=}}</ref> When described in U.S. newspapers, it was noted that they looked like large mandolins.<ref name=mandibandi>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Mexican Typical Orchestra|url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31557309/mexican_typical_orchestra_bandolons/ |work= New York Times |location=New York City |date=20 June 1885 |access-date=14 May 2019 |page= 4 |quote=\u2026 seven bandolons, the later being neither more nor less than magnified mandolins. |via=Newspaper.com}}</ref> It was also noted that Carlo Curti was a well-known mandolin player, and some newspapers never found out what the bandol\u00f3ns were, calling them mandolins.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Curti a well-known mandolin player |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31557579/curti_a_wellknown_mandolin_player/|work= The Courier-Journal|location= Louisville, Kentucky|date= 5 April 1885|page= 11|access-date=14 May 2019|quote=The Mexican Typical Orchestra will perform...under the leadership of Sig. Curti, the well-known Spanish mandolin player. |via=Newspaper.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Mandolin confused for bandol\u00f2n in Mexican Typical Orchestra write-up |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31557793/mandolin_confused_for_bandoln_in/ | work=Austin-American Statesman | location=Austin, Texas |date=15 April 1890 |page= 3 |access-date= 14 May 2019|quote= The Mexican Typical Orchestra, composed of bandurrias, mandolins, violins, violincellos, guitars, etc., \u2026  |via=Newspaper.com}}</ref>\n\nThe confusion may have added further to the impression in the United States that the mandolin and bandurria families were related. Musician [[Robert Braine]] wrote in the Etude in August 1918 that \"the craze for the mandolin in the United States was a direct result of the concert tours, covering several years, of two of such orchestras, the 'Spanish Students' and the 'Mexican Typical Orchestra' from Mexico City.\"<ref name=braine>{{cite magazine |last=Braine |first= Robert|date=August 1918 |title= Possibilities of the mandolin for the violin teachers |url= https://books.google.fr/books?id=hoOvYiTOVwkC&pg=PA544#v=onepage&q&f=false |magazine=The Etude |location= |publisher= |access-date=14 May 2019 }}</ref> Braine was aware of the nature of the Neapolitan mandolin, but lumped mandolins and bandurrias together in his article, saying that the mandolin was \"played, studied and taught\" in Spain, Mexico and the South American countries<ref name=braine/>.\n\n== New Zealand ==\nThe Auckland Mandolinata mandolin orchestra was formed in 1969 by Doris Flameling (1932\u20132004). Soon after arriving from the Netherlands with her family, Doris started teaching guitar and mandolin in West Auckland. In 1969, she formed a small ensemble for her pupils. This ensemble eventually developed into a full size mandolin orchestra, which survives today. Doris was the musical director and conductor of this orchestra for many years. The orchestra is currently led by Bryan Holden (conductor).\n\nThe early history of the mandolin in New Zealand is currently being researched by members of the Auckland Mandolinata.\n\n== Poland ==\nThe mandolin was used as a folk instrument throughout eastern part of European continent, including Poland, Ukraine and Slovakia in the early part of the 20th century.<ref name=tabletmagazine>{{cite web |url=http://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-arts-and-culture/music/48739/plucky-move |title=Plucky Move |last1=Gelfand |first1=Alexander |last2= |first2= |date=28 October 2010 |website=tabletmag.com |publisher=Tablet Magazine |access-date=25 October 2016 |quote=}}</ref> Mandolin orchestras were present as well.<ref name=tabletmagazine/> One example was the Mandolin Orchestra of Ger ([[Gora Kalwaria]], Poland).<ref name=tabletmagazine/> A photo exists of the orchestra, made up of Jewish residents who were in the orchestra in the 1930s before the Jewish population was sent to the [[Treblinka extermination camp]].<ref name=tabletmagazine/> A similar photo exists of a mandolin orchestra in the community of [[Grodno]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.grodnoonline.org/lost_worlds/section_2d_test.html |title=Lost Jewish Worlds, BETWEEN THE WORLD WARS - 4 |last1= Zandman|first1=F.|last2= |first2= |date= |website=grodnoonline.org |publisher=Tablet Grodno Online|access-date=25 October 2016 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n== Portugal ==\nThe ''bandolim'' (Portuguese for \"mandolin\") was a favourite instrument within the Portuguese bourgeoisie of the 19th century, but its rapid spread took it to other places, joining other instruments. Today you can see mandolins as part of the traditional and folk culture of Portuguese singing groups and the majority of the mandolin scene in Portugal is in Madeira Island. Madeira has over 17 active mandolin Orchestras and [[Tuna (music)|Tunas]]. The mandolin virtuoso [[Fabio Machado]] is one of Portugal's most accomplished mandolin players. The Portuguese influence brought the mandolin to Brazil and Sri Lanka.\n\n== Romania ==\n:[[:Category:Romanian mandolinists|See Romanian mandolinists]]\n\n== Russia ==\n[[:Category:Russian mandolinists|See Russian mandolinists]]\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n | align = right\n\n| image3 = Comerre-Pierrot jouant de la mandoline-Mus\u00e9e de Gap.jpg\n | width3 = 106\n | alt3 = Pierrot with mandolin\n | caption3 =The 1976 ''Adventures of Buratino'' character, Pierrot, played a mandolin. Similarly, the French painter [[L\u00e9on Comerre]] painted this image of a mandolin-playing Pierrot in 1884.\n\n | image2 = Gibson mandolin Glinka's museum Moscow Russia.jpg\n | width2 = 154\n | alt2 = Gibson mandolin modified with Russian electric pickup\n | caption2 = American-made Gibson mandolin, modified to electric with Russian-made pickups, at the Glinka National Museum Consortium of Musical Culture, Moscow, Russia.\n\n | image1 = Ernest K\u00f6hler, A new and practical school for Mandolin.jpg\n | width1 = 156\n | alt1 = book, Ernest K\u00f6hler, A new and practical school for Mandolin\n | caption1 = Cover of ''A New and Practical School for Mandolin'' (''\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0432\u0435\u0441\u044c\u043c\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u043d\u044f\u0442\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0448\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u043c\u0430\u043d\u0434\u043e\u043b\u0438\u043d\u044b'') by [[Ernesto K\u00f6hler]], with dual German-Russian entries. Version market to Germans was published c. 1887.<ref name=Schule>{{cite web |url= http://www.mandoisland.de/noten2011/ernest_koehler/ernesto_koehler.html#.WVfj0p9MEwg |title= Ernesto K\u00f6hler -Mandolin school for self teaching|last= Reichenbach|first= Michael|date= |website= mandoisland.de|publisher= |access-date= 1 July 2017|quote=}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe mandolin was popular in Russia in the pre-Soviet era and after as a folk instrument. Catalogs from the early 1900s offered a variety of bowlback mandolins, imports made by Italian companies. Locally made mandolins existed as well.\n\nThe first mandolin orchestra in Russia was put together in the early 1880s by an Italian immigrant, [[Ginislao Paris]], called ''The Society of Amateur Mandolinists and Guitarists''.<ref name=Speranski>{{cite web |url=https://archive.org/details/TheRussianEmbergher_201501 |title=The Russian Embergher |last=Speranski |first=Victor |date=November 2014 |website= |publisher= |access-date= 29 May 2017|quote=}}</ref> Paris designed double-top mandolins, which he had [[Luigi Embergher]] build.<ref name=Speranski/>  At least one member of the royal family of Russia played mandolin during this period, Tsarina Maria Fyodorovna who owned a Number 8 Embergher, a high-end instrument that would have been highly decorated.<ref name=Speranski/>\n\nThere were talented mandolinists, in various parts the country. [[Dave Apollon]], who became a well known (U.S.-based) player, was born in [[Kiev]], then part of Russia. After emigration from Russia, he was able to land a job in Vaudeville, exhibiting virtuosity.\n\nAfter the rise of the Soviet Union, bowlback mandolins were not imported in the numbers they had been. Although possibly that had much to with the turmoil starting in 1917, of the country being reorganized into a communist state, the timing also coincides with the drop in popularity worldwide, as the mandolin's ''Golden Era'' peaked. The instrument had competition as a folk instrument as well, from the [[domra]] and [[balalaika]]. [[Vasily Andreyev]] who founded the first balalaika orchestra in Russia and resurrected the domra was inspired by a performance of Russia's first mandolin orchestra.<ref name=vasily>{{cite web |url=https://archive.org/details/TheRussianEmbergher_201501 |title=The Russian Embergher |last=Speranski |first=Victor |date=November 2014 |website= |publisher= |access-date= 29 May 2017|quote= It was Ginislao's mandolin orchestra that inspired Andreev to turn from his solo balalaika performances to the creation of a full Russian folk instruments orchestra that brought him worldwide fame. }}</ref> The bowlback didn't just disappear, as they are common in photos of mandolin orchestras in Eastern Europe in the 1930s. However, the mandolins produced in Soviet factories were of the cheap, flatback, \"Portuguese\" style\u2014widespread throughout the Soviet Union.\n\nIn the 1970s and 80s, bluegrass music spread into Russia [[Czech bluegrass|from Czechoslovakia]], and through American performers touring in Russia, including [[Roy Clark]] and the [[Nitty Gritty Dirt Band]].<ref name=kukuruzachictrib>{{cite news |last=Duckman |first=David |date=20 February 1994 |title=No Second Fiddle, Bluegrass In Russia? Kukuruza Plucks and Picks With Aplomb |url= http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-02-20/features/9402200340_1_bluegrass-music-kukuruza-fax |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |location= Chicago, Illinois|access-date=7 February 2018 }}</ref> Russian bands were started with bluegrass elements that included a mandolin, including [[Kukuruza]] (with mandolinist Georgi Palmov) and Bering Strait (mandolinist Sergei Passov).<ref name=kukuruzachictrib/><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.allmusic.com/artist/bering-strait-mn0000057941/biography |title=Artist Biography |last=Ruhlmann |first=William |date= |website=allmusic.com |publisher= |access-date= 7 February 2018 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nThe mandolin was used in movies, including the 1976 film ''[[The Adventures of Buratino (1976 film)|The Adventures of Buratino]]'' (\u041f\u0440\u0438\u043a\u043b\u044e\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0411\u0443\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043d\u043e) to accompany songs by Tortila and [[Pierrot|Pierro]] (\u0422\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0438\u043b\u044b \u0438 \u041f\u044c\u0435\u0440\u043e).<ref>{{cite web |url= http://pazovsky.ru/mandoline/ |title= Mandolin |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= pazovsky.ru |publisher= |access-date= 4 April 2019 |quote= \u041c\u0430\u043d\u0434\u043e\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0431\u044b\u043b\u0430 \u043e\u0447\u0435\u043d\u044c \u043f\u043e\u043f\u0443\u043b\u044f\u0440\u043d\u0430 \u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u0432 \u0434\u043e\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u044f \u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435. \u041c\u043d\u043e\u0436\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0444\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c\u043e\u0432 \u0431\u044b\u043b\u043e \u043e\u0437\u0432\u0443\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043e \u0442\u0435\u043c\u0430\u043c\u0438 \u043c\u0430\u043d\u0434\u043e\u043b\u0438\u043d\u044b. \u041e\u0434\u043d\u0438\u043c\u0438 \u0438\u0437 \u0441\u0430\u043c\u044b\u0445 \u0437\u0430\u043f\u043e\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0430\u044e\u0449\u0438\u0445\u0441\u044f \u044f\u0432\u043b\u044f\u044e\u0442\u0441\u044f: \u0441\u043e\u043b\u043e \u0432 \u043f\u0435\u0441\u043d\u044f\u0445 \u043f\u0430\u043f\u044b \u041a\u0430\u0440\u043b\u043e, \u0447\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0430\u0445\u0438 \u0422\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0438\u043b\u044b \u0438 \u041f\u044c\u0435\u0440\u043e, \u0432 \u0444\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c\u0435 \u00ab\u041f\u0440\u0438\u043a\u043b\u044e\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0411\u0443\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043d\u043e\u00bb. [translation: Mandolin was very popular in Russia in the pre-Soviet times and after. A lot of films were voiced by mandolin themes. One of the most memorable are: solo in the songs of Pope Carlo, tortoises Tortila and Piero, in the film \u201cThe Adventures of Buratino\u201d}}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UexFpXloTwM|title= \u0420\u043e\u043c\u0430\u043d\u0441 \u0447\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0430\u0445\u0438 \u0422\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0438\u043b\u044b (\"\u041f\u0440\u0438\u043a\u043b\u044e\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0411\u0443\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043d\u043e\") |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= |publisher= |access-date= 4 April 2019|quote=[Clip from Adventures of Buratino featuring Tortila]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tzj6NbGXjGc|title= \u0420\u043e\u043c\u0430\u043d\u0441 \u0447\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0430\u0445\u0438 \u0422\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0438\u043b\u044b (\"\u041f\u0440\u0438\u043a\u043b\u044e\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0411\u0443\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043d\u043e\") |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= |publisher= |access-date= 4 April 2019|quote=[Clip from Adventures of Buratino featuring Pierro]}}</ref>\n\n== South Africa ==\nThe mandolin has been a prominent instrument in the recordings of [[Johnny Clegg]] and his bands [[Juluka]] and [[Savuka]]. Since 1992, Andy Innes has been the mandolinist for Johnny Clegg and Savuka.\n\n==Spain==\n[[File:John Phillip, A Lady Playing the Mandolin.jpg|right|thumb|Painting by [[John Phillip]] in 1854, showing a Spanish woman with mandolin.]]\nAccording to historian Paul Sparks, Spain is \"one of the few Western countries where the Neapolitan mandolin has never been widely played.\"<ref name=\"Sparks24-29\">{{harvnb|Sparks|2003|pages=10, 11, 24\u201329}}</ref> As the mandolin was used in Italy to serenade young ladies and make music in the streets, the equally high pitched and plucked [[bandurria]] was used by Spanish youth to accompany their songs in the street and serenade.<ref name=\"Sparks24-29\"/> The instruments were used alongside guitars for traditional dances.<ref name=\"Sparks24-29\"/> The tradition of dancing to fast music was one of the draws of the Spanish Students when they went to Paris with their bandurrias, guitars and fiddles.<ref name=\"Sparks24-29\"/>\n\nBoth the Spanish bandurria and Italian mandolins ultimately were developments of the [[gittern]] and the [[mandore (instrument)|mandore]]. In the 1880s, the mandolin and bandurria, with their small sizes and double rows of metal strings, were similar enough to be confused by ignorant audiences.<ref name=\"Sparks24-29\"/> This happened in America and, along with deception from opportunistic Italian musicians, led to the mandolin's expansion.<ref name=\"Sparks24-29\"/> Both instruments spread around the world from their original homes in Europe, the bandurria mainly in Spanish speaking areas such as South America and the Philippines.\n\nIn Spain today, the bandurria is a \"national instrument.\"<ref name=Hector>{{cite web |url= http://www.themandolintuner.com/mandolin-news-an-interview-with-hector-marin/ |title=An Interview with Hector Marin |last= Rizos |first= Christos |date= |website= themandolintuner.com|publisher= |access-date= 28 April 2019|quote=}}</ref> However, the mandolin can be learned there as well, especially by those pursuing a career as a classical musician.<ref name=Hector/> Although professional Spanish mandolinists may be rare, but they do exist: Hector Marin developed his skill with the mandolin sufficiently to complete in the Yasuo Kuwahara International Mandolin Competition in Germany in 2015.<ref name=Kuwaharacomp>{{cite web |url= https://m.eldiario.es/cultura/Hector-Marin-Concurso-Kuwahara-Alemania_0_385661844.amp.html |title=El placentino H\u00e9ctor Mar\u00edn, \u00fanico espa\u00f1ol en el Concurso Yasuo Kuwahara en Alemania [translation: Hector Mar\u00edn, the only Spaniard in the Yasuo Kuwahara Contest in Germany] |last= |first= |date= 8 May 2015|website= eldiario.es|publisher= |access-date= 28 April 2019|quote=}}</ref> The competition that year had 11 other \"virtuosos of the mandolin\" competing, six from Germany and five from Russia.<ref name=Kuwaharacomp/> Marin, spoke in an interview, of learning first the bandurria and then later the mandolin, concentrating on the latter for having a broader range of classical material to play.<ref name=Hector/> He benefited from European culture, having teachers in both Spain and elsewhere in Europe as he pursued music.<ref name=Hector/> Marin attended several schools, including in Austria.  He cited Juan Carlos Mu\u00f1oz (Spanish, teaching in Austria), Mari Fe Pav\u00f3n, Caterina Lichtenberg (German) and Avi Avital (Israeli)  as his mandolin-playing musical influences.<ref name=Hector/>\n\n== Sri Lanka ==\nThe mandolin was brought to Sri Lanka by the Portuguese, who colonized Sri Lanka from 1505 to 1658. The instrument has been heavily used in [[baila]], a genre of Sri Lankan music formed from a mixture of Portuguese, African and Sinhala music. For example, the mandolin features prominently in [[M.S. Fernando]]'s baila song, ''Bola Bola Meti''.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xRiglareR9c|title= Bola Bola Mati \u0db6\u0ddd\u0dbd \u0db6\u0ddd\u0dbd \u0db8\u0dd0\u0da7\u0dd2 M.S.Fernando |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= youtube.com|publisher= |access-date= 7 April 2019|quote=[YouTube. The song opens with a mandolin [[riff]]. The lyrics are about a [[mud dauber]] gathering mud from the riverbank and building a house.]}}</ref> Victor Rathnayaka's ''Thaniwennata Mage Lowe'', [[Sunil Perera]] & [[The Gypsies (Sri Lankan band)|Gypsies]] ''Saima Cut wela'' and Sujatha Athanayaka's ''Hathara watin Kalukaragena'' are among other examples of songs with mandolin.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hfMdQffJhRg|title= Saima Cut Wela - Sunil Perera (Gypsies) |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= youtube.com|publisher= |access-date= 7 April 2019|quote=[YouTube. The first minute of the song and its [[riff]]s throughout the songs are played on the mandolin.]}}</ref>  Modern day musicians include Antony Surendra, V. Hemapala Perera, Ananda Perera, [[Dinesh Subasinghe]], Susantha Kariyakarawana, Sarath Fernando, Nalaka Sajee, Haasriza Imran and Buddhika Perera\n\n== Tobago and Trinidad ==\nThe mandolin has a history on [[Tobago]] and [[Trinidad]] as the [[Bandolin (Trinidad)|bandolin]], dating back before World War I.<ref name=\"Winer2009\">{{cite book|author=Lise Winer|title=Dictionary of the English/Creole of Trinidad & Tobago: On Historical Principles|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_n82hsbDJBMC&pg=PA50|accessdate=5 May 2013|date=16 January 2009|publisher=McGill-Queen's Press - MQUP|isbn=978-0-7735-7607-0|pages=50\u2013}}</ref>  It was a small instrument, approximately 20 x 40 centimeters, strung with 8 strings in four courses of two each.<ref name=\"Winer2009\"/> Before the war, it was commonly a round-backed instrument, made of strips of wood.<ref name=\"Winer2009\"/> The flat-backed version appeared after the war. Occasionally a turtle shell would be used for the back of the instrument.<ref name=\"Winer2009\"/> It is used in Trinidad's ''[[parang]]'' music, accompanied by \"[[Cuatro (instrument)|cuatro]] and [[maracas]]\".<ref name=\"Winer2009\"/> There is another member of the mandolin family, the Trinidadian version of the [[Bandol (instrument)|bandol]], different from the mainland [[bandola]]. It is the tenor of the mandolin family on the island, also strung with 8 strings in 4 courses; however, the lower two string courses are strung differently, each having a metal and a nylon string.<ref name=\"Winer2009\"/>\n\n== Turkey ==\nTurkey has been the home of a mandolin-banjo manufacturer, [[C\u00fcmb\u00fcs]], since the early 20th century. The country had what may be its first Mandolin festival in June 2015, and has at least one Mandolin Orchestra.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mandolincafe.com/forum/showthread.php?106924-The-very-first-Mandolin-Festival-in-Turkey-June-2015 |title=Thread: The very first Mandolin Festival in Turkey June 2015 |last1= Hi\u00e7y\u0131lmaz |first1= Orkun|last2= |first2= |date=April 2012 |website= mandolincafe.com|publisher= Mandolin Cafe|access-date=October 18, 2015 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mandolincafe.com/forum/showthread.php?106924-The-very-first-Mandolin-Festival-in-Turkey-June-2015 |title=Thread: a melody from a turkish mandolin teaching book |last1= Hi\u00e7y\u0131lmaz |first1= Orkun|last2= |first2= |date=April 2012 |website= mandolincafe.com|publisher= Mandolin Cafe|access-date=October 18, 2015 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nOne professional musician to use the mandolin is Sumru A\u011f\u0131ry\u00fcr\u00fcyen who is known for singing and playing many styles of music including [[world music]], [[Klezmer]], Turkish folk, Balkan folk, blues, jazz, [[krautrock]], protest rock and [[Makam|maqam]].<ref name=list>{{cite web |url=http://istanbulmusic.blogspot.com/2011/03/best-turkish-female-musicians.html |title=50 Greatest Turkish Women in Music, Western Classical Music |last1=Alhan |first1=M.S. |last2= |first2= |date=2011|website=istanbulmusic.blogspot.com |publisher= |access-date=October 17, 2015 |quote=}}</ref><ref name=bug>{{cite web |url=http://www.bugunbugece.com/git-gor/rastlasmalar-ii-tolga-tuzun-sumru-agiryuruyen |title=Rastla\u015fmalar II: Tolga T\u00fcz\u00fcn - Sumru A\u011f\u0131ry\u00fcr\u00fcyen |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=January 10, 2013 |website=bugunbugece.com |access-date=October 17, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117033006/http://www.bugunbugece.com/git-gor/rastlasmalar-ii-tolga-tuzun-sumru-agiryuruyen |archivedate=November 17, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n== Ukraine ==\nThe Mandolin has been played in Ukraine, and pictures of it being played today can be found online.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.alamy.com/stock-photo-ukraine-yalta-livadia-palace-ukrainian-folkloric-show-women-in-traditional-49017321.html|title= Ukraine, Yalta, Livadia Palace. Ukrainian folkloric show. Women in traditional costumes playing Russian balalaikas & lutes|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= |publisher= Alamy|access-date= 26 October 2016|quote=Danita Delimont / Alamy Stock Photo}}</ref> One famous former resident of [[Kiev]] was [[Dave Apollon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blatata.com/biografii/bio01/9824-djejjv-apollon-dave-apollon.html|title=\u0414\u044d\u0439\u0432 \u0410\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043b\u043e\u043d (Dave Apollon)|author=|date=|website=blatata.com|accessdate=16 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816170712/http://www.blatata.com/biografii/bio01/9824-djejjv-apollon-dave-apollon.html|archive-date=16 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Other photos dating back to the early 20th century show Ukrainian Mandolin orchestras in Canada and the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.manitobamusicmuseum.com/mandolinorchofwpg.htm |title= Mandolin Orchestra, 1926 Ukrainian Labour Temple|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |publisher= Manitoba Music Museum |access-date=26 October 2016 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.ebay.com/itm/252186064378?_mwBanner=1 |title=UKRAINIAN MANDOLIN ORCHESTRA SCRANTON PA LAWRENCE UHRYN ANTIQUE VINTAGE PHOTO |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= eBay.com|publisher= |accessdate=2016-10-26|quote=from photo back side: Ukrainian Mandolin Orchestras, Organized 1932, Scranton, Pennsylvania, Professor Lawrence Uhryn, Instructor and Director}}</ref>\nOne of the offshoots of Ukrainian immigrants to North America is the [[Toronto Mandolin Orchestra]] (possibly the oldest mandolin orchestra in North America), which claims Ukrainians as among its founders. The orchestra's web site said of mandolins in Ukraine, that the instruments were popular in the early 20th century, but never reached folk-instrument status there. Ukrainian immigrants of the period took the instruments with them to their new countries.\n\nThe instrument has had to compete in Ukraine with native instruments that have been revived, such as the [[kobza]]. The orchestral variant of the kobza is similar to the Mandolin, having four strings and being tuned in fifths.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://home.att.net/~bandura.ca/VMfolkBook/banduras.html |title=PLUCKED STRING INSTRUMENTS, The Kobza |last1=Mishalow |first1=Victor |date=1999 |website=Folk Instruments of Ukraine |access-date=26 October 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20001008111837/http://home.att.net/~bandura.ca/VMfolkBook/banduras.html |archivedate=8 October 2000 }}</ref>\n\n== United Kingdom ==\n:[[:Category:British mandolinists|See British mandolinists]]\n\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n | direction = vertical | width=165\n | align = right\n | image1 = Mandolin guitar band crystal palace.jpg\n | alt1 = Polytechnic and People's Palace Mandoline and Guitar Band\n | caption1 = The ''Polytechnic and People's Palace Mandoline and Guitar Band'' in 1899 at the [[The Crystal Palace|Crystal Palace]].\n | image2 = SimonMayorMSI.jpg\n | alt2 = Simon Mayor\n | caption2 = [[Simon Mayor]] has worked at creating  a uniquely [[United Kingdom|British]] voice for the mandolin.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Joyner |first=Hermon |title=Simon Mayor - Approaching the Mandolin with Wit and Wisdom |magazine=Mandolin Magazine |date=Fall 2009 |volume=11 |issue=2 |pages=3\u20135 |url=http://www.mandolinmagazine.com |accessdate=20 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091215030434/http://www.mandolinmagazine.com/cgi/backissues/searchdb.cgi?searchterm=v11n2 |archivedate=15 December 2009}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20101102224621/http://mandolinmagazine.com/images/fall2009.jpg Cover]</ref>\n}}\nThe mandolin has been used extensively in the traditional music of [[England]] and [[Scotland]] for generations. [[Simon Mayor]] is a prominent British player who has produced six solo albums, instructional books and DVDs, as well as recordings with his mandolin quartet the Mandolinquents.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n[[File:John Paul Jones.jpg|thumb|left|[[John Paul Jones (musician)|John Paul Jones]] playing mandolin with ''[[The Duhks]]'' on Zeppelin's \"[[Whole Lotta Love]]\" at [[MerleFest]], 2007.<ref>{{cite web |title=MERLEFEST {{!}} 04.26 \u2013 04.29 {{!}} NORTH CAROLINA |date=May 23, 2007 |author=Anson Burtch |url=https://www.jambase.com/article/merlefest-04-26-04-29-north-carolina |website=JamBase |access-date=2019-05-18}}</ref>]]\nThe instrument has also found its way into British rock music. The mandolin was played by [[Mike Oldfield]] (and introduced by [[Vivian Stanshall]]) on Oldfield's album ''[[Tubular Bells]]'', as well as on a number of his subsequent albums (particularly prominently on ''[[Hergest Ridge]]'' (1974) and ''[[Ommadawn]]'' (1975)). It was used extensively by the British folk-rock band [[Lindisfarne (band)|Lindisfarne]], who featured two members on the instrument, [[Ray Jackson (musician)|Ray Jackson]] and Simon Cowe, and whose \"[[Fog on the Tyne]]\" was the biggest selling UK album of 1971\u201372. The instrument was also used extensively in the UK folk revival of the 1960s and 1970s with bands such as [[Fairport Convention]] and [[Steeleye Span]] taking it on as the lead instrument in many of their songs. \"[[Maggie May]]\" by [[Rod Stewart]], which hit No. 1 on both the British charts and the Billboard Hot 100, also featured Jackson's playing. It has also been used by other British rock musicians. [[Led Zeppelin]]'s bassist [[John Paul Jones (musician)|John Paul Jones]] is an accomplished mandolin player and has recorded numerous songs on mandolin including \"[[Going to California]]\" and \"[[That's the Way (Led Zeppelin song)|That's the Way]]\"; the mandolin part on \"[[The Battle of Evermore]]\" is played by [[Jimmy Page]], who composed the song. Other Led Zeppelin songs featuring mandolin are \"[[Hey Hey What Can I Do]]\", and \"[[Black Country Woman]]\". [[Pete Townshend]] of [[the Who]] played mandolin on the track \"[[Mike Post Theme]]\", along with many other tracks on ''[[Endless Wire (The Who album)|Endless Wire]]''. [[McGuinness Flint]], for whom [[Graham Lyle]] played the mandolin on their most successful single, ''[[When I'm Dead And Gone]]'', is another example. Lyle was also briefly a member of [[Ronnie Lane's Slim Chance]], and played mandolin on their hit \"[[How Come]]\". One of the more prominent early mandolin players in popular music was [[Robin Williamson]] in [[the Incredible String Band]]. [[Ian Anderson (musician)|Ian Anderson]] of Jethro Tull is a highly accomplished mandolin player, as is his guitarist [[Martin Barre]]. The popular song \"[[Please Please Please Let Me Get What I Want]]\" by [[the Smiths]] featured a mandolin solo played by [[Johnny Marr]]. More recently, the Glasgow-based band [[Sons and Daughters (band)|Sons and Daughters]] featured the mandolin, played by Ailidh Lennon, on tracks such as \"Fight\", \"Start to End\", and \"Medicine\". British [[folk punk|folk-punk]] icons [[the Levellers (band)|the Levellers]] also regularly use the mandolin in their songs. British comedian [[Ade Edmondson]] took the role of lead mandolin in his folk punk band, [[Bad Shepherds]]. Current bands are also beginning to use the mandolin and its unique sound, such as South London's [[Indigo Moss]] who use it throughout their recordings and live gigs. The mandolin has also featured in the playing of [[Matthew Bellamy]] in the rock band [[Muse (band)|Muse]]. It also forms the basis of [[Paul McCartney]]'s 2007 hit \"[[Dance Tonight]]\". That was not the first time a [[Beatle]] played a mandolin, however; that distinction goes to [[George Harrison]] on \"[[Gone Troppo]]\", the title cut from the 1982 album of the same name.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}} Also more recently [[hard rock]] supergroup [[Them Crooked Vultures]] have been playing a song, ''Highway One'' in which Jones \"morphs an effected mandolin bluegrass run into a slick rock riff\".<ref name=vulturesjones>{{cite web |url= https://www.jambase.com/article/them-crooked-vultures-02-08-nyc|title= Them Crooked Vultures, 02.08, NYC|last=  Dembinsky|first= Ryan|date= 11 February 2010|website= |publisher=jambase.com |access-date=17 April 2018 |quote=}}</ref> This song was left off their debut album ''[[Them Crooked Vultures (album)|Them Crooked Vultures]]'', and features former [[Led Zeppelin]] [[bassist]] [[John Paul Jones (musician)|John Paul Jones]].<ref name=vulturesjones/>\n\nIn the Classical style, performers such as Hugo D'Alton, [[Alison Stephens]] and Michael Hooper have continued to play music by British composers such as [[Michael Finnissy]], James Humberstone and Elspeth Brooke.\n\nThe mandolin is taught in Lanarkshire by the Lanarkshire Guitar and Mandolin Association to over 100 people.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n== United States ==\nSee: [[Mandolins in North America]] and [[Bluegrass mandolin]]\n:[[:Category:American mandolinists|See American mandolinists]] and [[:Category:American bluegrass mandolinists|American bluegrass mandolinists]]\n\nThe [[mandolin]] has had a place in North American culture since the 1880s, when a \"mandolin craze\" began.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Mandolin-Mad Belles, The new musical craze among fashionable News York girls|url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3181695/mandolin_madness_in_girls/ |work= The Times|location= Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|date= 27 Mar 1886|page=3 |access-date= 12 May 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= A mandolin craze |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/6925750/mandolin_craze_1895/ |work= The Weekly Wisconsin|location= |date= 2 Mar 1895| page=1 |access-date=12 May 2012 }} </ref> \n\nThe continent was a land of immigrants, including Italian immigrants, some of whom brought their mandolins with them. In spite of the mandolin having arrived in America, it was not in the national consciousness until after 1880 when the Spanish Students arrived on their international performing tour. Afterwards, a \"mandolin craze\" swept the United States, with large numbers of young people taking up the instrument and teachers such as [[Samuel Siegel]] touring the country. The fad died out after World War I, but enough had learned the instrument that it remained. The mandolin found a new surge with the music of [[Bill Monroe]]; the Gibson F-5 mandolin he played, as well as other [[Mandolin#Archtop|archtop instruments]], became the American standard for mandolins. [[Mandolin#Bowlback|Bowlback mandolins]] were displaced. The instrument has been taken up in blues, bluegrass, jug-band music, country, rock, punk, Celtic and other genres of music. While not as popular as the guitar, it is widespread across the country.\n\n== Venezuela ==\nAs in Brazil, the mandolin has played an important role in the [[Music of Venezuela]]. It has enjoyed a privileged position as the main melodic instrument in several different regions of the country. Specifically, the eastern states of Sucre, Nueva Esparta, Anzoategui and Monagas have made the mandolin the main instrument in their versions of [[Joropo]] as well as [[Punto (Venezuela)|Puntos]], [[Jota (music)|Jotas]], [[Polo]]s, Fulias, [[Merengue music|Merengues]] and [[Malague\u00f1a (genre)|Malague\u00f1as]]. Also, in the west of the country the sound of the mandolin is intrinsically associated with the regional genres of the Venezuelan Andes: Bambucos, Pasillos, Pasodobles, and Waltzes. In the western city of Maracaibo the Mandolin has been played in Decimas, Danzas and Contradanzas Zulianas; in the capital, [[Caracas]], the Merengue Rucaneao, Pasodobles and Waltzes have also been played with mandolin for almost a century. Today, Venezuelan mandolists include an important group of virtuoso players and ensembles such as Alberto Valderrama, Jesus Rengel, Ricardo Sandoval, Saul Vera, and Cristobal Soto.\n\n== Vietnam ==\n[[File:Ph\u00f2ng tr\u01b0ng b\u00e0y ngh\u1ec7 thu\u1eadt c\u1ea3i l\u01b0\u01a1ng 1496655927699.jpg|right|thumb|Three musical instruments with scalloped necks, guitar, mandolin, and a possible hybrid of the two.<ref name=Vietnameseinstruments>{{cite web |url=http://www.ddth.com/showthread.php/106779-T%C3%ACm-hi%E1%BB%83u-c%C3%A1c-lo%E1%BA%A1i-nh%E1%BA%A1c-c%E1%BB%A5-!!!?s=6a3493baf1d9d961a426bc6b8d2031d4 |title= Ch\u1ee7 \u0111\u1ec1: T\u00ecm hi\u1ec3u c\u00e1c lo\u1ea1i nh\u1ea1c c\u1ee5 !!! |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=December 11, 2006 |website=ddth.com |publisher= |access-date=June 4, 2017 |quote=[translation:] around 1938-1939 a new style was born, the guitar was smaller than the guitar but bigger than the mandolin and they gave it a name called \"guitar mandarin\".}}</ref>]]\n\nThe French ruled Vietnam completely by 1884 and set up a system of modern education. The population was exposed to French culture and music, which included the mandolin. The influence of French culture was strong enough to affect Vietnamese music. They began writing lyrics to French pop music in Vietnamese and teaching themselves other western instruments including mandolin, guitar, Hawaiian guitar and banjo.<ref name=Catholic>{{cite web |url=http://thingsasian.com/story/reform-and-tradition-early-vietnamese-popular-song |title= Reform and Tradition in Early Vietnamese Popular Song|last= Gibbs|first= James|date=2 March 2017 |website= thingsasian.com|publisher= |access-date=2 June 2017 |quote=}}</ref> Through the Catholics and later the conservatories, European classical music and instruments were taught, including piano and bowed instruments.<ref name=Catholic/>\n\nThe mandolin and guitar were played in both classical music and pop music. Although used in popular music, both instruments were also taught in the Saigon National Conservatory (now the [[Conservatory of Ho Chi Minh City]]).<ref name=vietconservatory>{{cite news|last= Tung|first= Son|date= 24 February 2012|title= Farewell to the Mandolin|url= http://english.thesaigontimes.vn/22034/Farewell-To-The-Mandolin.html|location= Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam|access-date= 1 June 2017|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170604160625/http://english.thesaigontimes.vn/22034/Farewell-To-The-Mandolin.html|archive-date= 2017-06-04|url-status= dead}}</ref> However, the mandolin has disappeared from the conservatory where it had been taught, apparently dropped from the curriculum.<ref name=vietconservatory/> Instead of Guitar-Mandolin department, the school lists Guitar-Accordion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hcmcons.vn/gioi-thieu/cac-khoa/guitar-accordeon/gioi-thieu |title= Guitar - Accordeon, Gi\u1edbi thi\u1ec7u |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= hcmcons.vn |publisher= |access-date=1 June 2017 |quote=Th\u00e0nh l\u1eadp t\u1eeb n\u0103m 1956, Khoa g\u1ed3m hai b\u1ed9 m\u00f4n: Guitare v\u00e0 Mandoline. Sau n\u0103m 1975, Khoa c\u00f3 th\u00eam b\u1ed9 m\u00f4n Accord\u00e9on v\u00e0 sau \u0111\u00f3 l\u00e0 Orgue \u0111i\u1ec7n t\u1eed.  [translation: Founded in 1956, the Faculty consists of two departments: Guitare and Mandoline. After 1975, Khoa added Accordion and later Electronic Organ.]}}</ref>\n\nThough probably never a dominant instrument, the mandolin was learned by enough people to have a presence among the settlers who left Vietnam for the United States, and who continued to play mandolins in their new home. There are still people in Vietnam playing as well, although the cost of a new instrument is prohibitive.<ref name=vietmanodoorch>{{cite web |url= http://thanhnien.vn/van-hoa/ban-nhac-mandolin-dat-bac-lieu-315625.html|title=Ban nh\u1ea1c mandolin \u0111\u1ea5t B\u1ea1c Li\u00eau [Bac Lieu mandolin band] |last=Giang |first=Huong  |date= December 9, 2012|website= |publisher=Thanh Nien |access-date= June 4, 2017 |quote=}}</ref> There is at least one mandolin orchestra still playing, a group of aging players teaching newcomers.<ref name=vietmanodoorch/>\n\nVietnamese luthiers have worked with mandolin design. Mandolins being made in Vietnam today for the international market use the French flatback style. However, some Vietnamese luthiers have added their own innovation, putting sound holes in the mandolins' sides.\n\nThe luthiers also worked with the idea of modifying the mandolin to meet local musical styles, making experimental changes to the necks of violins, guitars and mandolins to suit them to [[Cai luong]] opera music.<ref name=scoop>{{cite web |url= http://tomkhoshiwo.blogspot.com/|title= Cai luong|last= Shiwo |first=Tomkho |date=December 4, 2005 |website=Tomkhoshiwo.blogspot.com|access-date= June 4, 2017|quote=...the cai luong band uses modern musical instruments. Vietnamese artists renovated the Western violin, mandolin and guitar by making concave frets to create new tones and melodies...concave-fret guitar is the main instrument for cai luong and it has become a national instrument of Vietnam}}</ref> In the mid-1930s, they made concave frets, scooping out extra wood between the frets, making the space between them deep and to allow the musicians to bend the notes, and stringing them with four single strings.<ref name=scoop/> Musicians Hai N\u00e9n and Hai Nh\u00e0nh were associated with the instruments, possibly being the first to use them.<ref name=\"ph\u00edm l\u00f5m\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ddth.com/showthread.php/106779-T%C3%ACm-hi%E1%BB%83u-c%C3%A1c-lo%E1%BA%A1i-nh%E1%BA%A1c-c%E1%BB%A5-!!!?s=6a3493baf1d9d961a426bc6b8d2031d4 |title= Ch\u1ee7 \u0111\u1ec1: T\u00ecm hi\u1ec3u c\u00e1c lo\u1ea1i nh\u1ea1c c\u1ee5 !!! |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=December 11, 2006 |website=ddth.com |publisher= |access-date=June 4, 2017 |quote=V\u00e0o kho\u1ea3ng n\u0103m 1934-1935 c\u00e1c \u00f4ng Hai N\u00e9n v\u00e0 Hai Nh\u00e0nh l\u00e0 nh\u1eefng ng\u01b0\u1eddi \u0111\u1ea7u ti\u00ean s\u1eed d\u1ee5ng mandolin ph\u00edm l\u00f5m...Mandolin ph\u00edm l\u00f5m ra \u0111\u1eddi, tuy \u0111\u00e3 gi\u1ea3i quy\u1ebft \u0111\u01b0\u1ee3c v\u1ea5n \u0111\u1ec1 tr\u00ecnh t\u1ea5u nh\u1eefng b\u00e0i b\u1ea3n thu\u1ed9c h\u01a1i Nam, nh\u01b0ng k\u1ef9 thu\u1eadt di\u1ec5n t\u1ea5u \u0111\u00e3 g\u00e2y nhi\u1ec1u kh\u00f3 kh\u0103n cho nh\u1ea1c c\u00f4ng...[translation:Between 1934 and 1935, Hai Nam and Hai Nhanh were the first to use the concave mandolin....Mandolin concave was born, but solved the problem of the composition of the South, but the technique has caused many difficulties for musicians. At first, the rigidity of the mandolin string makes the musicians too painful hands with the fingers, the keyboard is too narrow, hard to hit...] }}</ref> The ''sunken-fret mandolin'' (mandolin ph\u00edm l\u00f5m) did not meet the musical needs as well as the [[Guitar ph\u00edm l\u00f5m|sunken-fret guitar]], because the mandolin's rigidity made it painful to get the same effects from the strings.<ref name=\"ph\u00edm l\u00f5m\"/> Also the mandolin's narrow fretboard made it difficult to hit the notes.<ref name=\"ph\u00edm l\u00f5m\"/> Another reason to move to a bigger instrument was the pitch range of the mandolin, high pitched and not as useful to accompany singing as the instruments that replaced it in the opera.<ref name=\"ph\u00edm l\u00f5m\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Mandolin family instruments}}\n\n[[Category:Mandolin family instruments]]\n[[Category:Mandolinists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Global traditions of playing the mandolin}}\n[[File:Giuseppe Pettine in 1898.jpg|upright|right|thumb|Italian mandolin virtuoso and child prodigy [[Giuseppe Pettine]] (here pictured in 1898) brought the Italian playing style to America where he settled in Providence, Rhode Island, as a mandolin teacher and composer. Pettine is credited with promoting a style where \"one player plays both the rhythmic chords and the lyric melodic line at once, combining single strokes and tremolo.\"<ref name=academicpaper>{{cite journal\n |ref              = {{sfnref|Dickson}}\n |author           = Jean Dickson, University at Buffalo (SUNY)\n |title            = Mandolin Mania in Buffalo\u2019s Italian Community, 1895 to 1918\n |url              = http://wings.buffalo.edu/research/anthrogis/oldsite/JWA/V2N2/Dickson-art.pdf\n |journal          = Journal of World Anthropology: Occasional Papers<!-- : Volume II, Number 2 -->\n |volume           = II\n |issue            = 2\n |publication-date = 2006\n |pages            = 1\u201315\n |access-date      = 2015-03-30\n |archive-url      = https://web.archive.org/web/20150402143811/http://wings.buffalo.edu/research/anthrogis/oldsite/JWA/V2N2/Dickson-art.pdf\n |archive-date     = 2015-04-02\n |url-status         = dead\n}}</ref>]]\nFollowing its invention and development in Italy the [[mandolin]] spread throughout the European continent. The instrument was primarily used in a classical tradition with [[mandolin orchestra]]s, so called ''Estudiantinas'' or in Germany ''Zupforchestern'', appearing in many cities. Following this continental popularity of the mandolin family, local traditions appeared outside Europe in the Americas and in Japan. Travelling mandolin virtuosi like [[Giuseppe Pettine]], [[Raffaele Calace]] and [[Silvio Ranieri]] contributed to the mandolin becoming a \"fad\" instrument in the early 20th century.<ref name=academicpaper/> This \"mandolin craze\" was fading by the 1930s, but just as this practice was falling into disuse, the mandolin found a new niche in American [[country music|country]], [[old-time music]], [[Bluegrass music|bluegrass]] and [[folk music]]. More recently, the [[Baroque]] and [[Classical music|Classical]] mandolin repertory and styles have benefited from the raised awareness of and interest in [[Early music]], with media attention to classical players such as Israeli [[Avi Avital]], Italian [[Carlo Aonzo]] and American [[Joseph Brent]].\n\nSee also: [[History of the mandolin]]\n\n== Algeria ==\n\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n | align = right\n | image1 = Karim tizouiar.jpg\n | width1 = 176\n | alt1 = Karim Tizouiar with a mandole\n | caption1 = Karim Tizouiar with a mandole. His music helps to preserve and revive the [[Amazigh]] language and its heritage.\n\n | image2 =Abderrahmane Abdelli.jpg\n | width2 = 99\n | alt2 = Abderrahmane Abdelli with Algerian mandole\n | caption2  = [[Abderrahmane Abdelli]] with Algerian mandole\n}}\n\nAlgeria was colonized by the French in the 19th century and there were large numbers of Europeans living there during the mandolin's golden age. Mandolins and larger members of the mandolin family were used in orchestras, including orchestras playing native Algerian music. With the decline of the mandolin worldwide, the mandolin became less common until by the 21st century it was rare. However, mandolins and [[mandolas]] are still occasionally made by luthiers. The major mandolin-family instrument in use today is the mandocello-sized [[mondol]] or \"mandole\" (French word for mandola applied to the new instrument). The flatback instrument was the result of a corroboration between an Italian luthier and an Algerian musician and was used initially for [[Chaabi]]. It has since spread to other music forms. Prominent players today include [[Mohamed Rouane]], [[Takfarinas]], Mohamed Abdennour (P'tit Moh), [[Abderrahmane Abdelli]] and Kader Fahem. Past players include [[El Hadj M'Hamed El Anka]], [[Boudjemaa El Ankis]], [[El Hachemi Guerouabi]], [[Amar Ezzahi]], [[Cheikh El Hasnaoui]], and [[Loun\u00e8s Matoub]]. The mondol received some international attention on the movie ''El Gusto'' a featuring the reunion of some chaabi players (including a mondol player) years after the turmoil in Algeria came out in the 2010s.\n\n== Australia ==\n:[[:Category:Australian mandolinists|See Australian mandolinists]]\nThe earliest references to the mandolin in [[Australia]] come from [[Phil Skinner]] (1903\u20131991). In his article \"Recollections\"<ref name=\"Skinner\">Recollections - by Phil Skinner.  FIGA magazine January February 1981 (Fretted Instrument Guild of America)</ref> he mentions a [[Walter Stent]], who was \"active in the early part of the century and organised possibly the first Mandolin Orchestra in [[Sydney]].\"\n\nPhil Skinner played a key role in 20th century development of the mandolin movement in Australia, and was awarded an MBE in 1979 for services to music and the community. He was born Harry Skinner in Sydney in 1903 and started learning [[music]] at age 10 when his uncle tutored him on the [[banjo]]. Skinner began teaching part-time at age 18, until the [[Great Depression]] forced him to begin teaching full-time and learn a broader range of instruments. Skinner founded the Sydney Mandolin Orchestra, the oldest surviving mandolin orchestra in [[Australia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fame.asn.au/sydney/history.htm|title=The Sydney Mandolin Orchestra - history|website=Web.archive.org|accessdate=21 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227174540/http://www.fame.asn.au/sydney/history.htm|archivedate=27 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Sydney Mandolins (Artistic Director: Adrian Hooper) have contributed greatly to the repertoire through commissioning over 200 works by Australian and International composers. Most of these works have been released on Compact Disks and can regularly be heard on radio stations on the ABC and MBS networks. One of their members, mandolin virtuoso Paul Hooper, has had a number of Concertos written for him by composers such as Eric Gross. He has performed and recorded these works with the Sydney Symphony Orchestra and the Tasmanian Symphony Orchestra. As well, Paul Hooper has had many solo works dedicated to him by Australian composers e.g., Caroline Szeto, Larry Sitsky and Michael Smetanin, as well as other works by Robert Allworth and Betty Beath.<!--I trimmed some detail from this that was too off point for the article.-->\n\nIn January 1979, the [[Federation of Australian Mandolin Ensembles]] (FAME) Inc. formed. [[Bruce Morey]] from [[Melbourne]] is the first FAME President. An Australian Mandolin Orchestra toured [[Germany]] in May 1980.\n\nAustralian popular groups such as [[My Friend The Chocolate Cake]] use the mandolin extensively. [[The McClymonts]] also use the mandolin, as do [[Mic Conway|Mic Conway's National Junk Band]] and [[the Blue Tongue Lizards]]. Nevertheless, in folk and traditional styles, the mandolin remains more popular in [[Irish Music]] and other traditional repertoires.\n\n==Austria==\nAs the capital of an empire bordering Italy, musicians traveled to Vienna to work, compose and teach. Vienna was \"the centre for the cultivation of mandolin playing\" in the last part of the 18th century, and music written for mandolin has been preserved there.<ref name=WolkiHistory2>{{cite book |last= W\u00f6lki |first=Konrad |translator-last1= Harris|translator-first1= Keith |date=1984 |title=Geschichte der Mandoline |trans-title= History of the Mandolin |url= |language= English|location= Arlington, Virginia|publisher= Plucked String |page=10 |isbn= |author-link= }}</ref> Composers and players who worked there or whose works have been preserved include [[Leonhard von Call|Leonhard d'Call]], [[Georg Druschetzky]], [[Giovanni Giuliani]], [[Giovanni Hoffmann]], [[Leopold Kozeluch]], [[Karl Stefan Aichelburg|Aichelbourgh]], Giuseppe Blesber, Conrad Schlick (husband to [[Regina Strinasacchi]], [[Leopold Neuhauser]], Vincent Neuling.<ref name=WolkiHistory2/>\n\n== Belgium ==\nIn the early 20th century several mandolin orchestras (Estudiantinas) were active in Belgium. Today only a few groups remain: [http://mandolin.be/ Royal Estudiantina la Napolitaine] (founded in 1904) in [[Antwerp]], [http://brasschaatsmandolineorkest.be/ Brasschaats mandoline orkest] in [[Brasschaat]], the Brugs mandolinegezelschap, the Mandolineclub De Krikskes (Berchem), the Cercle royal des mandolinistes Estudiantina in [[Mons|Mons (Bergen)]], the K\u00f6niglichen Mandolinenorchester Eupen, [https://www.nassognemandoline.be/ the Ensemble de plectres de Nassogne] and the [http://www.mandoline.be/ Cercle royal des mandolinistes de Malmedy].\n\nGerda Abts is a well known mandolin virtuoso in Belgium. She is also mandolin teacher and gives lessons in the music academies of Lier, Wijnegem and Brasschaat. She is now also professor mandolin at the music high school \u201cKoninklijk Conservatorium Artesis Hogeschool Antwerpen\u201d. She also gives various concerts each year in different ensembles. She is in close contact to the Brasschaat mandolin Orchestra. Her site is www.gevoeligesnaar.be\n\n== Brazil ==\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n | align = right\n | image1 = Hamilton de Holanda 25\u00ba Premio da Musica Brasileira(0).jpg\n | width1 = 224\n | alt1 =  Brazilian Mandolin virtuoso Hamilton de Holanda playing a ten-string ''bandolim''\n | caption1 =  Brazilian Mandolin virtuoso Hamilton de Holanda playing a ten-string ''bandolim''.\n\n | image2 =Armandinho - MinC - Comit\u00ea do Patrim\u00f4nio Mundial (19).jpg\n | width2 = 126\n | alt2 = Armandinho (Brazilian guitarist) with bandolim or mandolin\n | caption2  =  Brazilian guitarist [[Armandinho (Brazilian guitarist)|Armandinho]] playing a bandolim.\n}}\n:[[:Category:Brazilian mandolinists|See Brazilian mandolinists]]\n:See also the [[Portuguese guitar]] and [[Portuguese music]].\n\nThe mandolin has a particular shape in [[Brazil]]ian music and is known as the ''bandolim'' in the [[Portuguese language]], which is spoken there. The Portuguese have a long tradition of mandolins and mandolin-like instruments and brought their music to their colonies.\n\nIn modern Brazilian music, the bandolim is almost exclusively a melody instrument, often accompanied by the chordal accompaniment of the [[cavaquinho]], a steel stringed instrument similar to a [[ukulele]]. The bandolim's popularity has risen and fallen with instrumental folk music styles, especially [[choro]]. The later part of the 20th century saw a renaissance of choro in Brazil, and with it, a revival of the country's mandolin tradition. Composer and mandolin virtuoso, [[Jacob do Bandolim]], did much to popularize the instrument through many recordings, and his influence continues to the present day. Some contemporary mandolin players in Brazil include Jacob's disciple [[D\u00e9o Rian]], and [[Hamilton de Holanda]] (the former, a traditional choro-style player, the latter an eclectic innovator.) Another is [[Joel Nascimento]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cliquemusic.uol.com.br/artistas/ver/joel-nascimento|title=Joel Nascimento|author=|date=|website=CliqueMusic.uol.com.br|accessdate=2014-05-30}}</ref>\n\n== China ==\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n | align = left\n | image1 = Liangyou 045 cover - Guan Zilan.jpg\n | width1 = 160\n | alt1 =  Guan Zilan on the cover of Liangyou magazine #45\n | caption1 = 1930 cover of the Chinese magazine ''Li\u00e1ngy\u01d2u'' (''[[The Young Companion]]'') with Chinese painter [[Guan Zilan]] playing a mandolin.\n | image2 =Shanghai-girls-chinese-posters.jpg\n | width2 = 130\n | alt2 = Chinese girl playing mandolin\n | caption2  = Advertising poster for the East Asian Cigarette Company c.&nbsp;1930s, with a girl playing a mandolin.\n}}\n\nWestern instruments such as the guitar, mandolin and ukulele were \"associated with youth and freedom\", \"sophistication and cosmopolitanism\" in Shanghai and Hong Kong in the 1920s and 1930s.<ref name=worldstring>{{cite web |url= http://worldonastringblog.blogspot.com/2012/12/guitars-come-to-china.html?m=1 |title=The First Comes to China |last=Millward |first= Jom|date=30 December 2012 |website= |publisher= |access-date= 26 June 2018|quote=}}</ref>  They appeared in the hands of movie stars and in magazines like [[Ling Long]] with \"fashionable young ladies,\" where they became part of the [[modern girl]] image.<ref name=worldstring/> Modern girls were  college-age women, perceived as active and modern.<ref name=socialmandolin>{{cite web |url= http://wemedia.ifeng.com/6088742/wemedia.shtml|title=\u522b\u627e\u4e86\uff0c\u7f8e\u5973\u90fd\u5728\u8fd9\u513f\u5462\uff0c\u6709\u989c\u6709\u8170\u8fd8\u6709\u817f [translation:  Don't look for it. Beautiful women are here.] |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= |publisher= |access-date=22 June 2018 |quote=[illustration with mandolin is 12th image down] ...characterized by the exquisite water-jet brushing of the Western style...content is mainly about women's social life, such as the campus activities of female college students, women driving motorcycles, swimming, horse riding, horse racing, rowing competitions, and participating in social assistance...no longer important to have advertisements in the 40s. What is important is the United States}}</ref>  Independent and westernized, they  engaged in western recreational activities such as \"driving motorcycles, swimming, horse riding, horse racing, rowing competitions,\" and playing musical instruments.<ref name=socialmandolin/>\n\nArtist Guan Zilan was one such modern girl, educated in Chinese and Japanese colleges.<ref name=moderngirljapan>{{cite book |last=Ikeda |first=Shinobu |chapter=The Allure of a 'Woman in Chinese Dress' |editor-last1=Croissant |editor-first1=Doris |editor-last2=Yeh |editor-first2=Catherine Vance |editor-last3=Mostow |editor-first3=Joshua Scott |title=Performing \"Nation\": Gender Politics in Literature, Theater, and the Visual Arts of China and Japan, 1880\u20131940 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9fNTyTgKRaMC&pg=PA367 |year=2008 |publisher=BRILL |isbn=90-04-17019-7 |page=367}}</ref> Her artwork was displayed in ''The Young Companion'' magazine, and she herself was on the cover with her mandolin.<ref>{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Art style \"Friends\" Illustrated |url= http://cnarts.net/cweb/Exhibition/show/xuanyan/wz-19.asp|magazine= The Young Companion (Li\u00e1ngy\u01d2u pictorial)|location= |publisher= |date= |access-date= 28 June 2018|quote=\"Best Friends\", Issue 57, 1930, \"Ms. Guan Zilan's Personal Exhibition\" Special Edition Liangyou Magazine Co., Ltd.}}</ref>\n\nMandolins were also seen in Shanghai in an advertisement poster of the East Asia Cigarette Company, which showed a woman, well-dressed, holding a mandolin.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.1930shanghai.com/items/90802/Lady-playing-Musical-Instrument-Poster|title=1930 Shanghai and more, Lady playing Musical Instrument Poster |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= 1930shanghai.com|publisher= |access-date= 22 June 2018|quote=advertisement poster from 1930 Shanghai era is a cigarette advertisement for \"East Asia Cigarette Company\".}}</ref> A variation of this image was used elsewhere as a calendar illustration.<ref>{{cite web |url=  http://www.sohu.com/a/191045047_781133|title=\u8001\u4e0a\u6d77\u753b\u7247\u91cc\u7684\u6c11\u56fd\u7f8e\u5973 [translation: The beauty of the Republic of China in old Shanghai paintings]|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= sohu.com|publisher= |access-date=22 June 2018 |quote=[illustration, 27th image down] Foreign capitalists quickly learned from the use of the \u201ccalendar painting\u201d style with calendar solar terms in Chinese traditional folk paintings and incorporated them into product advertisements...a record of the side of an era of the Republic of China (1912-1949)}}</ref>\n\nAlthough prominent in media in the hands of women, the instruments were not solely women's. Young men in western-run schools could choose them up as part of their education. Trying to be like his brother, [[Chou Wen-Chung]] was able to \"dabble in\" the mandolin at a school in [[Nanjing]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Chang |first= Peter M.|date= 2006 |title=Chou Wen-Chung: The Life and Work of a Contemporary Chinese-born American Composer |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=n2cazQcTvBsC&lpg=PA16&dq=shanghai%20mandolin&pg=PA16#v=onepage&q=shanghai%20mandolin&f=false |location= |publisher= Scarecrow Press |chapter=2 |page=16 |isbn= |author-link= }}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1920s and 30s when the mandolin came to China, its popularity had peaked worldwide. Although the imported western instruments never became common in China, they were advertised for sale in Shanghai in 1920, in English-language publications, such as  ''Our Navy, the Standard Publication of the U.S. Navy''.<ref name=navychina>{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Everything Musical, Go to Moutrie's|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=FIM9AQAAMAAJ&lpg=RA5-PA49&dq=shanghai%20mandolin&pg=RA5-PA50#v=onepage&q&f=false|magazine= Our Navy, the Standard Publication of the U.S. Navy|location= |publisher= |date= 1920 |access-date= 26 June 2018|quote=...For American Banjos,Mandolins, and Guitars...Honking, Shanghai, Tientsin}}</ref> When popularity for the fad began to fade after World War 1, China's neighbor Japan was an exception to that; mandolins were still popular and their use growing. Japan had commercial ties to coastal China, the very area from which the magazines and advertisements arose.\n\nDuring the Chinese Cultural Revolution (1966-1976) it became dangerous in China to stick out from other people. The establishment feared \"the taint of foreign ideas\" and tried to root out   the \u201crepresentatives of the bourgeoisie who have sneaked into ... various spheres of culture.\u201d<ref>{{cite magazine |last= Osnos|first= Evan |date= 6 May 2016|title= The Cost of the Cultural Revolution, Fifty Years Later |url= https://www.newyorker.com/news/daily-comment/the-cost-of-the-cultural-revolution-fifty-years-later/amp |magazine= New Yorker |location= |publisher= |access-date=26 June 2018 }}</ref> Western classical music largely came to an end in China during the Cultural Revolution, when \"listening to Beethoven became a political crime.\"<ref name=culturalrevchina>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/jul/08/after-the-cultural-revolution-what-western-classical-music-means-in-china |title=After the Cultural Revolution: what western classical music means in China |last= Thien|first= Madeleine |date=8 July 2016 |website= |publisher= The Guardian|access-date= 23 June 2018|quote=}}</ref> At the Shanghai Conservatory of Music, western musical instruments were destroyed.<ref name=culturalrevchina/>\n\n== Croatia ==\n[[File:Young-woman-with-a-mandolin-vekoslav-karas.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Painting by [[Croatia|Croation]] painter [[Vjekoslav Karas]], c.&nbsp;1845-1847. ''Rimljanka s lutnjom'' (''A romance with a lullabies'').]]\n\nThe mandolin is staple of folk and traditional music on the Croatian coast.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mandolincafe.com/forum/archive/index.php/t-102279.html |title=Croatian luthier introduction (forum discussion) |last1=Glas |first1=Kruno |last2= |first2= |date=13 January 2014 |website=mandolincafe.com |publisher=Mandolin Cafe |accessdate=2016-10-11 |quote=Mandolins are most popular in the coastal area of Croatia and not so much inland because in the 90s the focus was on tamburitza. So, mandolin was a bit neglected.}}</ref> Croatian painter [[Vjekoslav Karas]] (1821-1858) painted an image of a girl playing a mandolin in about 1845.\n\n== Czech and Slovak republics ==\n:[[:Category:Czech mandolinists|See Czech mandolinists]], [[Czech bluegrass]]\nFrom Italy mandolin music extended in popularity throughout Europe in the early 20th century, with mandolin orchestras appearing throughout the continent.\n\nIn the 21st century an increased interest in [[bluegrass music]], especially in Central European countries such as the [[Czech Republic]] and [[Slovakia|Slovak Republic]], has inspired many new mandolin players and builders. These players often mix traditional folk elements with bluegrass. Radim Zenkl came from this tradition, emigrating to the United States, where he has played with U.S. stars, including [[David Grisman]] and [[B\u00e9la Fleck]].\n\n== Finland ==\n[[File:Finnish mandolin makers.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Finnish soldiers from 1943 with 12-string mandolins. One of the soldiers, Private T\u00f6rr\u00f6nen was credited as the luthier.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mandolincafe.com/forum/threads/101928-Finnish-1943-mandolins-from-a-public-war-history-photo-collection |title=Finnish 1943 mandolins from a public war history photo collection |website=Mandolin Cafe Forum |accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> Mandolin in bottom left is strung.]]\n\nFinland has mandolin players rooted in the folk music scene. Prominent names include Petri Hakala, Seppo Sillanp\u00e4\u00e4 and Heikki Lahti, who have taught and recorded albums. Classical music is also represented with players such as Risto Aalto.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.mandolincafe.com/forum/showthread.php?92168-Finnish-mandolin-players-playing-Chris-Thile-s-music-Bach-etc |title= Finnish mandolin players playing Chris Thile's music, Bach etc.|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= January 2013 |website=mandolincafe.com |publisher= |access-date= 28 May 2018 |quote=}}</ref> A Finnish immigrant to the United States [[Arthur Kylander]] became a recording contract there in 1927, releasing 20 recordings with Victor Records, playing mandolin.\n\n== France ==\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n | align = right\n | image2 = Woman holding a mandolin by Kuroda Seiki (Kuroda Kinenkan).jpg\n | width2 = 141\n | alt2 = Woman holding a mandolin, by Kuroda Seiki\n | caption2 = Painting by [[Kuroda Seiki]], ''Woman holding a mandolin'', 1891. He was a Japanese painter living in France.\n\n| image3 =Scribner's magazine (1887) (14801544383).jpg\n | width3 = 170\n | alt3 = Charles Auguste \u00c9mile Durand, Poet with Mandolin\n | caption3  = Painting by [[Carolus-Duran|Charles Auguste \u00c9mile Durand]], ''The Poet with the Mandolin'', published in [[Scribner's Magazine]], 1887.\n}}\n\nIn the 21st century, some have perceived a \"rebirth\" of the mandolin in France.<ref name=castellar>{{cite web |url= https://www.festivalmandoline.fr/a-propos/la-mandoline/ |title= Festival International de Mandoline de Castellar Du 17 au 20 juillet 2019|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= festivalmandoline.fr|publisher= |access-date= 27 April 2019 |quote=}}</ref> Although an \"Italian\" instrument, France had a history with the mandolin family going back centuries, to the [[gittern]]s (12th-14th centuries), and the [[mandore (instrument)|mandore]] arrived from Spain about 1570.<ref name=castellar/> One of the earliest surviving books of mandore music, the ''Music Tablature of Fran\u00e7ois de Chancey'' was published in 1629 and featured music for the French court.<ref name=castellar/> It was dedicated to the [[Cardinal Richelieu|Duke of Richelieu]], Prime Minister of [[Louis XIII]].<ref name=castellar/>\n\nPrior to the ''Golden Age of Mandolins'', France had a history with the mandolin, with mandolinists playing in Paris until the Napoleonic Wars.<ref name=\"Sparks1\">{{harvnb|Sparks|2003|page=1}}</ref>  The players, teachers and composers included [[Giovanni Fouchetti]], [[Eduardo Mezzacapo]], [[Gabriele Leone]], and [[Giovanni Battista Gervasio]].<ref name=\"Sparks98-109\">{{harvnb|Sparks|2003|page=98\u2013109}}</ref> From the mid 1750s until the Napoleanic War, virtuosos traveled Europe, performing, teaching and composing, many settling in France. Leone settled in Paris, Gervasio in [[Grenoble]]. Beginning with the French Revolution, the instrument declined from formal performance and \"eclypsed\" by 1820.<ref name=castellar/> It was rediscovered when the Spanish Students came to Paris for the Carnival of 1878. This was the beginning of the \"Golden Age\" of mandolins. During the Golden age itself (1880s-1920s), the mandolin had a strong presence in France. By the beginning of the 20th century, Paris had at least 30 mandolin orchestras.<ref name=castellar/> Prominent mandolin players or composers included [[Jules Cottin]] and his sister Madeleine Cottin, Jean Pietrapertosa, and [[Edgar Bara]].<ref name=\"Sparks98-109\"/> Paris had dozens of \"estudiantina\" mandolin orchestras in the early 1900s.<ref name=\"Sparks98-109\"/> Mandolin magazines included ''L'Estudiantina'', ''Le Plectre'', ''\u00c9cole de la mandolie''.<ref name=\"Sparks98-109\"/>\n\nWorld War I marks the end of the golden age, as a \"wave of American music at the Liberation buried the mandolin orchestras.\"<ref name=castellar/>\n\nIn the 21st century, interest in Baroque music has inspired a revival of concert mandolins for classical music, as musicians have begun rediscovering the \"great reperatoire.\"<ref name=castellar/> Partly this has been fed by the classical mandolin music tradition, preserved in Japan and Korea.<ref name=castellar/> French culture accepts music from around the globe, including former colonies \u2014 the [[Maghreb]].<ref name=castellar/> Algeria in particular had a mandolin culture and created its own mandolin family instrument, [[Algerian mandole|the mandole]]. Other mandolin imports to France include Latin music from South America, American bluegrass mandolin, and the \"plectrum instruments\" of Slavic culture.<ref name=castellar/>\n\nToday, French mandolinists include Patrick Vaillant, a prominent modern player, composer and recording artist for the mandolin, who also organizes courses for aspiring players.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mandopolis.org/?p=1419#comments |title=Stage de Mandoline avec Patrick Vaillant, \u00e0 Pigna ! |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= November 26, 2012|website= |publisher= |access-date= September 22, 2015|quote=Partant, am\u00e9liorer ses performances mandolinistiques et \u00e9tendre son domaine musical, acc\u00e9der mieux arm\u00e9 \u00e0 l'improvisation.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.livioufestival.com/patrick-vaillant-daniel-malavergne-2/ |title=Patrick VVaillant and Daniel Malevergna |website= livioufestival.com|publisher= |access-date= September 22, 2015|quote=Son bagage traditionnel, son go\u00fbt de l'improvisation, une inspiration travers\u00e9e de M\u00e9diterran\u00e9e et de jazz, l'originalit\u00e9 de son jeu comme de ses compositions, ont fait de lui un mandoliniste internationalement reconnu}}</ref>\n\n== Germany ==\n[[File:Fotothek df roe-neg 0006329 013 Mandolinenspielerin.jpg|thumb|right|upright|A woman playing a bowlback mandolin in Germany in 1952.]]\n\nThe [[Mandore (instrument)|mandore]] was known in Germany, prior to the invention of the Neapolitan mandolin.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Tyler |first=James |last2= |first2= |date=January 1981 |title=The Mandore in the 16th and 17th Centuries |url=http://le.luth.free.fr/mandore/articles/01-Tyler_mandore.pdf |journal=Early Music |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=2, 3 |doi= 10.1093/earlyj/9.1.22|access-date=21 October 2016|quote=...Under the name quintern the mandore is familiar to us from the illustrations found in Sebastian Virdung's Musica getutscht (1511) and Martin Agricola's Musica Instrumentalis Duedsch (1528)...Praetorius....gives an illustration of a Mandoraen... }}</ref> The mandolin spread to Germany with the visits of Italian mandolin virtuosi, including Achille Coronati.<ref name=germansparks>{{cite book |last=Sparks |first=Paul |date=1995 |title=The Classical Mandolin |url= |location=Oxford |publisher=Clarendon Press |pages=115\u2013117 |isbn=978-0-19-517337-6}}</ref> [[George Frideric Handel]] composed ''[[Alexander Balus]]'' in 1748. When the mandolin declined in much of Europe after the French Revolution, it found some energy in Bohemia, Germany and Vienna.<ref name=castellar/> [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart]] placed it in his 1787 work ''[[Don Giovanni]]'', and Beethoven  [[Beethoven's mandolin|experimented with four compositions]] in 1795 and 1796. [[Johann Nepomuk Hummel]] created a mandolin concerto in 1799 and a mandolin and piano sonata.<ref name=castellar/>\n\nThe mandolin gained popularity as a folk instrument, especially with the groups of youth participating in the [[German youth movement]], which began in 1897.<ref name=germansparks/> In the early 20th century the mandolin was popular in the [[Wandervogel]] movement (groups of young men and women, hiking and camping, singing and playing instruments), due to the instrument's small size.<ref name=germansparks/>\n\nThe mandolin became increasingly popular in contemporary music during the 20th century. An important German composer for mandolin and mandolin orchestra of the 20th century was [[Konrad W\u00f6lki]]; he was instrumental in bringing musicological recognition of the mandolin and the orchestra. Mandolin orchestras are still playing in Germany, in various chamber music ensembles and as a solo instrument. The instrument is popular enough today that there is an increasing number of professional mandolin players and composers writing new works for the mandolin.\n\nAt the college level the mandolin has a presence, in the professorial chair for mandolins, chaired by Caterina Lichtenberg. She succeeded Marga Wilden-H\u00fcsgen at the Hochschule f\u00fcr Musik und Tanz K\u00f6ln, in Wuppertal. Another program with specialized training for students offering a diploma in this instrument takes place by Gertrud Weyhofen at the Music Academy Kassel and more recently at the University of Music Saar and by Steffen Trekel at Hamburg Conservatory.\n\nThe instrument was present in the folk revival of the 1970s. One mandolin player was Erich Schmeckenbecher in the duo ''[[Zupfgeigenhansel]]''. Comedian Hans S\u00fcper played a modified mandolin, which he called his \"Bovec,\" in the duo ''Colonia''.\n\n== Greece ==\nThe mandolin has a long tradition in the [[Ionian Sea|Ionian]] islands (the ''[[Heptanese]]'') and [[Crete]], and later in the Urban centers of Southern Mainland Greece. It has long been played in the [[Aegean Sea|Aegean]] islands outside the control of the [[Ottoman Empire]]. It is common to see [[Cantata#The kantades of the Ionian Islands|choirs accompanied by mandolin players]] (the ''mandolin\u00e1tes'') in the [[Ionian islands]] and especially in the cities of [[Corfu]], [[Zakynthos]], [[Lefkada]] and [[Kefalonia]]. The evolution of the repertoire for choir and mandolins (''kant\u00e1des'') occurred during [[Venice|Venetian]] rule over the islands.\n\nOn the island of [[Crete]], along with the [[Lyra (Cretan)|lyra]] and the laouto ([[lute]]), the mandolin is one of the main instruments used in [[Music of Crete|Cretan Music]]. It appeared on Crete around the time of the Venetian rule of the island. Different variants of the mandolin, such as the \"mantola,\" were used to accompany the lyra, the [[violin]], and the laouto. Stelios Foustalierakis reported that the mandolin and the ''mpoulgari'' were used to accompany the lyra in the beginning of the 20th century in the city of Rethimno. There are also reports that the mandolin was mostly a woman's musical instrument. Nowadays it is played mainly as a solo instrument in personal and family events on the [[Ionian Sea|Ionian]] islands and Crete.\n\n[[Nikolaos Lavdas]] was a significant composer and mandolinists for Greece, who was the founder and director of the \"[https://athenianmandolinata.com/about/ Athenian Mandolinata]\", one of the oldest music associations and music schools in Greece.<ref>{{cite book |title=Art music in the Balkans |last=Shupo |first=Sokol |page=63 |year=2004 |publisher=ASMUS |oclc=443331457 }}</ref>\n\n== India ==\n:[[:Category:Indian mandolinists|See Indian mandolinists]]\n[[File:U. Srinivas.jpg|thumb|right|U. Srinivas]]\nMandolin music was used in Indian movies as far back as the 1940s by the [[Raj Kapoor]] Studios in movies such as [[Barsaat (1949 film)|Barsaat]]. The movie [[Dilwale Dulhania Le Jayenge]] (1995) used mandolin in several places. Bollywood music composer [[Sajjad Hussain (composer)|Ustad Sajjad Hussain]] (1917 \u2013 1995) played the mandolin as a \"Top Grade\" player for the Indian film industry in Mumbai for more than five decades and was reputed to have played more than 22,000 songs, including title-songs and background music.<ref name=Hussain>{{cite web |url= http://meetkalakar.com/Artist/1509-Mustafa-Sajjad-Hussain |title= Mustafa Sajjad Hussain, Mandolin artist|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=Meetkalakar.com |publisher= |access-date= 30 August 2018|quote=}}</ref> Besides the music for movies, he was known to play Indian classical music (Hindustani), as well as Arab and Sufi music.<ref name=Hussain/>\n\nAdoption of the mandolin in [[Carnatic music]] is recent and involves an electric instrument. [[U. Srinivas]] (1969-2014) has, over the last couple of decades, made his version of the mandolin very popular in India and abroad.\n\nMany adaptations of the instrument have been done to cater to the special needs of Indian Carnatic music.\nIn [[Indian classical music]] and Indian light music, the mandolin, which bears little resemblance to the European mandolin, is usually tuned E\u2013B\u2013E\u2013B. As there is no concept of absolute pitch in Indian classical music, any convenient tuning maintaining these relative pitch intervals between the strings can be used. Another prevalent tuning with these intervals is C\u2013G\u2013C\u2013G, which corresponds to ''sa\u2013pa\u2013sa\u2013pa'' in the Indian carnatic classical music style. This tuning corresponds to the way violins are tuned for carnatic classical music. This type of mandolin is also used in [[Bhangra (music)|Bhangra]], dance music popular in Punjabi culture.\n\n[[Uppalapu Rajesh]] is another performer using the mandolin in Indian music, playing Indian classical music, jazz-fusion, and world music. He was nominated for a Grammy in 2009.<ref name=\"CR2\">{{cite news|title= Soul Strings: U Rajesh on the legacy of playing an Italian lute in the Carnatic classical system |url= http://indianexpress.com/article/lifestyle/art-and-culture/u-rajesh-soul-strings-4803160/ |newspaper=[[The Indian Express]] |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180322204500/http://indianexpress.com/article/lifestyle/art-and-culture/u-rajesh-soul-strings-4803160/ |archivedate= 22 March 2018 }}</ref> He is brother to U. Srinivas.\n\n== Ireland ==\n:[[:Category:Irish mandolinists|See Irish mandolinists]]\nThe mandolin has become a more common instrument amongst Irish traditional musicians. Fiddle tunes are readily accessible to the mandolin player because of the equivalent tuning and range of the two instruments, and the practically identical (allowing for the lack of frets on the fiddle) left hand fingerings.\n\nThough almost any variety of acoustic mandolin might be adequate for Irish traditional music, virtually all Irish players prefer flat-backed instruments with oval sound holes to the Italian-style bowl-back mandolins or the carved-top mandolins with f-holes favoured by [[Bluegrass music|bluegrass]] mandolinists. The former are often too soft-toned to hold their own in a session (as well as having a tendency to not stay in place on the player's lap), whilst the latter tend to sound harsh and overbearing to the traditional ear. The f-hole mandolin, however, does come into its own in a traditional session, where its brighter tone cuts through the sonic clutter of a pub. Greatly preferred for formal performance and recording are flat-topped \"Irish-style\" mandolins (reminiscent of the WWI-era Martin Army-Navy mandolin) and carved (arch) top mandolins with oval soundholes, such as the Gibson A-style of the 1920s.\n\nNoteworthy Irish mandolinists include [[Andy Irvine (musician)|Andy Irvine]] (who, like [[Johnny Moynihan]], almost always tunes the top E down to D, to achieve an open tuning of G\u2013D\u2013A\u2013D),<ref name=\"Walsh\">{{cite book|last1=\u00d3 Callanain|first1= Niall|last2=Walsh|first2= Tommy|year=1989|title= The Irish Bouzouki|location=Ireland|publisher= Waltons|isbn= 0-7866-1595-8}}</ref>{{rp|38}} [[Paul Brady]], [[Mick Moloney]], [[Paul Kelly (Irish musician)|Paul Kelly]] and Claudine Langille. [[John Sheahan]] and the late [[Barney McKenna]], respectively fiddle player and tenor banjo player with [[the Dubliners]], are also accomplished Irish mandolin players. The instruments used are either flat-backed, oval hole examples as described above (made by UK luthier Roger Bucknall of Fylde Guitars), or carved-top, oval hole instruments with arched back (made by Stefan Sobell in Northumberland). The Irish guitarist [[Rory Gallagher]] often played the mandolin on stage, and he most famously used it in the song \"Going To My Hometown.\"\n\n== Israel ==\n:[[:Category:Israeli mandolinists|See Israeli mandolinists]]\n\nThe re-founding of Israel after World War II drew people from all across the world. Among them were people from Eastern European countries, where mandolin orchestras had been in use before the war. Researchers, such as Jeff Warschauer have gone to Israel, seeking to preserve klesmer music and Yiddish songs.<ref name=cantor/>\n\nMandolin orchestras were founded in the 1920s in the pioneering settlement in the Jezreel Valley and in the Jordan Valley by a teacher named Goldman. The orchestra in the Jordan Valley continues to operate today.\n\nThe oldest of the mandolin orchestras, which has been continuously active since the 1940s, is the Shfeya Orchestra, founded by Moshe Medalia, and today made up of graduates from the Shfeya Youth Village.<ref name=moshe>{{cite web |url= http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3690289,00.html|title=The student who became a music teacher  |last=Man |first=Nadav |date=23 March 2009 |website=ynetnews.com |publisher= |access-date=29 May 2017 |quote=}}</ref> The village is a boarding school for at-risk junior and senior high-school students.<ref name=school>{{cite web |url=http://www.hadassah.org/connecting-to-israel/youth-aliyah.html |title=Our Villages, Meir Shfeyah |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= hadassah.org|publisher= |access-date= 29 May 2017|quote=}}</ref> Part of the education includes students working together in small groups, teaching music to one another.<ref name=moshe/> There wasn't much in the way of learning materials when Moshe Jacobson, founder of the music program arrived in 1942. So he wrote text books for the instruments and composed music and songs.<ref name=moshe/>\n\n[[Shimon Peres]] was an example of someone who brought his musical background. Peres, (born Szymon Perski), grew up in the then Polish town of [[Vishnyeva]], was part of a mandolin orchestra when he was a child.<ref name=speres>{{cite news | url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/larger-than-life-shimon-peres-a-legacy-in-pictures/ | title=Larger than life: Shimon Peres, a legacy in pictures | newspaper=[[The Times of Israel]] | author=Raphael Ahren | date=2016-09-28 | accessdate=2017-05-29}}</ref>  The Vishnyeva orchestra of which he was part of was immortalized in a black-and-white photography, a group of young people dressed up holding their mandolins.<ref name=speres/> Although busy with his political career, Peres remained musical for the rest of his life, composing songs in his home in Israel.<ref name=\"auto4\">[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/32453580/ns/world_news-wonderful_world/t/poems-turn-song-israeli-ex-leader-turns/#.V-ta_fl97IU Poems turn to song as ex-leader turns 86] AP, updated August 17, 2009 7:55:07 PM ET</ref>\n\nIsrael today has four especially prominent mandolinists: [[Avi Avital]],<ref name=israel1>[http://www.thebluegrassspecial.com/archive/2011/jan2011/bordercrossingjan2011.php Artist To Artist: 10 Minutes With Avi Avital.] ''The Bluegrass Special'', January 2011 by Joe Brent.</ref> Alon Sariel,<ref name=israel2>{{cite web| url=http://www.mandolin.org.uk/interviews/sariel.php| title=Alon Sariel interview| last=| first=| date=| website=Mandolin.org.uk| publisher=| access-date=September 3, 2015| quote=What mandolins do you own? Which one(s) is(are) your favourite(s)? Whoever knows the Beer-Sheva school of mandolin must have heard of the Israeli type of modern mandolins. A mandolin maker called Arik Kerman who lives in Tel-Aviv, invented a formula to make the mandolin in a way for which it has a much of a round and sweet sound, and can easily produce a very soft sound other than the metallic Neapolitan one...}}</ref><ref name=israel3>{{cite web|url=http://www.alon-sariel.com/repertoire/instrumentarium/|title=Instrumentarium|author=|date=|website=Alon Sariel \u2013 mandolinist, conductor, lutenist|accessdate=16 March 2018}}</ref> [[Jacob Reuven]],<ref name=mandoKerman>{{cite web| url=http://www.mandolincafe.com/forum/showthread.php?102738-Avi-Avital-and-the-Arik-Kerman-mandolin| title=Thread: Avi Avital and the Arik Kerman mandolin| last=| first=| date=| website=mandolincafe.com| publisher=| access-date=September 3, 2015| quote=This thread digressed into the topic of Avi's Kerman, where it was established that it has a double top and a convex back. \u2026 it looks like it is based on the modern German flatback as made by makers such as Seifert, a little deep-bodied. The difference from the German models is that it has the sound holes on the edges and, even more important(?) has a double top.}}</ref> and Tom Cohen.<ref name=israel4>{{cite web| url=http://frusion.co.uk/artists/concert/global/Tom_Cohen.html| title=Concert artists: Tom Cohen| last=| first=| date=| website=frusion.co.uk| publisher=| access-date=September 3, 2015| quote=The mandolin that Tom plays was built especially for him by Israeli artist Arik Kerman and new instrument is currently being built for, and inspired by him, by internationally-known luthier Boaz Elkayam.}}</ref> Another is composer [[Shaul Bustan]], whose works include a ''Concerto for Mandolin and Accordion'' (2010) and an arrangement of Mozart's ''Symphony No 40 in G minor'' for mandolin, mandola, guitar and double bass (2014).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shaulbustan.com |title= Shaul Bustan, composer, conductor and multi-instrumentalist |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=Shaulbustan.com |publisher= |access-date=1 July 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n== Italy ==\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n | align = right\n|header=19th-century visitors to Italy capture mandolin in art\n| \n| image3 = Chase William Merritt The Mandolin Player 1878.jpg\n | width3 = 149\n | alt3 = 1924 Gibson F-5 mandolin\n | caption3  = ''The Mandolin Player'' by [[William Merritt Chase]] (1879). He visited Italy 1877-1878. The mandolin in the painting was among his props in the USA.<ref name=globe>{{cite news |last= Guerrieri |first= Matthew|date=20 October 2016 |title= Exotic collection was instrumental for painter William Merritt Chase|url= https://www2.bostonglobe.com/arts/music/2016/10/20/exotic-collection-was-instrumental-for-painter-william-merritt-chase/CxdPlbK0ISoU8doT4AxLfN/story.html|work= Boston Globe|location= Boston, Massachusetts|access-date= 28 April 2019|quote=A few made their way into Chase\u2019s art: \u201cThe Mandolin Player\u201d (1879) plucks Chase\u2019s fanciest specimen, a Spanish instrument with inlaid mother-of-pearl }}</ref>\n\n|image2= Schwarz 1851.jpg\n | width2 = 150\n | alt2 = Gibson A4 mandolin\n | caption2  =Estonia/Russia, ''The Mandolin Player'' by [[Julie Wilhelmine Hagen-Schwarz]], 1851.<ref name=kusnt>{{cite web |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080309083045/http://www.tartmus.ee/et/kogud/schwarz.html |title= Julie Hagen-Schwarz Mandoliinim\u00e4ngija. 1851 \u00d5li, l\u00f5uend. 157 x 106,5|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= liveestonia.com|publisher= |access-date=28 April 2019 |quote=}}</ref> She visited Italy for several years, when this was painted.\n\n | image1 = Duret Vendangeur.jpg\n | width1 = 166\n | alt1 = Painting, Grape-picker Extemporing, by Francisque Joseph Duret, 1839\n | caption1 = French sculptor [[Francisque Joseph Duret]] visited Naples and made ''Grape-picker Extemporizing'' by 1839. The mandolin was a folk instrument for most of the 19th century.\n\n}}\n:[[:Category:Italian mandolinists|See Italian mandolinists]]\nImportant performers in the Italian tradition include [[Raffaele Calace]] (luthier, virtuoso and composer of 180 works for many instruments including mandolin), [[Pietro Denis]] (who also composed ''Sonata for mandolin & continuo No. 1 in D major'' and ''Sonata No. 3''), [[Giovanni Fouchetti]], [[Gabriele Leone]], [[Carlo Munier]] (1859\u20131911), [[Giuseppe Branzoli]] (1835\u20131909), [[Giovanni Gioviale]] (1885\u20131949) and [[Silvio Ranieri]] (1882\u20131956).<ref name=lgma>[http://www.mandolinscotland.org/home/Newsletters/LGMA_SPRING_2007_NEWSLETTER3.pdf Ian Pommerenke, ''The Mandolin in the early to mid 19th Century'', Lanarkshire Guitar and Mandolin Association Newsletter, Spring 2007.]</ref><ref name=lgma2>[http://www.mandolinscotland.org/home/Newsletters/LGMA_November_2006_Newsletter.pdf Ian Pommerenke, ''The Mandolin the early 18th Century'', Lanarkshire Guitar and Mandolin Association Newsletter, November 2006.]</ref>\n\n[[Antonio Vivaldi]] composed a mandolin concerto (''Concerto in C major op.3 no.6'') and two concertos for two mandolins and orchestra.\n\n[[Antonio Maria Bononcini]] composed ''La conquista delle Spagne di Scipione Africano il giovane'' in 1707. Others include [[Giovanni Battista Gervasio]] (''Sonata in D major for Mandolin and Basso Continuo''), [[Giuseppe Giuliano]] (''Sonata in D major for Mandolin and Basso Continuo''), [[Emanuele Barbella]] (''Sonata in D major for Mandolin and Basso Continuo''), [[Domenico Scarlatti]] (''Sonata no.54 (K.89) in D minor for Mandolin and Basso Continuo''), and [[Addiego Guerra]] (''Sonata in G major for Mandolin and Basso Continuo'').<ref name=lgma/><ref name=recording>{{cite AV media |url=http://www.claudiorecords.com/detail/taylor.html |people=Frances Taylor, mandolinist |title=Italian Mandolin Sonatas |via=Claudio Records |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304002201/http://www.claudiorecords.com/detail/taylor.html |archive-date=2016-03-04}}</ref>\n\nMore contemporary composers for the mandolin include [[Giuseppe Anedda]] (a virtuoso performer and teacher of the first chair of the Conservatory of Italian mandolin), [[Carlo Aonzo]] and [[Dorina Frati]].\n\n=== Cultural ghettoization and revival in Naples ===\n\nIn the late 20th century, information on the instrument, especially its history became hard to find in Naples, where there instrument was born.<ref name=foolk>{{cite web |url= http://www.blogfoolk.com/2017/01/splendori-musicali-settecenteschi.html?m=1|title=Splendori musicali settecenteschi, \"Mandolini al Cinema\" e Pink Floyd a pizzico: intervista al maestro e outsider del mandolino Mauro Squillante (translation: Splendors eighteenth-century music, \"Mandolins at the Cinema\" and Pink Floyd to pinch: interview with the teacher and outsiders mandolin Mauro Squillante) |last= De Rosa|first= Ciro|date= 17 January 2017|website= blogfoolk.com|publisher= |access-date=8 July 2017i |quote=}}</ref>\n\nHistorian Konrad W\u00f6lki commented on this in 1939, suggesting that after only 100 years, there was a disturbing ignorance of the mandolin's history among Italian specialists.<ref name=WolkiHistory1>{{cite book |last= W\u00f6lki |first=Konrad |translator-last1= Harris|translator-first1= Keith |date=1984 |title=Geschichte der Mandoline |trans-title= History of the Mandolin |url= |language= English|location= Arlington, Virginia|publisher= Plucked String |page=12 |isbn= |author-link= }}</ref> He felt that mandolinists must have fared better away from home and left \"hardly any evidence of classical Italian mandolin music in Italy itself.\"<ref name=WolkiHistory1/> His lists of places where the mandolin did better include Vienna, France and Germany.<ref name=WolkiHistory1/>\n\nThe term ''cultural ghettoization'' has been used to describe the situation where no information is readily available about the mandolin's history, its luthiers, composers, musicians, and the relationship of the instrument to folk music and the \"classic Neapolitan song\".<ref name=foolk/> Tourists arriving in the city were more likely to find such information elsewhere.<ref name=foolk/> The city had moved on from mandolins and didn't place particular emphasis on remembering their history or place in Neapolitan culture.<ref name=foolk/>\n\nFurthermore, throughout Italy there was a similar slide. By 1992 there was only one active chair remaining for mandolins at the country's conservatories, the Pollini Conservatory of Padua.<ref name=esspr>{{cite web |url=http://www.espressonapoletano.it/il-mandolino-trova-casa/#.WWI0gZ9MEwj |title= \n(Translation: The mandolin is home) |last=Esposito |first=Ornella |date= 8 February 2017|website= Espressonapoletano.it|access-date= 9 July 2017|quote=}}</ref>\n\nSince then there has been some progress made to revive the mandolin and knowledge of it.\n\nProjects to address the lack of visibility of the mandolin and its history include the formation of a Neapolitan Mandolin Association in 1988,  the restarting of the Neapolitan Mandolin Academy in 1992, and the creation of the Mandolin House.<ref name=foolk/>\n\nThe Neapolitan Mandolin Academy is a school in Naples offering a specialized course of study in the mandolin.\n\nThe Mandolin House is a restored house in via Duomo that has room for concerts, and which offers classes to international visitors, as well as serving as an information point for tourists.<ref name=esspr/> The crowdfunded project was in part begun by the efforts of [[Mauro Squillante]] as he tried to revive the mandolin tradition.<ref name=esspr/> He wanted a place in which to give concerts, do training and give exhibitions.<ref name=esspr/>\n\nAnother sign of progress is the growth of the mandolin within the college education system. While in 1992 there was only one active conservatory chair for mandolins, at Padua (instructor [[Dorina Frati]]), today there are also the [[Music conservatories of Naples]], the Conservatorio di Milan (mandolin professor [[Ugo Orlandi]]), the Conservatorio di Musica \"Niccol\u00f2 Piccinni\" in Bari (instructor [[Mauro Squillante]]), the Conservatorio di Musica \"Nicola Sala\" in Benevento (instructor [[Nunzio Reina]]), and conservatories in Palermo, and Salerno as well.<ref name=esspr/><ref name=foolk/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.conservatorio.bn.it/index.php?p=274 |title= MANDOLINO, REINA NUNZIO|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= conservatorio.bn.it|publisher= Conservatorio Statale di Musica Nicola Sala |access-date=10 July 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n== Japan ==\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n | align = right\n | image1 = Poster of Sakura Beer 2 by Kitano Tsunetomi.jpg\n | width1 = 132\n | alt1 = Kitano Tsunetomi artwork on Sakura beer poster\n | caption1 = Japan, 1916, Sakura beer poster with girl playing mandolin. Art by [[Kitano Tsunetomi]].\n\n| image2= Morishige Takei 01.jpg\n | width2 = 150\n | alt2 = Morishige Takei in 1913\n | caption2  =Morishige Takei in 1913. \n}}\n\nInstruments of the mandolin family are popular in Japan, particularly Neapolitan (round-back) style instruments, and Roman-Embergher style mandolins are still being made there.<ref name=Sparks174-177>{{harvnb|Sparks|2003|page=174\u2013177}}</ref> Japan became seriously interested in mandolins at the beginning of the 20th century during a process of becoming westernized.<ref name=Sparks133-134>{{harvnb|Sparks|2003|page=133\u2013134}}</ref> In 1901, musical educator Kimihachi Hiruma (1867-1936) returned home to Japan after studying the mandolin.<ref name=Hiruma>{{cite web |url=https://www.ikegaku.co.jp/freshmandolin_his.htm |title=\u30de\u30f3\u30c9\u30ea\u30f3\u306e\u751f\u307e\u308c\u3068\u4f1d\u6765 (Birth and Inheritance of the Mandolin) |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=ikegaku.co.jp |publisher=ikegaku I Mandolini a congresso |access-date=22 May 2016 |quote=\u672c\u683c\u7684\u306a\u666e\u53ca\u306f\u3001\u6771\u4eac\u97f3\u697d\u5b66\u6821\u306e\u8b1b\u5e2b\u3067\u3042\u3063\u305f\u6bd4\u7559\u9593\u8ce2\u516b(1867-1936)\u304c\u30a4\u30bf\u30ea\u30a2\u4eba\u306e\u30a2\u30c3\u30c6\u30a3\u30ec\u30fb\u30b3\u30eb\u30ca\u30c6\u30a3\u306b\u30de\u30f3\u30c9\u30ea\u30f3\u3092\u5b66\u3093\u30671901\u5e74\u306b\u5e30\u56fd\u3001\u30de\u30f3\u30c9\u30ea\u30f3\u30fb\u30ae\u30bf\u30fc\u587e\u3092\u958b\u3044\u305f\u3053\u3068\u304c\u5951\u6a5f\u3068\u306a\u308a\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002[translation:...Kimihachi Hiruma (1867-1936) who was a lecturer at the Tokyo Music School learned mandolin at Italy's Attila Kornati, returned home in 1901, opened a mandolin / guitar cram school...]  }}</ref> He opened a school and founded a mandolin ensemble in 1905.<ref name=Hiruma/>\n\nWhere interest in the mandolin declined in the United States and parts of Europe after World War I, in Japan there was a boom, with orchestras being formed all over the country.<ref name=\"Sparks133-134\"/>\n\nConnections to the West, including cultural connections with World War II ally Italy, were forming. One musical connection that encouraged mandolin music growth was a visit by mandolin virtuoso [[Raffaele Calace]], who toured extensively at the end of 1924, into 1925, and who gave a performance for the Japanese emperor. Another visiting mandolin virtuoso, Samuel Adelstein, toured from his home in the United States.\n\nThe expansion of mandolin use continued after World War II through the late 1960s, and Japan still maintains a strong classical music tradition using mandolins, with active orchestras and university music programs. New orchestras were founded and new orchestral compositions composed. Japanese mandolin orchestras today may consist of up to 40 or 50 members, and can include woodwind, percussion, and brass sections. Japan also maintains an extensive collection of 20th-century mandolin music from Europe and one of the most complete collections of mandolin magazines from mandolin's golden age, purchased by Morishige Takei.\n\nIn [[Nagoya]] the [[Mandolin Melodies Museum]], founded by mandolin player Hirokazu Nanya, is dedicated to mandolins.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.t-museum.jp/|title=MATSUSHIMA\uff5cThe Museum Matsushima|website=T-museum.jp|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Influential people ====\n[[Morishige Takei]] (1890\u20131949), a member of the court of Emperor [[Hirohito]], established a mandolin orchestra in the Italian style before [[World War II]].<ref name=coldwell>{{cite web |url= http://www.digitalguitararchive.com/2012/02/morishige-takei/|title= Morishige Takei|last= Coldwell|first= Robert|date= 4 February 2012|website= digitalguitararchive.com |publisher= |access-date= 16 April 2018|quote=}}</ref> He was able to maintain his mandolin-guitar orchestra until 1943, in spite of the [[National Mobilization Law]] of 1938 that allowed the government to assert control of music, and ban western music and instruments, including the electric guitar, banjo and ukulele.<ref name=Japan1938>{{cite book |last= Yano|first= Christine Reiko |date= 2003|title= Tears of Longing: Nostalgia and the Nation in Japanese Popular Song|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=SnGY9XQj0ocC&lpg=PA37&dq=National%20%20Mobilization%20Law%20of%201938%2C%20mandolin&pg=PA38#v=onepage&q=National%20%20Mobilization%20Law%20of%201938,%20mandolin&f=false|location= |publisher= Harvard Univ Asia Center|pages= 37\u201338|isbn= 9780674012769|author-link= }}</ref><ref name=coldwell/> He was also a major composer, with 114 compositions for mandolin.\n\nAnother composer, [[Jiro Nakano]] (1902\u20132000), arranged many of the Italian works for regular orchestras or winds composed before World War II as new repertoires for Japanese mandolin orchestras.\n\nOriginal compositions for mandolin orchestras were composed increasingly after World War II. [[Seiichi Suzuki (composer)|Seiichi Suzuki]] (1901\u20131980) composed music for early [[Akira Kurosawa|Kurosawa]] films. Others include Tadashi Hattori (1908\u20132008), and [[Hiroshi Ohguri]] (1918\u20131982). Ohguri was influenced by [[B\u00e9la Bart\u00f3k]] and composed many symphonic works for Japanese mandolin orchestras. [[Yasuo Kuwahara]] (1946\u20132003) used German techniques. Many of his works were published in Germany.\n\n== Jewish Eastern Europe and diaspora ==\nIn Jewish communities in Eastern Europe and North America the mandolin was important in the years before World War II. The modern Ger Mandolin Orchestra website explained the importance, calling mandolins a \"quintessential Jewish musical form... Mandolin clubs and orchestras were at one time ubiquitous in Jewish Eastern Europe and in North American immigrant communities.\"<ref name=Ger>{{cite web |url=https://germandolin.com/about |title=The Ger Mandolin Orchestra Story |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=germandolin.com |publisher= |access-date= 22 May 2017|quote=}}</ref>  In the Holocaust Museum in Washington D.C, recorded memories recall the mandolin's place in Eastern Europe, in Poland, Latvia, Lithuania, Croatia and Macedonia. For some, the mandolin was progressive.<ref>{{cite interview |last=Salsitz |first= Norman|subject-link= |interviewer=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum ID Card Project |title=Oral history interview with Norman Salsitz |url=https://collections.ushmm.org/search/catalog/irn509201 |publisher=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |location= |date= 5 November 1992|access-date=28 May 2017|quote=From interview about life in [[Kolbuszowa]] in the 1930s to 1945: But the sisters went to school, the sisters used to all play mandolin, progressive. So the brothers nod their heads, progressive. They were progressive, Jewish, traditional. }}</ref> Individuals, once from Eastern Europe, speak of playing music in different languages, of family members who were able to make the instruments needed for an entire orchestra, of playing or having family members play in mandolin orchestras, of parents who used to teach music.\n\nThe instrument was inexpensive and fairly easy for beginners to learn and became a first instrument for children.<ref name=Warschauer>{{Cite AV media notes |title=Jeff Warschauer The Singing Waltz Klezmer Guitar and Mandolin |title-link= |others= |year=1997 |chapter= |url= |access-date= |first= |last= |author-link= |first2= |last2= |author-link2= |page=1 |pages= |type= |publisher=Omega |id= |location= |ref=}}</ref> In the United States, it was embraced by left-wing \"Socialists and Unionists\" as the \"Instrument of the people\" and was part of the curriculum in Yiddish schools.<ref name=Ger/><ref name=Dumneazu>{{cite web |url=http://horinca.blogspot.com/2010/12/chanukah-why-no-jewish-mandolin.html |title=Chanukah: Why no Jewish Mandolin Orchestras?  |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=horinca.blogspot.com |publisher= |access-date=22 May 2017 |quote=}}</ref> There were Jewish mandolin orchestras and the instrument was popular with apartment dwellers as a quiet instrument that wouldn't disturb the neighbors.<ref name=Dumneazu/> When Avner Yonai started researching the likely pieces that an Eastern European mandolin orchestra would have played, he found that little could be found about the repertoire his ancestor had played Poland; it was likely to have been light classical pieces, tango, and folk songs, possibly ethnic music from Jewish theater, Yiddish songs, [[Hasidic]] music and Klezmer.<ref name=Dumneazu/><ref name=GerTablet>{{cite web |url=http://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-arts-and-culture/music/48739/plucky-move |title=Plucky Move |last= Gelfrand|first=Alexander |date= |website=tabletmag.com |publisher= |access-date= 22 May 2017|quote=}}</ref>\n\nJewish mandolinists were prominent on the American mandolin. The earliest were performing during the Golden Era of the Mandolin, from the 1880s through the 1920s. They include [[Vaudeville]] musician [[Samuel Siegel]] of Des Moines (parents from Baden, Germany), Charles J. Levin of Baltimore, Samuel Adelstein of San Francisco, C.H. Pomeroy of Salt Lake City, and [[Valentine Abt]] of Pittsburgh.<ref name=Naxos>{{Cite AV media notes |title=Spaghetti Rag, Rag Music for Mandolins |title-link= |others= |year= |chapter= |url=https://www.naxos.com/mainsite/blurbs_reviews.asp?item_code=8.557999&catNum=557999&filetype=About%20this%20Recording&language=English |access-date=22 May 2017 |first= Ugo|last=Orlandi |author-link= |first2= Fiorenzo|last2= Gitti|author-link2= |page= |pages= |type= |publisher=Naxos |id= |location= |ref=}}</ref> \nAnother player who helped to keep the mandolin in the public eye after the Golden Era passed was [[Dave Apollon]] (1897-1972). Apollon grew up in [[Kiev]] and performed in [[Vaudeville]] for 20 years, played with Russian, Latin, Gypsy and Ragtime material.<ref name=ApollonCAfe>{{cite web |url= https://www.mandolincafe.com/archives/article.html|title=History of the Mandolin in America |last=Coolik |first=Daniel |date=18 November 1998 |website= mandolincafe.org|publisher= |access-date=22 May 2017 |quote=}}</ref> His long lifetime playing let people hear virtuoso performances of the mandolin, and he contributed to the instrument's revival.<ref name=ApollonCAfe/>\n\nModern players play a variety of music, as they explore their roots. Avner Yonai, descendant of people from Gora Kalwaria, Poland, put together an orchestra in Berkeley, California in honor of the original Ger Mandolin Orchestra.<ref name=Ger/><ref name=GerTablet/> Examples of the New Ger Mandolin Orchestra's reperatoire include ''Russian Rag'' (a mandolin orchestra piece) and the \n''Abe Schwartz Freylekh'' (Klezmer adapted for mandolins).<ref name=Dumneazu/> Klezmer and mandolins came together in the 1970s in a \"revival\" in New York City, where \"the overwhelmingly Jewish folk music scene would gather for Jam sessions \u2013 fiddles, banjos, and mandolins\", with Klezmer and Bluegrass musician [[Andy Statman]] being credited for the success of the revival. Statman mixed jazz with klezmer.<ref name=Dumneazu/>\n\nJeff Warschauer (a [[cantor]] since 2015) started the Klezmer Conservatory Band (1990-2003) and is part of The Strauss/Warschauer Duo (1995 to present) and has led Jewish mandolin orchestras ''Klez Camp'' and ''New York Arbeiter Ring''.<ref name=Dumneazu/><ref name=cantor>{{cite web |url=http://www.cantorjeff.com/ |title=Jeff Warschauer Cantor, Musician, and Educator |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=cantorjeff.com |publisher= |access-date=28 May 2017 |quote=}}</ref> He has become a modern link to the older Jewish tradition, interviewing older Jewish musicians to collect songs in Yiddish and klesmer music.<ref name=cantor/> Coming from a background in [[Bluegrass music|Bluegrass]], [[Swing music|Swing]], [[R&B]] and [[Folk music]], he adapted his skills to use the mandolin in Klezmer, which doesn't use mandolin as a traditional instrument<ref name=Warschauer/> In one example on his album ''The Singing Waltz'', Warschauer mixed mandolin with trombones for the song ''Dem Helfand's Tants'' (''The Elephant's Dance''), a combination that was also used for the ''Odessa Swing'' (composed by Steve Netsky).<ref name=Warschauer/> He mixed accordion, drums and piano with mandolin on the song ''Ot Azoy'' (''That's the Way!'').<ref name=Warschauer/>\n\nAnother bandleader is Eric Stein of Canada; his ''Beyond the Pale'' band plays Klezmer and Eastern European music.<ref name=Dumneazu/>\n\nAlthough information today is sparse, evidence of the musical culture remains, collected at The United States Holocaust Memorial Museum in Washington D.C., where there are pictures and recorded memories of Eastern European Jewish people, which recall the culture that existed in the first decades of the 20th century. Those that remained, emigrants to other countries took their music and memories with them, and gradually assimilated. Drawing on them for their memories has been part of the revival of the cultures that passed.\n\n== Latvia ==\nThe Holocaust Museum has online artifacts dealing with musician Elfa Heifecs, a Jewish musician from Riga, Latvia, who organized mandolin orchestra there, about 1930.<ref name=Elfa>{{cite web |url=http://collections.ushmm.org/search/catalog/pa1166407 |title=Elja Heifecs conducts a Jewish mandolin orchestra in Riga, Latvia.|last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website=ushmm.org |publisher=United States Holocaust Museum |access-date=25 October 2016 |quote=}}</ref><ref name=Elfa2>{{cite web |url= https://collections.ushmm.org/search/catalog/irn523433 |title= Text only poster for a musical performance in prewar Riga|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= |publisher= United States Holocaust Memorial Museum|access-date= 7 February 2018 |quote=Announcement for a concert featuring 25 year old Elja Heifecs and his Mandolin Orchestra in Riga, Latvia, on January 10, 1937.}}</ref><ref name=Elfa3>{{cite web |url= https://collections.ushmm.org/search/catalog/pa1166409 |title= Elja Heifecs gives mandolin lessons to two students.|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= |publisher= United States Holocaust Memorial Museum|access-date= 7 February 2018 |quote=[caption]: Elja Heifecs gives mandolin lessons to two students.}}</ref>\n\n== Macedonia ==\nMacedonia has a mandolin tradition that dates back before World War II; The [[United States Holocaust Museum]] has a 1929 photo of a Jewish mandolin orchestra on display online.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://collections.ushmm.org/search/catalog/pa1119054 |title=A group of Macedonian Jewish youth who are members of a mandolin band, pose outside a building in Bitola, Macedonia |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website=ushmm.org |publisher=United States Holocaust Museum |access-date=11 October 2016 |quote=Caption: A group of Macedonian Jewish youth who are members of a mandolin band, pose outside a building in Bitola, Macedonia. Date: 1930 March 02 Locale: Bitola, [Macedonia; Bitolj] Yugoslavia }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/culturalinstitute/beta/asset/dihovo-macedonia-yugoslavia-a-group-of-mandolin-players-on-a-hike-22-12-1929/TAE0bZjY_znP6g?hl=en |title=Dihovo, Macedonia, Yugoslavia, A group of mandolin players on a hike, 22/12/1929 |last1=Vashem |first1=Yad |last2= |first2= |date= |website=google.com |publisher=Google Arts and Culture |access-date=11 October 2016 |quote= Title: Dihovo, Macedonia, Yugoslavia, A group of mandolin players on a hike, 22/12/1929. Location: Bitola, Yugoslavia Subject Keywords: Music, Prewar period, Orchestras Origin: Gabriel Albocher Name of submitter: Nina Shpringer Aharoni Credit: Yad Vashem Collection: Yad Vashem Photo Archive Archival signature: 6214/38  }}</ref> In modern times, the Skopje Mandolin orchestra was formed in 2001 and has performed in international competitions.<ref name=skopje>{{cite web|url=http://visitskopje.mk/index.php/concerts/179-concert-of-the-mandolin-orchestra |title=Concert of the Mandolin Orchestra |website=visitskopje.mk |access-date=11 October 2016 |quote=Formed in 2001, the Mandolin Orchestra \"Skopje\" has won multiple...  Under Ramadan Shukri's conducting, the orchestra will performs its traditional annual pre- new year's concert... Soloists as Suzana Turundzieva, Mustafa Imeri, Serafina Fantauzo, Gligor Popovski and Lazar Sandev... |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416051026/http://visitskopje.mk/index.php/concerts/179-concert-of-the-mandolin-orchestra |archivedate=16 April 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ladna.com.mk/en/news/mandolin-orchestra |title=News, Mandolin Orchestra from Skopje |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website=ladna.com |publisher= |access-date=11 October 2016 |quote=Ladna sponsored the Mandolin Orchestra in Skopje, supporting its members on the 10-th International Festival in Vienne France, where the orchestra had won two gold medals...}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mandolin-orchestra.org/orchestra.htm |title=Skopje Mandolin Orchestra of the Youth Cultural Center (Macedonia)  |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website=mandolin-orchestra.org/orchestra.htm |publisher= |access-date=11 October 2016 |quote=The Mandolin Orchestra in Skopje, Macedonia, is one of the top touring mandolin orchestras in Europe....young musicians, aged 14 to 22}}</ref> Mandolinists associated with the Skopje Mandolin Orchestra include Ramadan Shukri, Suzana Turundzieva, Mustafa Imeri, Serafina Fantauzo, Gligor Popovski and Lazar Sandev.<ref name=skopje/>\n\n==Mexico==\nColonized by Spain, Mexico had both Spanish instruments as well as instruments created locally. These include the [[bandurria]] and the [[bandol\u00f3n]].\n\nWhen [[Carlo Curti]] finished with playing mandolin with his \"Spanish Students\" in the United States, he organized a new act in Mexico in 1883-1884, the Mexican Typical Orchestra, which performed at the World's Industrial and\nCotton Exposition (1885) in New Orleans and then toured the United States.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Castillo |first=Manuel M.  |last2= |first2= |date=2014 |title=Italian and Spanish Influence on Selected Works of Mexican Composers: Mar\u00eda Grever, Ignacio Fern\u00e1ndez Esper\u00f3n \"Tata Nacho,\" and August\u00edn Lara |url=http://uknowledge.uky.edu/music_etds/32/ |journal=The UNiversity of Kentucky UKnowledge, Thesis and Dissertations, Music |publisher=The University of Kentucky |volume= |issue= |pages= 20|doi= |access-date=September 8, 2015|quote=[Full article: https://uknowledge.uky.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1034&context=music_etds]}}</ref> The band included as many as seven [[bandol\u00f3n]]s. Bandol\u00f3ns were developed in Mexico, guitar sized instruments with 18 strings (in 6 courses of 3) related to the [[bandurria]].<ref>\n{{cite web |url=http://lexicoon.org/es/bandolon |title= DEFINICI\u00d3N DE BANDOL\u00d3N, qu\u00e9 significa bandol\u00f3n |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=lexicoon.org |publisher= |access-date=September 16, 2015 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Alfab\u00e9tico tem\u00e1tica Invicta |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=01uOcTvyNuIC&lpg=PA863&ots=Ca6mDUyFA3&dq=El%20bandol%C3%B3n&pg=PA863#v=onepage&q&f=false |location= |publisher= |page=863 |date= |isbn=}}</ref> When described in U.S. newspapers, it was noted that they looked like large mandolins.<ref name=mandibandi>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Mexican Typical Orchestra|url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31557309/mexican_typical_orchestra_bandolons/ |work= New York Times |location=New York City |date=20 June 1885 |access-date=14 May 2019 |page= 4 |quote=\u2026 seven bandolons, the later being neither more nor less than magnified mandolins. |via=Newspaper.com}}</ref> It was also noted that Carlo Curti was a well-known mandolin player, and some newspapers never found out what the bandol\u00f3ns were, calling them mandolins.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Curti a well-known mandolin player |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31557579/curti_a_wellknown_mandolin_player/|work= The Courier-Journal|location= Louisville, Kentucky|date= 5 April 1885|page= 11|access-date=14 May 2019|quote=The Mexican Typical Orchestra will perform...under the leadership of Sig. Curti, the well-known Spanish mandolin player. |via=Newspaper.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Mandolin confused for bandol\u00f2n in Mexican Typical Orchestra write-up |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/31557793/mandolin_confused_for_bandoln_in/ | work=Austin-American Statesman | location=Austin, Texas |date=15 April 1890 |page= 3 |access-date= 14 May 2019|quote= The Mexican Typical Orchestra, composed of bandurrias, mandolins, violins, violincellos, guitars, etc., \u2026  |via=Newspaper.com}}</ref>\n\nThe confusion may have added further to the impression in the United States that the mandolin and bandurria families were related. Musician [[Robert Braine]] wrote in the Etude in August 1918 that \"the craze for the mandolin in the United States was a direct result of the concert tours, covering several years, of two of such orchestras, the 'Spanish Students' and the 'Mexican Typical Orchestra' from Mexico City.\"<ref name=braine>{{cite magazine |last=Braine |first= Robert|date=August 1918 |title= Possibilities of the mandolin for the violin teachers |url= https://books.google.fr/books?id=hoOvYiTOVwkC&pg=PA544#v=onepage&q&f=false |magazine=The Etude |location= |publisher= |access-date=14 May 2019 }}</ref> Braine was aware of the nature of the Neapolitan mandolin, but lumped mandolins and bandurrias together in his article, saying that the mandolin was \"played, studied and taught\" in Spain, Mexico and the South American countries<ref name=braine/>.\n\n== New Zealand ==\nThe Auckland Mandolinata mandolin orchestra was formed in 1969 by Doris Flameling (1932\u20132004). Soon after arriving from the Netherlands with her family, Doris started teaching guitar and mandolin in West Auckland. In 1969, she formed a small ensemble for her pupils. This ensemble eventually developed into a full size mandolin orchestra, which survives today. Doris was the musical director and conductor of this orchestra for many years. The orchestra is currently led by Bryan Holden (conductor).\n\nThe early history of the mandolin in New Zealand is currently being researched by members of the Auckland Mandolinata.\n\n== Poland ==\nThe mandolin was used as a folk instrument throughout eastern part of European continent, including Poland, Ukraine and Slovakia in the early part of the 20th century.<ref name=tabletmagazine>{{cite web |url=http://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-arts-and-culture/music/48739/plucky-move |title=Plucky Move |last1=Gelfand |first1=Alexander |last2= |first2= |date=28 October 2010 |website=tabletmag.com |publisher=Tablet Magazine |access-date=25 October 2016 |quote=}}</ref> Mandolin orchestras were present as well.<ref name=tabletmagazine/> One example was the Mandolin Orchestra of Ger ([[Gora Kalwaria]], Poland).<ref name=tabletmagazine/> A photo exists of the orchestra, made up of Jewish residents who were in the orchestra in the 1930s before the Jewish population was sent to the [[Treblinka extermination camp]].<ref name=tabletmagazine/> A similar photo exists of a mandolin orchestra in the community of [[Grodno]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.grodnoonline.org/lost_worlds/section_2d_test.html |title=Lost Jewish Worlds, BETWEEN THE WORLD WARS - 4 |last1= Zandman|first1=F.|last2= |first2= |date= |website=grodnoonline.org |publisher=Tablet Grodno Online|access-date=25 October 2016 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n== Portugal ==\nThe ''bandolim'' (Portuguese for \"mandolin\") was a favourite instrument within the Portuguese bourgeoisie of the 19th century, but its rapid spread took it to other places, joining other instruments. Today you can see mandolins as part of the traditional and folk culture of Portuguese singing groups and the majority of the mandolin scene in Portugal is in Madeira Island. Madeira has over 17 active mandolin Orchestras and [[Tuna (music)|Tunas]]. The mandolin virtuoso [[Fabio Machado]] is one of Portugal's most accomplished mandolin players. The Portuguese influence brought the mandolin to Brazil and Sri Lanka.\n\n== Romania ==\n:[[:Category:Romanian mandolinists|See Romanian mandolinists]]\n\n== Russia ==\n[[:Category:Russian mandolinists|See Russian mandolinists]]\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n | align = right\n\n| image3 = Comerre-Pierrot jouant de la mandoline-Mus\u00e9e de Gap.jpg\n | width3 = 106\n | alt3 = Pierrot with mandolin\n | caption3 =The 1976 ''Adventures of Buratino'' character, Pierrot, played a mandolin. Similarly, the French painter [[L\u00e9on Comerre]] painted this image of a mandolin-playing Pierrot in 1884.\n\n | image2 = Gibson mandolin Glinka's museum Moscow Russia.jpg\n | width2 = 154\n | alt2 = Gibson mandolin modified with Russian electric pickup\n | caption2 = American-made Gibson mandolin, modified to electric with Russian-made pickups, at the Glinka National Museum Consortium of Musical Culture, Moscow, Russia.\n\n | image1 = Ernest K\u00f6hler, A new and practical school for Mandolin.jpg\n | width1 = 156\n | alt1 = book, Ernest K\u00f6hler, A new and practical school for Mandolin\n | caption1 = Cover of ''A New and Practical School for Mandolin'' (''\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0432\u0435\u0441\u044c\u043c\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u043d\u044f\u0442\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0448\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u043c\u0430\u043d\u0434\u043e\u043b\u0438\u043d\u044b'') by [[Ernesto K\u00f6hler]], with dual German-Russian entries. Version market to Germans was published c. 1887.<ref name=Schule>{{cite web |url= http://www.mandoisland.de/noten2011/ernest_koehler/ernesto_koehler.html#.WVfj0p9MEwg |title= Ernesto K\u00f6hler -Mandolin school for self teaching|last= Reichenbach|first= Michael|date= |website= mandoisland.de|publisher= |access-date= 1 July 2017|quote=}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe mandolin was popular in Russia in the pre-Soviet era and after as a folk instrument. Catalogs from the early 1900s offered a variety of bowlback mandolins, imports made by Italian companies. Locally made mandolins existed as well.\n\nThe first mandolin orchestra in Russia was put together in the early 1880s by an Italian immigrant, [[Ginislao Paris]], called ''The Society of Amateur Mandolinists and Guitarists''.<ref name=Speranski>{{cite web |url=https://archive.org/details/TheRussianEmbergher_201501 |title=The Russian Embergher |last=Speranski |first=Victor |date=November 2014 |website= |publisher= |access-date= 29 May 2017|quote=}}</ref> Paris designed double-top mandolins, which he had [[Luigi Embergher]] build.<ref name=Speranski/>  At least one member of the royal family of Russia played mandolin during this period, Tsarina Maria Fyodorovna who owned a Number 8 Embergher, a high-end instrument that would have been highly decorated.<ref name=Speranski/>\n\nThere were talented mandolinists, in various parts the country. [[Dave Apollon]], who became a well known (U.S.-based) player, was born in [[Kiev]], then part of Russia. After emigration from Russia, he was able to land a job in Vaudeville, exhibiting virtuosity.\n\nAfter the rise of the Soviet Union, bowlback mandolins were not imported in the numbers they had been. Although possibly that had much to with the turmoil starting in 1917, of the country being reorganized into a communist state, the timing also coincides with the drop in popularity worldwide, as the mandolin's ''Golden Era'' peaked. The instrument had competition as a folk instrument as well, from the [[domra]] and [[balalaika]]. [[Vasily Andreyev]] who founded the first balalaika orchestra in Russia and resurrected the domra was inspired by a performance of Russia's first mandolin orchestra.<ref name=vasily>{{cite web |url=https://archive.org/details/TheRussianEmbergher_201501 |title=The Russian Embergher |last=Speranski |first=Victor |date=November 2014 |website= |publisher= |access-date= 29 May 2017|quote= It was Ginislao's mandolin orchestra that inspired Andreev to turn from his solo balalaika performances to the creation of a full Russian folk instruments orchestra that brought him worldwide fame. }}</ref> The bowlback didn't just disappear, as they are common in photos of mandolin orchestras in Eastern Europe in the 1930s. However, the mandolins produced in Soviet factories were of the cheap, flatback, \"Portuguese\" style\u2014widespread throughout the Soviet Union.\n\nIn the 1970s and 80s, bluegrass music spread into Russia [[Czech bluegrass|from Czechoslovakia]], and through American performers touring in Russia, including [[Roy Clark]] and the [[Nitty Gritty Dirt Band]].<ref name=kukuruzachictrib>{{cite news |last=Duckman |first=David |date=20 February 1994 |title=No Second Fiddle, Bluegrass In Russia? Kukuruza Plucks and Picks With Aplomb |url= http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-02-20/features/9402200340_1_bluegrass-music-kukuruza-fax |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |location= Chicago, Illinois|access-date=7 February 2018 }}</ref> Russian bands were started with bluegrass elements that included a mandolin, including [[Kukuruza]] (with mandolinist Georgi Palmov) and Bering Strait (mandolinist Sergei Passov).<ref name=kukuruzachictrib/><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.allmusic.com/artist/bering-strait-mn0000057941/biography |title=Artist Biography |last=Ruhlmann |first=William |date= |website=allmusic.com |publisher= |access-date= 7 February 2018 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nThe mandolin was used in movies, including the 1976 film ''[[The Adventures of Buratino (1976 film)|The Adventures of Buratino]]'' (\u041f\u0440\u0438\u043a\u043b\u044e\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0411\u0443\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043d\u043e) to accompany songs by Tortila and [[Pierrot|Pierro]] (\u0422\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0438\u043b\u044b \u0438 \u041f\u044c\u0435\u0440\u043e).<ref>{{cite web |url= http://pazovsky.ru/mandoline/ |title= Mandolin |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= pazovsky.ru |publisher= |access-date= 4 April 2019 |quote= \u041c\u0430\u043d\u0434\u043e\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0431\u044b\u043b\u0430 \u043e\u0447\u0435\u043d\u044c \u043f\u043e\u043f\u0443\u043b\u044f\u0440\u043d\u0430 \u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u0432 \u0434\u043e\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u044f \u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435. \u041c\u043d\u043e\u0436\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0444\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c\u043e\u0432 \u0431\u044b\u043b\u043e \u043e\u0437\u0432\u0443\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043e \u0442\u0435\u043c\u0430\u043c\u0438 \u043c\u0430\u043d\u0434\u043e\u043b\u0438\u043d\u044b. \u041e\u0434\u043d\u0438\u043c\u0438 \u0438\u0437 \u0441\u0430\u043c\u044b\u0445 \u0437\u0430\u043f\u043e\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0430\u044e\u0449\u0438\u0445\u0441\u044f \u044f\u0432\u043b\u044f\u044e\u0442\u0441\u044f: \u0441\u043e\u043b\u043e \u0432 \u043f\u0435\u0441\u043d\u044f\u0445 \u043f\u0430\u043f\u044b \u041a\u0430\u0440\u043b\u043e, \u0447\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0430\u0445\u0438 \u0422\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0438\u043b\u044b \u0438 \u041f\u044c\u0435\u0440\u043e, \u0432 \u0444\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c\u0435 \u00ab\u041f\u0440\u0438\u043a\u043b\u044e\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0411\u0443\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043d\u043e\u00bb. [translation: Mandolin was very popular in Russia in the pre-Soviet times and after. A lot of films were voiced by mandolin themes. One of the most memorable are: solo in the songs of Pope Carlo, tortoises Tortila and Piero, in the film \u201cThe Adventures of Buratino\u201d}}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UexFpXloTwM|title= \u0420\u043e\u043c\u0430\u043d\u0441 \u0447\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0430\u0445\u0438 \u0422\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0438\u043b\u044b (\"\u041f\u0440\u0438\u043a\u043b\u044e\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0411\u0443\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043d\u043e\") |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= |publisher= |access-date= 4 April 2019|quote=[Clip from Adventures of Buratino featuring Tortila]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tzj6NbGXjGc|title= \u0420\u043e\u043c\u0430\u043d\u0441 \u0447\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0430\u0445\u0438 \u0422\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0438\u043b\u044b (\"\u041f\u0440\u0438\u043a\u043b\u044e\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0411\u0443\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043d\u043e\") |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= |publisher= |access-date= 4 April 2019|quote=[Clip from Adventures of Buratino featuring Pierro]}}</ref>\n\n== South Africa ==\nThe mandolin has been a prominent instrument in the recordings of [[Johnny Clegg]] and his bands [[Juluka]] and [[Savuka]]. Since 1992, Andy Innes has been the mandolinist for Johnny Clegg and Savuka.\n\n==Spain==\n[[File:John Phillip, A Lady Playing the Mandolin.jpg|right|thumb|Painting by [[John Phillip]] in 1854, showing a Spanish woman with mandolin.]]\nAccording to historian Paul Sparks, Spain is \"one of the few Western countries where the Neapolitan mandolin has never been widely played.\"<ref name=\"Sparks24-29\">{{harvnb|Sparks|2003|pages=10, 11, 24\u201329}}</ref> As the mandolin was used in Italy to serenade young ladies and make music in the streets, the equally high pitched and plucked [[bandurria]] was used by Spanish youth to accompany their songs in the street and serenade.<ref name=\"Sparks24-29\"/> The instruments were used alongside guitars for traditional dances.<ref name=\"Sparks24-29\"/> The tradition of dancing to fast music was one of the draws of the Spanish Students when they went to Paris with their bandurrias, guitars and fiddles.<ref name=\"Sparks24-29\"/>\n\nBoth the Spanish bandurria and Italian mandolins ultimately were developments of the [[gittern]] and the [[mandore (instrument)|mandore]]. In the 1880s, the mandolin and bandurria, with their small sizes and double rows of metal strings, were similar enough to be confused by ignorant audiences.<ref name=\"Sparks24-29\"/> This happened in America and, along with deception from opportunistic Italian musicians, led to the mandolin's expansion.<ref name=\"Sparks24-29\"/> Both instruments spread around the world from their original homes in Europe, the bandurria mainly in Spanish speaking areas such as South America and the Philippines.\n\nIn Spain today, the bandurria is a \"national instrument.\"<ref name=Hector>{{cite web |url= http://www.themandolintuner.com/mandolin-news-an-interview-with-hector-marin/ |title=An Interview with Hector Marin |last= Rizos |first= Christos |date= |website= themandolintuner.com|publisher= |access-date= 28 April 2019|quote=}}</ref> However, the mandolin can be learned there as well, especially by those pursuing a career as a classical musician.<ref name=Hector/> Although professional Spanish mandolinists may be rare, but they do exist: Hector Marin developed his skill with the mandolin sufficiently to complete in the Yasuo Kuwahara International Mandolin Competition in Germany in 2015.<ref name=Kuwaharacomp>{{cite web |url= https://m.eldiario.es/cultura/Hector-Marin-Concurso-Kuwahara-Alemania_0_385661844.amp.html |title=El placentino H\u00e9ctor Mar\u00edn, \u00fanico espa\u00f1ol en el Concurso Yasuo Kuwahara en Alemania [translation: Hector Mar\u00edn, the only Spaniard in the Yasuo Kuwahara Contest in Germany] |last= |first= |date= 8 May 2015|website= eldiario.es|publisher= |access-date= 28 April 2019|quote=}}</ref> The competition that year had 11 other \"virtuosos of the mandolin\" competing, six from Germany and five from Russia.<ref name=Kuwaharacomp/> Marin, spoke in an interview, of learning first the bandurria and then later the mandolin, concentrating on the latter for having a broader range of classical material to play.<ref name=Hector/> He benefited from European culture, having teachers in both Spain and elsewhere in Europe as he pursued music.<ref name=Hector/> Marin attended several schools, including in Austria.  He cited Juan Carlos Mu\u00f1oz (Spanish, teaching in Austria), Mari Fe Pav\u00f3n, Caterina Lichtenberg (German) and Avi Avital (Israeli)  as his mandolin-playing musical influences.<ref name=Hector/>\n\n== Sri Lanka ==\nThe mandolin was brought to Sri Lanka by the Portuguese, who colonized Sri Lanka from 1505 to 1658. The instrument has been heavily used in [[baila]], a genre of Sri Lankan music formed from a mixture of Portuguese, African and Sinhala music. For example, the mandolin features prominently in [[M.S. Fernando]]'s baila song, ''Bola Bola Meti''.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xRiglareR9c|title= Bola Bola Mati \u0db6\u0ddd\u0dbd \u0db6\u0ddd\u0dbd \u0db8\u0dd0\u0da7\u0dd2 M.S.Fernando |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= youtube.com|publisher= |access-date= 7 April 2019|quote=[YouTube. The song opens with a mandolin [[riff]]. The lyrics are about a [[mud dauber]] gathering mud from the riverbank and building a house.]}}</ref> Victor Rathnayaka's ''Thaniwennata Mage Lowe'', [[Sunil Perera]] & [[The Gypsies (Sri Lankan band)|Gypsies]] ''Saima Cut wela'' and Sujatha Athanayaka's ''Hathara watin Kalukaragena'' are among other examples of songs with mandolin.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hfMdQffJhRg|title= Saima Cut Wela - Sunil Perera (Gypsies) |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= youtube.com|publisher= |access-date= 7 April 2019|quote=[YouTube. The first minute of the song and its [[riff]]s throughout the songs are played on the mandolin.]}}</ref>  Modern day musicians include Antony Surendra, V. Hemapala Perera, Ananda Perera, [[Dinesh Subasinghe]], Susantha Kariyakarawana, Sarath Fernando, Nalaka Sajee, Haasriza Imran and Buddhika Perera\n\n== Tobago and Trinidad ==\nThe mandolin has a history on [[Tobago]] and [[Trinidad]] as the [[Bandolin (Trinidad)|bandolin]], dating back before World War I.<ref name=\"Winer2009\">{{cite book|author=Lise Winer|title=Dictionary of the English/Creole of Trinidad & Tobago: On Historical Principles|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_n82hsbDJBMC&pg=PA50|accessdate=5 May 2013|date=16 January 2009|publisher=McGill-Queen's Press - MQUP|isbn=978-0-7735-7607-0|pages=50\u2013}}</ref>  It was a small instrument, approximately 20 x 40 centimeters, strung with 8 strings in four courses of two each.<ref name=\"Winer2009\"/> Before the war, it was commonly a round-backed instrument, made of strips of wood.<ref name=\"Winer2009\"/> The flat-backed version appeared after the war. Occasionally a turtle shell would be used for the back of the instrument.<ref name=\"Winer2009\"/> It is used in Trinidad's ''[[parang]]'' music, accompanied by \"[[Cuatro (instrument)|cuatro]] and [[maracas]]\".<ref name=\"Winer2009\"/> There is another member of the mandolin family, the Trinidadian version of the [[Bandol (instrument)|bandol]], different from the mainland [[bandola]]. It is the tenor of the mandolin family on the island, also strung with 8 strings in 4 courses; however, the lower two string courses are strung differently, each having a metal and a nylon string.<ref name=\"Winer2009\"/>\n\n== Turkey ==\nTurkey has been the home of a mandolin-banjo manufacturer, [[C\u00fcmb\u00fcs]], since the early 20th century. The country had what may be its first Mandolin festival in June 2015, and has at least one Mandolin Orchestra.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mandolincafe.com/forum/showthread.php?106924-The-very-first-Mandolin-Festival-in-Turkey-June-2015 |title=Thread: The very first Mandolin Festival in Turkey June 2015 |last1= Hi\u00e7y\u0131lmaz |first1= Orkun|last2= |first2= |date=April 2012 |website= mandolincafe.com|publisher= Mandolin Cafe|access-date=October 18, 2015 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mandolincafe.com/forum/showthread.php?106924-The-very-first-Mandolin-Festival-in-Turkey-June-2015 |title=Thread: a melody from a turkish mandolin teaching book |last1= Hi\u00e7y\u0131lmaz |first1= Orkun|last2= |first2= |date=April 2012 |website= mandolincafe.com|publisher= Mandolin Cafe|access-date=October 18, 2015 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nOne professional musician to use the mandolin is Sumru A\u011f\u0131ry\u00fcr\u00fcyen who is known for singing and playing many styles of music including [[world music]], [[Klezmer]], Turkish folk, Balkan folk, blues, jazz, [[krautrock]], protest rock and [[Makam|maqam]].<ref name=list>{{cite web |url=http://istanbulmusic.blogspot.com/2011/03/best-turkish-female-musicians.html |title=50 Greatest Turkish Women in Music, Western Classical Music |last1=Alhan |first1=M.S. |last2= |first2= |date=2011|website=istanbulmusic.blogspot.com |publisher= |access-date=October 17, 2015 |quote=}}</ref><ref name=bug>{{cite web |url=http://www.bugunbugece.com/git-gor/rastlasmalar-ii-tolga-tuzun-sumru-agiryuruyen |title=Rastla\u015fmalar II: Tolga T\u00fcz\u00fcn - Sumru A\u011f\u0131ry\u00fcr\u00fcyen |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=January 10, 2013 |website=bugunbugece.com |access-date=October 17, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117033006/http://www.bugunbugece.com/git-gor/rastlasmalar-ii-tolga-tuzun-sumru-agiryuruyen |archivedate=November 17, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n== Ukraine ==\nThe Mandolin has been played in Ukraine, and pictures of it being played today can be found online.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.alamy.com/stock-photo-ukraine-yalta-livadia-palace-ukrainian-folkloric-show-women-in-traditional-49017321.html|title= Ukraine, Yalta, Livadia Palace. Ukrainian folkloric show. Women in traditional costumes playing Russian balalaikas & lutes|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= |publisher= Alamy|access-date= 26 October 2016|quote=Danita Delimont / Alamy Stock Photo}}</ref> One famous former resident of [[Kiev]] was [[Dave Apollon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blatata.com/biografii/bio01/9824-djejjv-apollon-dave-apollon.html|title=\u0414\u044d\u0439\u0432 \u0410\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043b\u043e\u043d (Dave Apollon)|author=|date=|website=blatata.com|accessdate=16 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816170712/http://www.blatata.com/biografii/bio01/9824-djejjv-apollon-dave-apollon.html|archive-date=16 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Other photos dating back to the early 20th century show Ukrainian Mandolin orchestras in Canada and the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.manitobamusicmuseum.com/mandolinorchofwpg.htm |title= Mandolin Orchestra, 1926 Ukrainian Labour Temple|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |publisher= Manitoba Music Museum |access-date=26 October 2016 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.ebay.com/itm/252186064378?_mwBanner=1 |title=UKRAINIAN MANDOLIN ORCHESTRA SCRANTON PA LAWRENCE UHRYN ANTIQUE VINTAGE PHOTO |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= eBay.com|publisher= |accessdate=2016-10-26|quote=from photo back side: Ukrainian Mandolin Orchestras, Organized 1932, Scranton, Pennsylvania, Professor Lawrence Uhryn, Instructor and Director}}</ref>\nOne of the offshoots of Ukrainian immigrants to North America is the Toronto Mandolin Orchestra (possibly the oldest mandolin orchestra in North America), which claims Ukrainians as among its founders. The orchestra's web site said of mandolins in Ukraine, that the instruments were popular in the early 20th century, but never reached folk-instrument status there. Ukrainian immigrants of the period took the instruments with them to their new countries.\n\nThe instrument has had to compete in Ukraine with native instruments that have been revived, such as the [[kobza]]. The orchestral variant of the kobza is similar to the Mandolin, having four strings and being tuned in fifths.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://home.att.net/~bandura.ca/VMfolkBook/banduras.html |title=PLUCKED STRING INSTRUMENTS, The Kobza |last1=Mishalow |first1=Victor |date=1999 |website=Folk Instruments of Ukraine |access-date=26 October 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20001008111837/http://home.att.net/~bandura.ca/VMfolkBook/banduras.html |archivedate=8 October 2000 }}</ref>\n\n== United Kingdom ==\n:[[:Category:British mandolinists|See British mandolinists]]\n\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n | direction = vertical | width=165\n | align = right\n | image1 = Mandolin guitar band crystal palace.jpg\n | alt1 = Polytechnic and People's Palace Mandoline and Guitar Band\n | caption1 = The ''Polytechnic and People's Palace Mandoline and Guitar Band'' in 1899 at the [[The Crystal Palace|Crystal Palace]].\n | image2 = SimonMayorMSI.jpg\n | alt2 = Simon Mayor\n | caption2 = [[Simon Mayor]] has worked at creating  a uniquely [[United Kingdom|British]] voice for the mandolin.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Joyner |first=Hermon |title=Simon Mayor - Approaching the Mandolin with Wit and Wisdom |magazine=Mandolin Magazine |date=Fall 2009 |volume=11 |issue=2 |pages=3\u20135 |url=http://www.mandolinmagazine.com |accessdate=20 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091215030434/http://www.mandolinmagazine.com/cgi/backissues/searchdb.cgi?searchterm=v11n2 |archivedate=15 December 2009}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20101102224621/http://mandolinmagazine.com/images/fall2009.jpg Cover]</ref>\n}}\nThe mandolin has been used extensively in the traditional music of [[England]] and [[Scotland]] for generations. [[Simon Mayor]] is a prominent British player who has produced six solo albums, instructional books and DVDs, as well as recordings with his mandolin quartet the Mandolinquents.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n[[File:John Paul Jones.jpg|thumb|left|[[John Paul Jones (musician)|John Paul Jones]] playing mandolin with ''[[The Duhks]]'' on Zeppelin's \"[[Whole Lotta Love]]\" at [[MerleFest]], 2007.<ref>{{cite web |title=MERLEFEST {{!}} 04.26 \u2013 04.29 {{!}} NORTH CAROLINA |date=May 23, 2007 |author=Anson Burtch |url=https://www.jambase.com/article/merlefest-04-26-04-29-north-carolina |website=JamBase |access-date=2019-05-18}}</ref>]]\nThe instrument has also found its way into British rock music. The mandolin was played by [[Mike Oldfield]] (and introduced by [[Vivian Stanshall]]) on Oldfield's album ''[[Tubular Bells]]'', as well as on a number of his subsequent albums (particularly prominently on ''[[Hergest Ridge]]'' (1974) and ''[[Ommadawn]]'' (1975)). It was used extensively by the British folk-rock band [[Lindisfarne (band)|Lindisfarne]], who featured two members on the instrument, [[Ray Jackson (musician)|Ray Jackson]] and Simon Cowe, and whose \"[[Fog on the Tyne]]\" was the biggest selling UK album of 1971\u201372. The instrument was also used extensively in the UK folk revival of the 1960s and 1970s with bands such as [[Fairport Convention]] and [[Steeleye Span]] taking it on as the lead instrument in many of their songs. \"[[Maggie May]]\" by [[Rod Stewart]], which hit No. 1 on both the British charts and the Billboard Hot 100, also featured Jackson's playing. It has also been used by other British rock musicians. [[Led Zeppelin]]'s bassist [[John Paul Jones (musician)|John Paul Jones]] is an accomplished mandolin player and has recorded numerous songs on mandolin including \"[[Going to California]]\" and \"[[That's the Way (Led Zeppelin song)|That's the Way]]\"; the mandolin part on \"[[The Battle of Evermore]]\" is played by [[Jimmy Page]], who composed the song. Other Led Zeppelin songs featuring mandolin are \"[[Hey Hey What Can I Do]]\", and \"[[Black Country Woman]]\". [[Pete Townshend]] of [[the Who]] played mandolin on the track \"[[Mike Post Theme]]\", along with many other tracks on ''[[Endless Wire (The Who album)|Endless Wire]]''. [[McGuinness Flint]], for whom [[Graham Lyle]] played the mandolin on their most successful single, ''[[When I'm Dead And Gone]]'', is another example. Lyle was also briefly a member of [[Ronnie Lane's Slim Chance]], and played mandolin on their hit \"[[How Come]]\". One of the more prominent early mandolin players in popular music was [[Robin Williamson]] in [[the Incredible String Band]]. [[Ian Anderson (musician)|Ian Anderson]] of Jethro Tull is a highly accomplished mandolin player, as is his guitarist [[Martin Barre]]. The popular song \"[[Please Please Please Let Me Get What I Want]]\" by [[the Smiths]] featured a mandolin solo played by [[Johnny Marr]]. More recently, the Glasgow-based band [[Sons and Daughters (band)|Sons and Daughters]] featured the mandolin, played by Ailidh Lennon, on tracks such as \"Fight\", \"Start to End\", and \"Medicine\". British [[folk punk|folk-punk]] icons [[the Levellers (band)|the Levellers]] also regularly use the mandolin in their songs. British comedian [[Ade Edmondson]] took the role of lead mandolin in his folk punk band, [[Bad Shepherds]]. Current bands are also beginning to use the mandolin and its unique sound, such as South London's [[Indigo Moss]] who use it throughout their recordings and live gigs. The mandolin has also featured in the playing of [[Matthew Bellamy]] in the rock band [[Muse (band)|Muse]]. It also forms the basis of [[Paul McCartney]]'s 2007 hit \"[[Dance Tonight]]\". That was not the first time a [[Beatle]] played a mandolin, however; that distinction goes to [[George Harrison]] on \"[[Gone Troppo]]\", the title cut from the 1982 album of the same name.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}} Also more recently [[hard rock]] supergroup [[Them Crooked Vultures]] have been playing a song, ''Highway One'' in which Jones \"morphs an effected mandolin bluegrass run into a slick rock riff\".<ref name=vulturesjones>{{cite web |url= https://www.jambase.com/article/them-crooked-vultures-02-08-nyc|title= Them Crooked Vultures, 02.08, NYC|last=  Dembinsky|first= Ryan|date= 11 February 2010|website= |publisher=jambase.com |access-date=17 April 2018 |quote=}}</ref> This song was left off their debut album ''[[Them Crooked Vultures (album)|Them Crooked Vultures]]'', and features former [[Led Zeppelin]] [[bassist]] [[John Paul Jones (musician)|John Paul Jones]].<ref name=vulturesjones/>\n\nIn the Classical style, performers such as Hugo D'Alton, [[Alison Stephens]] and Michael Hooper have continued to play music by British composers such as [[Michael Finnissy]], James Humberstone and Elspeth Brooke.\n\nThe mandolin is taught in Lanarkshire by the Lanarkshire Guitar and Mandolin Association to over 100 people.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n== United States ==\nSee: [[Mandolins in North America]] and [[Bluegrass mandolin]]\n:[[:Category:American mandolinists|See American mandolinists]] and [[:Category:American bluegrass mandolinists|American bluegrass mandolinists]]\n\nThe [[mandolin]] has had a place in North American culture since the 1880s, when a \"mandolin craze\" began.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Mandolin-Mad Belles, The new musical craze among fashionable News York girls|url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3181695/mandolin_madness_in_girls/ |work= The Times|location= Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|date= 27 Mar 1886|page=3 |access-date= 12 May 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= A mandolin craze |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/6925750/mandolin_craze_1895/ |work= The Weekly Wisconsin|location= |date= 2 Mar 1895| page=1 |access-date=12 May 2012 }} </ref> \n\nThe continent was a land of immigrants, including Italian immigrants, some of whom brought their mandolins with them. In spite of the mandolin having arrived in America, it was not in the national consciousness until after 1880 when the Spanish Students arrived on their international performing tour. Afterwards, a \"mandolin craze\" swept the United States, with large numbers of young people taking up the instrument and teachers such as [[Samuel Siegel]] touring the country. The fad died out after World War I, but enough had learned the instrument that it remained. The mandolin found a new surge with the music of [[Bill Monroe]]; the Gibson F-5 mandolin he played, as well as other [[Mandolin#Archtop|archtop instruments]], became the American standard for mandolins. [[Mandolin#Bowlback|Bowlback mandolins]] were displaced. The instrument has been taken up in blues, bluegrass, jug-band music, country, rock, punk, Celtic and other genres of music. While not as popular as the guitar, it is widespread across the country.\n\n== Venezuela ==\nAs in Brazil, the mandolin has played an important role in the [[Music of Venezuela]]. It has enjoyed a privileged position as the main melodic instrument in several different regions of the country. Specifically, the eastern states of Sucre, Nueva Esparta, Anzoategui and Monagas have made the mandolin the main instrument in their versions of [[Joropo]] as well as [[Punto (Venezuela)|Puntos]], [[Jota (music)|Jotas]], [[Polo]]s, Fulias, [[Merengue music|Merengues]] and [[Malague\u00f1a (genre)|Malague\u00f1as]]. Also, in the west of the country the sound of the mandolin is intrinsically associated with the regional genres of the Venezuelan Andes: Bambucos, Pasillos, Pasodobles, and Waltzes. In the western city of Maracaibo the Mandolin has been played in Decimas, Danzas and Contradanzas Zulianas; in the capital, [[Caracas]], the Merengue Rucaneao, Pasodobles and Waltzes have also been played with mandolin for almost a century. Today, Venezuelan mandolists include an important group of virtuoso players and ensembles such as Alberto Valderrama, Jesus Rengel, Ricardo Sandoval, Saul Vera, and Cristobal Soto.\n\n== Vietnam ==\n[[File:Ph\u00f2ng tr\u01b0ng b\u00e0y ngh\u1ec7 thu\u1eadt c\u1ea3i l\u01b0\u01a1ng 1496655927699.jpg|right|thumb|Three musical instruments with scalloped necks, guitar, mandolin, and a possible hybrid of the two.<ref name=Vietnameseinstruments>{{cite web |url=http://www.ddth.com/showthread.php/106779-T%C3%ACm-hi%E1%BB%83u-c%C3%A1c-lo%E1%BA%A1i-nh%E1%BA%A1c-c%E1%BB%A5-!!!?s=6a3493baf1d9d961a426bc6b8d2031d4 |title= Ch\u1ee7 \u0111\u1ec1: T\u00ecm hi\u1ec3u c\u00e1c lo\u1ea1i nh\u1ea1c c\u1ee5 !!! |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=December 11, 2006 |website=ddth.com |publisher= |access-date=June 4, 2017 |quote=[translation:] around 1938-1939 a new style was born, the guitar was smaller than the guitar but bigger than the mandolin and they gave it a name called \"guitar mandarin\".}}</ref>]]\n\nThe French ruled Vietnam completely by 1884 and set up a system of modern education. The population was exposed to French culture and music, which included the mandolin. The influence of French culture was strong enough to affect Vietnamese music. They began writing lyrics to French pop music in Vietnamese and teaching themselves other western instruments including mandolin, guitar, Hawaiian guitar and banjo.<ref name=Catholic>{{cite web |url=http://thingsasian.com/story/reform-and-tradition-early-vietnamese-popular-song |title= Reform and Tradition in Early Vietnamese Popular Song|last= Gibbs|first= James|date=2 March 2017 |website= thingsasian.com|publisher= |access-date=2 June 2017 |quote=}}</ref> Through the Catholics and later the conservatories, European classical music and instruments were taught, including piano and bowed instruments.<ref name=Catholic/>\n\nThe mandolin and guitar were played in both classical music and pop music. Although used in popular music, both instruments were also taught in the Saigon National Conservatory (now the [[Conservatory of Ho Chi Minh City]]).<ref name=vietconservatory>{{cite news|last= Tung|first= Son|date= 24 February 2012|title= Farewell to the Mandolin|url= http://english.thesaigontimes.vn/22034/Farewell-To-The-Mandolin.html|location= Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam|access-date= 1 June 2017|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170604160625/http://english.thesaigontimes.vn/22034/Farewell-To-The-Mandolin.html|archive-date= 2017-06-04|url-status= dead}}</ref> However, the mandolin has disappeared from the conservatory where it had been taught, apparently dropped from the curriculum.<ref name=vietconservatory/> Instead of Guitar-Mandolin department, the school lists Guitar-Accordion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hcmcons.vn/gioi-thieu/cac-khoa/guitar-accordeon/gioi-thieu |title= Guitar - Accordeon, Gi\u1edbi thi\u1ec7u |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= hcmcons.vn |publisher= |access-date=1 June 2017 |quote=Th\u00e0nh l\u1eadp t\u1eeb n\u0103m 1956, Khoa g\u1ed3m hai b\u1ed9 m\u00f4n: Guitare v\u00e0 Mandoline. Sau n\u0103m 1975, Khoa c\u00f3 th\u00eam b\u1ed9 m\u00f4n Accord\u00e9on v\u00e0 sau \u0111\u00f3 l\u00e0 Orgue \u0111i\u1ec7n t\u1eed.  [translation: Founded in 1956, the Faculty consists of two departments: Guitare and Mandoline. After 1975, Khoa added Accordion and later Electronic Organ.]}}</ref>\n\nThough probably never a dominant instrument, the mandolin was learned by enough people to have a presence among the settlers who left Vietnam for the United States, and who continued to play mandolins in their new home. There are still people in Vietnam playing as well, although the cost of a new instrument is prohibitive.<ref name=vietmanodoorch>{{cite web |url= http://thanhnien.vn/van-hoa/ban-nhac-mandolin-dat-bac-lieu-315625.html|title=Ban nh\u1ea1c mandolin \u0111\u1ea5t B\u1ea1c Li\u00eau [Bac Lieu mandolin band] |last=Giang |first=Huong  |date= December 9, 2012|website= |publisher=Thanh Nien |access-date= June 4, 2017 |quote=}}</ref> There is at least one mandolin orchestra still playing, a group of aging players teaching newcomers.<ref name=vietmanodoorch/>\n\nVietnamese luthiers have worked with mandolin design. Mandolins being made in Vietnam today for the international market use the French flatback style. However, some Vietnamese luthiers have added their own innovation, putting sound holes in the mandolins' sides.\n\nThe luthiers also worked with the idea of modifying the mandolin to meet local musical styles, making experimental changes to the necks of violins, guitars and mandolins to suit them to [[Cai luong]] opera music.<ref name=scoop>{{cite web |url= http://tomkhoshiwo.blogspot.com/|title= Cai luong|last= Shiwo |first=Tomkho |date=December 4, 2005 |website=Tomkhoshiwo.blogspot.com|access-date= June 4, 2017|quote=...the cai luong band uses modern musical instruments. Vietnamese artists renovated the Western violin, mandolin and guitar by making concave frets to create new tones and melodies...concave-fret guitar is the main instrument for cai luong and it has become a national instrument of Vietnam}}</ref> In the mid-1930s, they made concave frets, scooping out extra wood between the frets, making the space between them deep and to allow the musicians to bend the notes, and stringing them with four single strings.<ref name=scoop/> Musicians Hai N\u00e9n and Hai Nh\u00e0nh were associated with the instruments, possibly being the first to use them.<ref name=\"ph\u00edm l\u00f5m\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ddth.com/showthread.php/106779-T%C3%ACm-hi%E1%BB%83u-c%C3%A1c-lo%E1%BA%A1i-nh%E1%BA%A1c-c%E1%BB%A5-!!!?s=6a3493baf1d9d961a426bc6b8d2031d4 |title= Ch\u1ee7 \u0111\u1ec1: T\u00ecm hi\u1ec3u c\u00e1c lo\u1ea1i nh\u1ea1c c\u1ee5 !!! |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=December 11, 2006 |website=ddth.com |publisher= |access-date=June 4, 2017 |quote=V\u00e0o kho\u1ea3ng n\u0103m 1934-1935 c\u00e1c \u00f4ng Hai N\u00e9n v\u00e0 Hai Nh\u00e0nh l\u00e0 nh\u1eefng ng\u01b0\u1eddi \u0111\u1ea7u ti\u00ean s\u1eed d\u1ee5ng mandolin ph\u00edm l\u00f5m...Mandolin ph\u00edm l\u00f5m ra \u0111\u1eddi, tuy \u0111\u00e3 gi\u1ea3i quy\u1ebft \u0111\u01b0\u1ee3c v\u1ea5n \u0111\u1ec1 tr\u00ecnh t\u1ea5u nh\u1eefng b\u00e0i b\u1ea3n thu\u1ed9c h\u01a1i Nam, nh\u01b0ng k\u1ef9 thu\u1eadt di\u1ec5n t\u1ea5u \u0111\u00e3 g\u00e2y nhi\u1ec1u kh\u00f3 kh\u0103n cho nh\u1ea1c c\u00f4ng...[translation:Between 1934 and 1935, Hai Nam and Hai Nhanh were the first to use the concave mandolin....Mandolin concave was born, but solved the problem of the composition of the South, but the technique has caused many difficulties for musicians. At first, the rigidity of the mandolin string makes the musicians too painful hands with the fingers, the keyboard is too narrow, hard to hit...] }}</ref> The ''sunken-fret mandolin'' (mandolin ph\u00edm l\u00f5m) did not meet the musical needs as well as the [[Guitar ph\u00edm l\u00f5m|sunken-fret guitar]], because the mandolin's rigidity made it painful to get the same effects from the strings.<ref name=\"ph\u00edm l\u00f5m\"/> Also the mandolin's narrow fretboard made it difficult to hit the notes.<ref name=\"ph\u00edm l\u00f5m\"/> Another reason to move to a bigger instrument was the pitch range of the mandolin, high pitched and not as useful to accompany singing as the instruments that replaced it in the opera.<ref name=\"ph\u00edm l\u00f5m\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Mandolin family instruments}}\n\n[[Category:Mandolin family instruments]]\n[[Category:Mandolinists]]\n", "name_user": "Greyjoy", "label": "safe", "comment": "linkToronto Mandolin OrchestrausingFind link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mandolin_playing_traditions_worldwide"}
{"title_page": "Red Princesses", "text_new": "{{short description|2013 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Red Princesses\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Laura Astorga]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = Laura Astorga\n| starring       = [[Fernando Bola\u00f1os]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|2013|2|11|[[63rd Berlin International Film Festival|Berlin]]|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 90 minutes\n| country        = Costa Rica\n| language       = Spanish\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Red Princesses''''' ({{lang-es|'''Princesas rojas'''}}) is a 2013 Costa Rican [[drama film]] directed by [[Laura Astorga]]. It was selected as the Costa Rican entry for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] at the [[87th Academy Awards]], but was not nominated.<ref name=\"Costa Rica\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nacion.com/ocio/cine/Laura_Astorga-Princesas_Rojas-Costa_Rica-Oscar_0_1442455854.html |title=Costa Rica postula a 'Princesas Rojas' al \u00d3scar 2015 |accessdate=1 October 2014 |work=La Nacion}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Fernando Bola\u00f1os]] as Felipe\n* [[Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9 Callejas]] as Floria\n* [[Valeria Conejo]] as Claudia\n* [[Aura Dinarte]] as Antonia\n* [[Ivette Guier]] as Cora\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of submissions to the 87th Academy Awards for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n* [[List of Costa Rican submissions for the Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|2396870|Red Princesses}}\n\n{{Costa Rican submission for Academy Awards}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Red Princesses}}\n[[Category:2013 films]]\n[[Category:2013 drama films]]\n[[Category:Costa Rican films]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language films]]\n{{CostaRica-film-stub}}\n{{2010s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2013 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Red Princesses\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Laura Astorga]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = Laura Astorga\n| starring       = [[Fernando Bola\u00f1os]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|2013|2|11|[[63rd Berlin International Film Festival|Berlin]]|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 90 minutes\n| country        = Costa Rica\n| language       = Spanish\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Red Princesses''''' ({{lang-es|'''Princesas rojas'''}}) is a 2013 Costa Rican [[drama film]] directed by [[Laura Astorga]]. It was selected as the Costa Rican entry for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] at the [[87th Academy Awards]], but was not nominated.<ref name=\"Costa Rica\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nacion.com/ocio/cine/Laura_Astorga-Princesas_Rojas-Costa_Rica-Oscar_0_1442455854.html |title=Costa Rica postula a 'Princesas Rojas' al \u00d3scar 2015 |accessdate=1 October 2014 |work=La Nacion}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Fernando Bola\u00f1os]] as Felipe\n* [[Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9 Callejas]] as Floria\n* [[Valeria Conejo]] as Claudia\n* [[Aura Dinarte]] as Antonia\n* [[Ivette Guier]] as Cora\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of submissions to the 87th Academy Awards for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n* [[List of Costa Rican submissions for the Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|2396870|Red Princesses}}\n\n{{Costa Rican submission for Academy Awards}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Red Princesses}}\n[[Category:2013 films]]\n[[Category:2013 drama films]]\n[[Category:Costa Rican films]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language films]]\n{{CostaRica-film-stub}}\n{{2010s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Princesses"}
{"title_page": "Seattle Preparatory School", "text_new": "{{ref improve|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox school\n | name                    = Seattle Preparatory School\n | logo                    = Sprepseal.jpg\n | motto                   = ''Virtus in Arduis''\n | motto_translation       = Virtue in Hard Work\n | streetaddress           = 2400 11th Avenue East\n | city                    = [[Seattle]]\n | county                  = ([[King County, Washington|King County]])\n | state                   = [[Washington (state)|Washington]]\n | zipcode                 = 98102\n | country                 = USA\n | coordinates             = {{Coord|47.641387|N|122.317531|W|region:US-WA_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n | type                    = [[Private school|Private]]\n | religion                = [[Roman Catholic]]<br>[[Jesuit]]\n | patron                  = \n | established             = {{Start date and age|1891}}\n | ceeb                    = 481160<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vanderbilt.edu/Admissions/highschoolcode.html |title=High School Code Lookup|publisher=[[Vanderbilt University]] |accessdate=2009-09-27 }}</ref>\n | chairperson             = \n | principal               = Erin Luby\n | faculty                 = 125<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seaprep.org/aboutprep/directory |title=High School Faculty Number|publisher=[[Seattle Preparatory School]] |accessdate=2020-02-21 }}</ref>  \n | teaching_staff          = \n | grades                  = [[Ninth grade|9]]\u2013[[Twelfth grade|12]]\n | gender                  = [[Coeducational]]\n | grade9                  = \n | grade10                 = \n | grade11                 = \n | grade12                 = \n | other                   = \n | avg_class_size          = 13\n | ratio                   = 11:1\n | system                  = \n | slogan                  = \n | song                    = \n | fightsong               = \"Hail to thee our fighting Panthers\"\n | athletics               = \n | conference              = Metro AAA League\n | sports                  = \n | mascot                  = [[Black panther|Panther]]\n | nickname                = Seattle Prep\n | team_name               = Panthers\n | accreditation           = [[Northwest Accreditation Commission]] <ref name=\"Northwest Accreditation Commission\">{{cite web|url=http://www.advanc-ed.org/oasis2/u/par/accreditation/summary?institutionId=53322|title=Northwest Accreditation Commission|accessdate=2009-07-29|author=NWAC}}</ref>\n | ranking                 = \n | national_ranking        = \n | SAT                     = \n | ACT                     = \n | publication             = Panther Tracks Magazine\n | newspaper               = ''The Seattle Prep Panther''\n | picture                 = Image:SeattlePrep.png\n | picture_caption         = McDonnell Hall with PACCAR Commons\n | affiliation             = \n | president               = Kent Hickey\n | tuition                 = $17,900\n | campus type             = Urban\n | mascot image            = \n | colors                  = blue and white {{color box|blue}}{{color box|white}}\n | rivals                  = [[Bishop Blanchet]] - [[Holy Names Academy]] - [[O'Dea High School]]\n | enrollment              = 720\n | enrollment_as_of        = \n | homepage                = [http://www.seaprep.org seaprep.org]\n}}\n\n'''Seattle Preparatory School''', popularly known as '''Seattle Prep,''' is a private, [[Jesuit]] [[high school]] located on [[Capitol Hill (Seattle)|Capitol Hill]] in [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]].\n\n==Curriculum==\nStudents generally pursue a traditional four-year course of study at Seattle Prep and then pursue other arrangements (entrance into a four-year college, or a two-year college).{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nA wide variety of extracurricular activities are offered at Seattle Prep including Film Club, Chess Team, Mock Trial, Dance Team (also known as Pulse), Yearbook, Newspaper, ASB, One Voice, Global Justice Coalition, National Honors Society, and Drama.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seaprep.org/studentlife/activities|title=Student Activities and Clubs - Seattle Preparatory School|website=www.seaprep.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nAdmissions are based on grades, extracurricular activities, an entrance exam, reference letters, and essays, among other criteria.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seaprep.org/admissions/how-to-apply|title=How to Apply - Seattle Preparatory School|website=www.seaprep.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n\n==Facts and figures==\nFacts and figures (as of 2008):\n\n* [[Education|Enrollment]]: 667                                                           \n* [[Faculty (university)|Faculty]]: 125\n* Faculty with advanced degrees: 90%\n* Student/Teacher Ratio: 9.5:1\n* Average Class Size: 13\n* Percentage of College-Bound Graduates: 99%\n* [[Tuition]]: $21,950 + $600 Application fee<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seaprep.org/admissions/tuition|title=Tuition & Tuition Assistance Scholarships - Seattle Preparatory School|website=www.seaprep.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n* Library Volumes: 20,000+\n* Tuition Assistance: 1,000,000\n{{Nothing}}\n\n==Magis Christian Service==\nSeattle Prep has a 4-year requirement of various community service. The four year Magis Christian Service Program at Seattle Prep exposes students to many different forms of service including service to family (freshman), to school (sophomore), to the poor and marginalized (junior), and to leadership for justice (senior).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seaprep.org/faithandservice/magisservice|title=Magis Christian Service Program - Seattle Preparatory School|website=www.seaprep.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n==Physical structure==\n[[File:Seaprep1.png|thumb|250px|right|McHugh Gymnasium & St. Ignatius Hall]]\nIn the 1950s, McDonnell Hall was added to the existing Adelphia Hall, and in the 1960s, Peyton Hall was added across the parking lot from McDonnell and Adelphia Halls. The McHugh Gymnasium was built in front of Adelphia Hall and opened in 1983, a result of the school's first major fundraising campaign. Funds from this campaign were used to remodel the third floor of Adelphia Hall for improved science facilities. During this time the library, which then became known as Loyola Library, was moved to Peyton Hall.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nThere were several major additions to Seattle Prep in the late 1990s. A new underground parking garage was built to replace the old parking lot, which was replaced by a grass [[Quadrangle (architecture)|quad]]. In addition, St. Ignatius Hall was erected across from Peyton and McDonnell Halls.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n[[File:Chapel10.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Thomas Healy SJ Theater]]\n\nIn 2007, the PACCAR Commons (Donated by the Pigott family) were completed, including new office space with reception desks and also a sick room. Also construction was completed on the Thomas Healy, S.J., Theater and Classrooms.  This was the first major renovation since the addition of St. Ignatius Hall.  The  theater, which also accommodates school Masses, features an orchestra pit with hydraulics moving it up and down for various uses, including the transportation of heavy equipment.  The workout rooms and locker rooms were also altered in this remodel.  The space below the theater is used for arts classes, a [[sacristy]] (to be used for liturgies and Masses), and weight/workout rooms. In 2008, sections of pathway around the campus plaza were redone and electronic doors were installed on several major entrances.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n==Notable alumni==\n<!--ENTRIES ON THIS LIST SHOULD EITHER HAVE AN ACCOMPANYING EXISTING ARTICLE LINK WHICH VERIFIES THEY ARE AN ALUMNUS, OR RELIABLE SOURCES AS FOOTNOTES AGAINST THE NAME.-->\n* [[Bob Bellinger]], American football player\n* [[Bryce Fisher]], former NFL defensive lineman (1999\u20132008) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/players/brycefisher/profile?id=FIS192130 |title=Bryce Fisher |publisher=NFL.com |date=1977-12-05 |accessdate=2010-06-06}}</ref>\n* [[Tom Gorman (tennis)|Tom Gorman]], former professional tennis player {{Citation needed|date=May 2009}}\n* [[Spencer Hawes]], professional NBA basketball player, [[Milwaukee Bucks]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/playerfile/spencer_hawes/ |title=Spencer Hawes Info Page |publisher=NBA.com |date= |accessdate=2010-06-06}}</ref>\n* [[Don Kardong]], Olympic marathon runner {{Citation needed|date=May 2009}}\n* [[Amanda Knox]], convicted of murdering a fellow student in Italy, conviction later overturned<ref>{{cite book |last=Follain |first=J. |title=Death in Perugia: The Definitive Account of the Meredith Kercher Case from Her Murder to the Acquittal of Raffaele Sollecito and Amanda Knox |publisher=St. Martin's True Crime |date=2011 |isbn=978-0-340-99309-5 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/deathinperugia0002foll/page/13 13\u201315] |url=https://archive.org/details/deathinperugia0002foll/page/13 }}</ref>\n* [[Joe Lombardi]], NFL offensive coordinator, [[Detroit Lions]] <ref name=aggnsptr>{{cite news |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1989-10-29/sports/8901270196_1_joe-lombardi-special-treatment-vince-lombardi |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |agency=(Seattle Times) |last=Peoples |first=John |title=Lombardi's grandson gets no special treatment |date=October 29, 1989 |accessdate=September 22, 2014}}</ref><ref name=jlbonleg>{{cite web |url=http://www.packersnews.com/story/sports/columnists/dougherty/2014/09/18/joe-lombardi-building-legacy/15868371/ |publisher=Packer News |title=Joe Lombardi building own NFL legacy |last=Dougherty |first=Pete |agency=Press-Gazette Media |date=September 18, 2014 |accessdate=September 22, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Mike McGavick]], former CEO of [[Safeco]] and former [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidate for the [[United States Senate]] {{Citation needed|reason=Previous footnote was a circular reference to WP using answers.com|date=July 2010}}\n* [[John McKay (attorney)|John McKay]], former US Attorney for the Western District Of Washington <ref>[http://www.law.seattleu.edu/x2991.xml McKay]</ref>  \n* [[Greg Nickels]], former mayor of [[Seattle]] (2002\u20132010) <ref name=\"Greg Nickels\">{{cite web|url=http://www.seattle.gov/mayor/about/bio.htm|title=ABOUT MAYOR GREGORY J. NICKELS|publisher=City of Seattle|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629094308/http://www.seattle.gov/mayor/about/bio.htm|archivedate=June 29, 2011 |accessdate=2009-05-27}}</ref>\n* [[John Spellman]], former governor of Washington (1981\u20131985) <ref>[http://www.nndb.com/people/459/000122093/ Spellman]</ref> \n* [[Martell Webster]], professional NBA basketball player, [[Washington Wizards]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/playerfile/martell_webster|title=Martell Webster Info Page|publisher=NBA.com|accessdate=2010-06-06}}</ref>\n<!--ENTRIES ON THIS LIST MUST HAVE AN ACCOMPANYING EXISTING ARTICLE-->\n\n==Athletics and activities==\n{{unsourced section|date=May 2018}}\nSeattle Prep has won numerous league and state titles in many different men's and women's sports. As of 2010, by size Prep is a high-end 1A class school, but plays up in 3A classification.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nThe girls' soccer team are back-to-back state champions (2011 and 2012) and have four other appearances in the state championship game. The girls basketball team qualified for State 14 years in a row, winning it all in 2002.\nPrep's volleyball team won three straight state titles from 2001\u201303, and returned to the champions circle in 2010.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nThe boys' basketball team won state titles in 2000 and 2006 and narrowly missed another title in 2012 losing in the state championship game. The team has qualified for State 6 of the last 7 seasons. Prep boys' basketball has a rich tradition of players who have gone on to star in college and the NBA.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nPrep boy's [[cross country running|cross country]] team won the title in 1966 (led by future 4th-place finisher in the Montreal Olympics marathon [[Don Kardong]]), 1972, and 2000. Prep's boy's cross country teams have finished as one of the top five 3A teams every year but one from 1996-2013. During that span, Prep never placed lower than second in the Metro League. In 2006, Prep won its first women's Metro League team title.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nThe Mock Trial program boasts one national championship and twelve state titles in the last fourteen years (winning State in 2003, 2004, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, and 2016). Prep has placed in the top-10 at the [[National High School Mock Trial Championship]] eight times during that span. Its 3rd-place finish in 2009 was the best in program history, until the program won the national title in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kingcounty.gov/council/news/2014/June/mocktrial.aspx|title=County Council recognizes Seattle Prep\u2019s Mock Trial Champions|last=|first=|date=June 16, 2014|website=King county.gov|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe Prep Chess Team has played in the Washington High School State Team Championship in each of the past 17 years. Its highest finishes were 2nd (2002), 3rd (2009), 5th (2005 and 2010), and 6th (1999). In 1999, they also won the Metro Championship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seaprep.org/studentlife/activities/chessteam|title=Chess Team - Seattle Preparatory School|website=www.seaprep.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Jesuit Secondary Education Association}}\n{{Schools in the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Seattle}}\n{{WIAA Sea-King District 2|A|3A}}\n\n[[Category:Catholic secondary schools in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Jesuit high schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Schools in Seattle]]\n[[Category:High schools in King County, Washington]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1891]]\n[[Category:Schools accredited by the Northwest Accreditation Commission]]\n[[Category:High schools within the Archdiocese of Seattle]]\n[[Category:1891 establishments in Washington (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{ref improve|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox school\n | name                    = Seattle Preparatory School\n | logo                    = Sprepseal.jpg\n | motto                   = ''Virtus in Arduis''\n | motto_translation       = Virtue in Hard Work\n | streetaddress           = 2400 11th Avenue East\n | city                    = [[Seattle]]\n | county                  = ([[King County, Washington|King County]])\n | state                   = [[Washington (state)|Washington]]\n | zipcode                 = 98102\n | country                 = USA\n | coordinates             = {{Coord|47.641387|N|122.317531|W|region:US-WA_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n | type                    = [[Private school|Private]]\n | religion                = [[Roman Catholic]]<br>[[Jesuit]]\n | patron                  = \n | established             = {{Start date and age|1891}}\n | ceeb                    = 481160<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vanderbilt.edu/Admissions/highschoolcode.html |title=High School Code Lookup|publisher=[[Vanderbilt University]] |accessdate=2009-09-27 }}</ref>\n | chairperson             = \n | principal               = Erin Luby\n | faculty                 = 125<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seaprep.org/aboutprep/directory |title=High School Faculty Number|publisher=[[Seattle Preparatory School]] |accessdate=2020-02-21 }}</ref>  \n | teaching_staff          = \n | grades                  = [[Ninth grade|9]]\u2013[[Twelfth grade|12]]\n | gender                  = [[Coeducational]]\n | grade9                  = \n | grade10                 = \n | g